{"title_page": "Robert F. Kennedy Jr.", "text_new": "{{short description|American anti-vaccine pseudoscientific activist}}\n{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Robert F. Kennedy Jr.\n|image       = Robert F. Kennedy Jr. by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n|caption     = Kennedy in 2017\n|party       = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]]\n|birth_name  = Robert Francis Kennedy Jr.\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1954|1|17}}\n|birth_place = [[Washington, D.C.]], U.S.\n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|spouse      = {{marriage|Emily Black|1982|1994|reason=divorce}}<br/>{{marriage|[[Mary Richardson Kennedy|Mary Richardson]]|1994|2012|reason=died}}<br/>{{marriage|[[Cheryl Hines]]|2014}}\n|children    = 6 (including [[Kyra Kennedy]])\n|relatives = ''See [[Kennedy family]]''\n|education  = [[Harvard College|Harvard University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br/>[[London School of Economics]]<br/>[[University of Virginia School of Law|University of Virginia]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])<br/>[[Pace University School of Law|Pace University]] ([[Master of Laws|LLM]])\n|parents     = [[Robert F. Kennedy]]<br/>[[Ethel Kennedy|Ethel Skakel]]\n}}\n\n'''Robert Francis Kennedy Jr.''' (born January 17, 1954) is an American environmental attorney, author, and opponent of vaccination. Kennedy is a son of [[Robert F. Kennedy]] and nephew of former president [[John F. Kennedy]]. He is the president of the board of [[Waterkeeper Alliance]], a non-profit environmental group that he helped found in 1999.\n\nFrom 1986 until 2017, Kennedy was a senior attorney for the [[Natural Resources Defense Council|Natural Resources Defense Council (NRDC)]], a non-profit environmental organization. From 1984 until 2017, he was a board member and chief prosecuting attorney for [[Hudson Valley|Hudson]] [[Riverkeeper]].<ref>Agee, J'nelle (March 18, 2017) \"[http://spectrumlocalnews.com/nys/hudson-valley/news/2017/03/17/robert-kennedy-jr-resigns-from-riverkeeper Robert F. Kennedy, Jr. Resigns From Riverkeeper]\". ''Spectrum News'' {{Webarchive |url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171004135637/http://spectrumlocalnews.com/nys/hudson-valley/news/2017/03/17/robert-kennedy-jr-resigns-from-riverkeeper |date=October 4, 2017 }}</ref> For over thirty years, Kennedy has been an adjunct professor of [[Environmental law]] at [[Pace University School of Law]]. Until August 2017, he also held the post as supervising attorney and co-director of Pace Law School's Environmental Litigation Clinic, which he founded in 1987.<ref>Smith, Steve (April 29, 2015). \"[http://news.unl.edu/newsrooms/today/article/rfk-jr-to-address-college-of-law-graduates RFK Jr. to address College of Law graduates]\". ''Nebraska Today''. {{Webarchive |url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171004085140/http://news.unl.edu/newsrooms/today/article/rfk-jr-to-address-college-of-law-graduates |date= October 4, 2017 }}</ref>  He is currently professor [[emeritus]] at Pace.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://law.pace.edu/faculty/robert-f-kennedy-jr+-|title = Faculty |website= Pace Law School|access-date=November 20, 2017|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171201033134/http://law.pace.edu/faculty/robert-f-kennedy-jr+-|archive-date=December 1, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nKennedy co-hosts ''[[Ring of Fire (radio program)|Ring of Fire]]'', a nationally syndicated American radio program, and has written or edited ten books, including two [[The New York Times Best Seller list|''New York Times'' bestsellers]].\n\nHe is a prominent [[Vaccine hesitancy|anti-vaccine]] activist and believes in [[pseudoscience|pseudoscientific]] speculation of a link between [[vaccines and autism]].<ref>{{Cite web| url = https://arstechnica.com/science/2019/07/anti-vaxxers-lose-again-ny-judge-upholds-ban-on-religious-exemptions |title =Prominent anti-vaxxers lose New York court case over religious exemptions|last=Mole|first=Beth |date= 2019-07-12| website= Ars Technica | access-date=2019-11-15 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20191115030802/https://arstechnica.com/science/2019/07/anti-vaxxers-lose-again-ny-judge-upholds-ban-on-religious-exemptions |archive-date= November 15, 2019| url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url = https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/13/us/california-vaccine-bill.html |title = Here Is What Jessica Biel Opposes in California's Vaccine Bill | last = Hassan |first =Adeel|date= 2019-06-13|work=The New York Times |access-date= 2019-11-15| issn= 0362-4331|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20191114205822/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/13/us/california-vaccine-bill.html|archive-date=November 14, 2019| url-status =live}}</ref> Kennedy has denied such characterization.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sciencemag.org/news/2017/01/exclusive-qa-robert-f-kennedy-jr-trumps-proposed-vaccine-commission |title=Exclusive Q&A: Robert F. Kennedy Jr. on Trump's proposed vaccine commission|last=Wadman |first = Meredith|date= 2017-01-10|website=Science|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dispatch.com/opinion/20190627/letter-stronger-testing-required-to-make-vaccines-safe|title= Stronger testing required to make vaccines safe|last=Kennedy Jr.|first=Robert F.|date=2019-06-27|website=The Columbus Dispatch|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nKennedy was born in [[Washington, D.C.]], on January 17, 1954. He is the third of eleven children of Senator and Attorney General [[Robert F. Kennedy]] and [[Ethel Kennedy]].\n\nAdditionally, he is a nephew of [[Joseph P. Kennedy Jr.]], President [[John F. Kennedy]], and Senator [[Ted Kennedy]]. His aunt [[Eunice Kennedy Shriver]] founded [[Special Olympics]], and another aunt, [[Jean Kennedy Smith]], is a former U.S. Ambassador to Ireland.<ref>{{Cite newspaper | url=https://articles.latimes.com/1995-11-26/opinion/op-7471_1_jean-kennedy-smith| title=Los Angeles Times Interview : Jean Kennedy Smith : This Kennedy Returned to Ireland| journal=Los Angeles Times| date=1995-11-26| last1=Tuohy| first1=William| access-date=October 14, 2017 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180405092429/http://articles.latimes.com/1995-11-26/opinion/op-7471_1_jean-kennedy-smith| archive-date=April 5, 2018| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nKennedy grew up at his family's homes in [[McLean, Virginia]], and [[Cape Cod, Massachusetts]].<ref>{{cite book |title =American Values: Lessons I Learned from My Family|first=Robert F. |last=Kennedy Jr. |pages=3\u20138|year=2018|isbn=978-0062845917 |publisher= HarperLuxe}}</ref> He was 9 years old in 1963 when his uncle, President John F. Kennedy, [[Assassination of John F. Kennedy|was assassinated]], and 14 years old in 1968 when his [[Assassination of Robert F. Kennedy|father was assassinated]] while running for president in the [[Democratic Party presidential primaries, 1968|1968 Democratic presidential primaries]].\n\nKennedy learned of his father's shooting when he was at [[Georgetown Preparatory School]], a Jesuit boarding school in North Bethesda, Maryland.<ref>\"Oprah Talks to Bobby Kennedy Jr.\". February 2007. ''O, The Oprah Magazine''</ref> A few hours later, he flew to Los Angeles on vice-president [[Hubert Humphrey|Hubert Humphrey's plane]], along with his elder sister [[Kathleen Kennedy Townsend|Kathleen]] and elder brother [[Joseph P. Kennedy II|Joseph]], and was with his father when he died. Kennedy was a pallbearer in his father's funeral, where he spoke and read excerpts from his father's speeches at the Mass commemorating his death at [[Arlington National Cemetery]].<ref>Storrin, Matt. (June 7, 1969). \"[https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/boston/doc/506180659.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Jun%2007,%201969&author=&pub=Boston%20Globe%20(1960-1979)&edition=&startpage=&desc=Folk%20Mass%20Honors%20RFK Folk Mass Honors RFK]\". ''Boston Globe''.   {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170918202156/https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/boston/doc/506180659.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Jun%2007,%201969&author=&pub=Boston%20Globe%20(1960-1979)&edition=&startpage=&desc=Folk%20Mass%20Honors%20RFK |date =September 18, 2017 }}</ref><ref>Special to The New York Times (June 7, 1970) \"[https://www.nytimes.com/1970/06/07/archives/robert-kennedys-words-sung-in-mass-marking-assassination.html Robert Kennedy's Words Sung In Mass Marking Assassination]\". ''New York Times''. {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171006113141/http://www.nytimes.com/1970/06/07/archives/robert-kennedys-words-sung-in-mass-marking-assassination.html |date=October 6, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nAfter obtaining his high school diploma from the Palfrey Street School in [[Massachusetts]],<ref>{{cite book|title=RFK Jr.: Robert F. Kennedy Jr. and the Dark Side of the Dream|first=Jerry |last=Oppenheimer|pages=129\u2013147|year=2015|isbn=978-1250096661|publisher=St. Martin's Griffin}}</ref> Kennedy continued his education at [[Harvard University|Harvard]] and the [[London School of Economics]], graduating from [[Harvard College]] in 1976 with a Bachelor of Arts in American History and Literature. He went on to earn a [[Juris Doctor]] from the [[University of Virginia School of Law|University of Virginia]] and a [[Master of Laws]] from [[Pace University School of Law|Pace University]].<ref>[http://www.backbonecampaign.org/cabinet/nominee.cfm?ID=62 The Backbone Cabinet \u2013 A Progressive Cabinet Roster] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929042337/http://www.backbonecampaign.org/cabinet/nominee.cfm?ID=62 |date=September 29, 2007 }}, backbonecampaign.org</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\nIn 1983, Kennedy was an Assistant District Attorney in Manhattan. In 1984, Kennedy joined Riverkeeper as an investigator, and was promoted to senior prosecuting attorney<ref name=\"auto4\">Cronin, John; Kennedy Jr., Robert F. (1997). ''The Riverkeepers: Two Activists Fight to Reclaim Our Environment as a Basic Human Right''. New York: Scribner. p. 304. {{ISBN|0684839083}}.</ref>  when he was admitted to the New York bar in 1985.<ref>Dunlap, David W. and Perlez, Jane (June 4, 1985). \"[https://www.nytimes.com/1985/06/04/nyregion/new-york-day-by-day-a-quiet-victory-for-robert-f-kennedy-jr.html A Quiet Victory For Robert F. Kennedy Jr]\". ''The New York Times''.{{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171007070349/http://www.nytimes.com/1985/06/04/nyregion/new-york-day-by-day-a-quiet-victory-for-robert-f-kennedy-jr.html |date=October 7, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nKennedy is an environmental law specialist and partner in the law firms of Morgan & Morgan PA and of Kennedy & Madonna, LLP,<ref>Slansky, Dov (April 01, 2016). \"Robert F. Kennedy, Jr. and Kevin J. Madonna Join Morgan & Morgan\". PRWEB.</ref> and is an advocate for environmental justice.\n\nThrough litigation, lobbying, teaching, and public campaigns and activism, Kennedy has advocated for the protection of waterways, indigenous rights, and renewable energy.<ref>Little, Amanda (July 14, 2004). \"An interview with Robert F. Kennedy Jr., environmental advocate and Bush basher\". Grist.org. http://grist.org/article/griscom-kennedy/ {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171007120150/http://grist.org/article/griscom-kennedy/ |date=October 7, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2018 the National Trial Lawyers Association awarded Kennedy and his trial team Trial Team of the Year for their work winning a $289 million jury verdict in Dewayne \"Lee\" Johnson v Monsanto.<ref name=\"Millican, Scott\">{{cite web|url=https://trofire.com/2019/03/04/ring-of-fires-rfk-jr-wins-award-for-monsanto-trial/|title=Ring of Fire's RFK Jr. Wins Award for Monsanto Trial|author=Millican, Scott|date=March 4, 2019|website =trofire.com|accessdate=March 5, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190305115249/https://trofire.com/2019/03/04/ring-of-fires-rfk-jr-wins-award-for-monsanto-trial |archive-date=March 5, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Riverkeeper===\nKennedy litigated and supervised environmental enforcement lawsuits on the east coast estuaries on behalf of Hudson Riverkeeper and the [[Soundkeeper|Long Island Soundkeeper]],<ref>\"Our core mission: Environmental enforcement\". 2016. ''Riverkeeper Journal''.</ref> where he was also a board member. Long Island Soundkeeper brought numerous lawsuits against cities and industries along the Connecticut and New York coastlines.<ref>Gordon, Maggie (April 2, 2014). \"[https://www.stamfordadvocate.com/news/article/Soundkeeper-sues-state-in-Stamford-boatyard-battle-5371462.php Soundkeeper sues state in Stamford boatyard battle]\". ''Stamford Advocate''.</ref>  In 1986, Kennedy won a landmark case against Remington Arms Trap and Skeet Gun Club in [[Stratford, Connecticut]], that ended the practice of shooting lead shot into Long Island Sound.<ref>777 F. Supp. 173 (1981) ''Connecticut Coastal Fisherman's Association v. Remington Arms Company, Inc. and E.I. Dupont DeNemours and Company''. Civ. No. B-87-250 (EBB). United States District Court, D. Connecticut. September 11, 1991. Justia US Law.</ref>  Kennedy also filed federal lawsuits to close the Pelham Bay landfill and the New York Athletic clubs, arguing that those facilities were interfering with public use of Long Island Sound.<ref>Venezia, Todd (July 5, 2005). \"Bx. Dump Poisoned, Killed Kids \u2013 Now City Must Pay: Residents\". New York Post.</ref>  On the Hudson, Kennedy brought a series of lawsuits against municipalities, including New York City, to properly treat sewage, and against industries, including, [[Consolidated Edison]], [[General Electric]] and [[Exxon]], to stop discharging pollution and to clean up legacy contamination.<ref>Navasky, Bruno (August 11, 2016). \"[https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2016/08/robert-f-kennedy-jr-on-the-environment-election-and-donald-trump Robert F. Kennedy Jr. On The Environment, The Election, And A 'Dangerous' Donald Trump]\". ''Vanity Fair''.</ref>\n\nIn 1995, Kennedy advocated for repeal of the anti-environmental legislation during the 104th Congress.<ref name=\"auto\">Werth, Barry (May 2, 2004). \"[https://www.outsideonline.com/1886331/somewhere-down-crazy-river Somewhere Down the Crazy River]\". ''Outside''.</ref> In 1997, Kennedy worked with John Cronin to write ''The Riverkeepers'', a history of the early Riverkeepers and a primer for the Waterkeeper movement.<ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n\nDrawing on his experience investigating and prosecuting polluters on behalf of the Waterkeepers, Kennedy has written extensively about environmental law enforcement.<ref name=\"watershed\">{{cite news |last1 =Worth |first1=Robert |title= Watershed Warrior |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2001/07/01/nyregion/watershed-warrior.html |accessdate=13 January 2020 |work= New York Times |date=1 July 2001}}</ref>\n\n===Pace Environmental Litigation Clinic===\nIn 1987, Kennedy founded the Environmental Litigation Clinic at Pace University School of Law, where for three decades he was the clinic's supervising attorney and co-director, and as Clinical Professor of Law.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.law.pace.edu/pace-environmental-litigation-clinic|title=Pace Environmental Litigation Clinic - Pace Law School|author=|date=|website=www.law.pace.edu|accessdate=October 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171013103626/http://www.law.pace.edu/pace-environmental-litigation-clinic|archive-date=October 13, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>  Kennedy obtained a special order from the New York State Court of Appeals that permitted his 10 clinic students\u2013second- and third-year law students\u2013to practice law and to try cases against Hudson River polluters in state and federal court, under the supervision of Kennedy and his co-director, Professor Karl Coplan. The clinic's full-time clients are Riverkeeper and Long Island Soundkeeper.<ref name=\"oregon\">Kennedy Jr., Robert F., Solow, Steven P. (1993). \"Environmental Litigation as Clinical Education: A Case Study\". ''University of Oregon Journal of Environmental Law and Litigation'' Volume 8</ref>\n\nThe clinic has prosecuted numerous governments and companies for polluting Long Island Sound and the Hudson River and its tributaries.<ref>\"A conversation with the authors of 'The Riverkeepers: Two Activists Fight to Reclaim Our Environment as a Basic Human Right'\". November 10, 1997. Charlie Rose.</ref>  The clinic argued cases to expand citizen access to the shoreline, and won hundreds of settlements for the Hudson Riverkeeper.<ref>Cronin, John and Kennedy Jr., Robert F. (July 26, 1997). \"It's Our River \u2013 Let Us Get to It\". The New York Times</ref>  Kennedy and his students also sued dozens of municipal waste-water treatment plants to force compliance with the [[Clean Water Act]].<ref name=\"oregon\"/> In 2010, a Pace lawsuit forced [[ExxonMobil]] to clean up tens of millions of gallons of oil from legacy refinery spills in Newtown Creek in Brooklyn, New York.<ref>Brown, Kim (July 8, 2004). \"ExxonMobil Sued Over 55-Acre Oil Spill In Newtown Creek\". ''Queens Chronicle''.</ref>\n\nOn April 11, 2001, ''[[Men's Journal]]'' recognized Kennedy with its \"Heroes\" Award for his creation of the Pace Environmental Litigation Clinic.<ref>Kaydo, Chad (April 13, 2001). \"A Manly Awards Party for ''[[Men's Journal]]''\". BizBash.</ref>  Kennedy and his Pace Environmental Litigation Clinic received other awards for successful legal work cleaning up the environment.<ref>Pace Environmental Litigation Clinic. \"Clinic Awards\". Pace Law.</ref>  The Pace Clinic became a model for similar environmental law clinics throughout the country including Rutgers,<ref>Rutgers School of Law Environmental Law Clinic. \"About this Organization\". Justia Lawyers.</ref>  Golden Gate, UCLA,<ref>Environmental Law Courses and Clinics. UCLA Law.</ref>  Widener,<ref>Environmental Law Clinic. Widener Environmental Law Center. Widener Law.</ref> and Boalt Hall at Berkeley.<ref>Environmental Law Clinic. Berkeley Law.</ref>\n\n===Waterkeepers Alliance===\nIn June 1999, as Riverkeeper's success on the Hudson began inspiring the creation of Waterkeepers across North America, Kennedy and a few dozen Riverkeepers gathered in Southampton, Long Island, to found the Waterkeeper Alliance, which is now the umbrella group for the 344 licensed Waterkeeper programs<ref>Gallay, Paul. May 3, 2018. \u201cChina enlists local groups in environmental enforcement push\u201c. Waterkeeper.org.</ref> located in 44 countries.<ref>Yaggi, Marc, Waterkeeper Alliance. August 2, 2018. \u201cLet Our Rivers Run Free: A Global Look at How Dams are Destroying our Waterways\u201d. Waterkeeper Magazine</ref> As President of the Alliance, Kennedy oversees its legal, membership, policy and fundraising programs. The Alliance states that it is dedicated to promoting \"swimmable, fishable, drinkable waterways, worldwide,\"<ref>\"Robert F. Kennedy, Jr. Honored at Water's Edge Gala\". (2014). Stroudcenter.org.</ref> and is also a clearinghouse, approving new Keeper programs and licensing use of the trademarked \"Waterkeeper,\" \"Riverkeeper,\" \"Soundkeeper,\" \"Lakekeeper,\" \"Baykeeper,\" \"Bayoukeeper,\" \"Canalkeeper,\" \"Coastkeeper,\" etc. names.<ref>Wilke, Chris (March 19, 2012) \"The Clean Water Act \u2013 A Story of Activism and Change\". Read the Dirt.</ref>\n\nKennedy and his environmental work have been the focus of several films including ''The Hudson Riverkeepers'' (1998)<ref>\"The Hudson Riverkeepers (1998)\". IMDb.</ref> and ''The Waterkeepers'' (2000),<ref>\"The Waterkeepers (TV Movie 2000)\". IMDb.</ref> both directed by Les Guthman. In 2008, he appeared in the [[IMAX]] documentary film ''[[Grand Canyon Adventure: River at Risk]]'', riding the length of the [[Grand Canyon]] in a wooden dory with his daughter Kick and with anthropologist [[Wade Davis (anthropologist)|Wade Davis]].<ref>\"Grand Canyon Adventure: River at Risk (2008)\". IMDb.</ref>\n\n===New York City Watershed Agreement===\nBeginning in 1991, Kennedy represented environmentalists and New York City watershed consumers in a series of lawsuits against New York City, New York State, and upstate watershed polluters. Kennedy authored a series of articles and reports<ref>Gordon, David K. and Kennedy, Jr., Robert F. (September 1991). \"The Legend of City Water: Recommendations For Rescuing the New York City Water Supply\". The Hudson Riverkeeper Fund.</ref><ref>Kennedy Jr., Robert F. (August 22, 1989). \"New York City's Water: Down the Drain\". ''The New York Times''.</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www1.nyc.gov/assets/planning/download/pdf/about/cpc/990237.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=October 14, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929044431/http://www1.nyc.gov/assets/planning/download/pdf/about/cpc/990237.pdf |archive-date=September 29, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> alleging that New York State was abdicating its responsibility to protect the water repository and supply. In 1996, he helped orchestrate the $1.2 billion New York City Watershed Agreement, which ''[[New York Magazine]]'' recognized in its cover story, \"The Kennedy Who Matters\".<ref>Wechsler, Pat (Nov 27, 1995). \"The Kennedy Who Matters\". ''New York Magazine''.</ref>  This agreement, which Kennedy negotiated on behalf of environmentalists and New York City watershed consumers, is regarded as an international model in stakeholder consensus negotiations and sustainable development.<ref>Schneeweiss, Jonathan (1997). \"Watershed Protection Strategies: A Case Study of the New York City Watershed in Light of the 1996 Amendments to the Safe Drinking Water Act\". 8 Vill. ''Environmental Law Journal'' 77.</ref>\n\n===Kennedy & Kevin Madonna===\n[[File:R.F.K._jr_2000.jpg|thumb|Kennedy in 2000]]\n\nIn 2000, Kennedy and environmental lawyer Kevin Madonna founded the [[environmental law]] firm Kennedy & Madonna, LLP, to represent private [[plaintiffs]] against polluters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kennedy-madonna-1zcf.squarespace.com/team/|title=Team|author=|date=|website=Kennedy & Madonna, LLP| accessdate=October 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929001322/http://kennedy-madonna-1zcf.squarespace.com/team/|archive-date=September 29, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The firm litigates environmental contamination cases on behalf of individuals, non-profit organizations, school districts, public water suppliers, Indian tribes, municipalities and states. In 2001, Kennedy & Madonna organized a team of prestigious plaintiff law firms to challenge pollution from industrial pork and poultry production.<ref>\"Farmers Worried by Suits Targeting Hog Producers\". January 7, 2001. ''Des Moines Register''. P.9.</ref>  In 2004, the firm was part of a legal team that secured a $70 million settlement for property owners in Pensacola, Florida whose properties were contaminated by chemicals from an adjacent [[Superfund]] site.<ref>\"ConocoPhillips agrees to $70M settlement for former Fla. facility\". April 7, 2004 EENews.net.</ref>\n\nKennedy & Madonna is profiled in the 2010 HBO documentary ''Mann v. Ford''<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1498566/ \"Mann v. Ford\"] (2010). IMDb.</ref> that chronicles four years of litigation brought by the firm on behalf of the [[Ramapough Mountain Indians|Ramapough Mountain Indian Tribe]] against the [[Ford Motor Company]] over the dumping of toxic waste on tribal lands in northern New Jersey.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hbo.com/documentaries/mann-v-ford/synopsis.html|title=Mann v. Ford: Synopsis|website=HBO| accessdate=October 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171006145520/http://www.hbo.com/documentaries/mann-v-ford/synopsis.html|archive-date=October 6, 2017|url-status=dead |df=mdy-all}}</ref>  In addition to a monetary settlement for the tribe, the lawsuit contributed to the community's land being re-listed on the federal Superfund list, the first time in the nation's history that a de-listed site was re-listed.<ref>Strunsky, Steve (October 14, 2006). \"[https://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/14/nyregion/nyregionspecial2/15njringwood.html Superfund Site Is Relisted, and Inquiry Begins]\". ''New York Times''.</ref>  In 2007 Kennedy was one of three finalists nominated as \"Trial Lawyer of the Year\" by Public Justice for his role in the $396 million jury verdict against [[DuPont]] for contamination from its [[Spelter]], West Virginia zinc plant.<ref>\"DuPont Fined $196.2M In Class-Action Suit\". October 19, 2007. CBSNews.com.</ref> In 2017, the firm was part of the trial team that secured a $670 million settlement on behalf of over 3,000 residents from Ohio and West Virginia whose drinking water was contaminated with the toxic chemical, C8, which was released into the environment by [[DuPont]] in [[Parkersburg]], West Virginia.<ref>Rinehart, Earl (February 13, 2017). \"DuPont to pay $670 million to settle C8 lawsuits\". ''The Columbus Dispatch''.</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Kennedy became counsel to the Morgan & Morgan PA|Morgan & Morgan P.A. law firm.<ref>{{cite web | url= https://www.forthepeople.com/attorneys/robert-f-kennedy-jr/ | title=Attorney Robert F. Kennedy, Jr | access-date=October 14, 2017 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929001139/https://www.forthepeople.com/attorneys/robert-f-kennedy-jr/ | archive-date=September 29, 2017 | url-status=live }}</ref>  The partnership arose from the two firms' successful collaboration on the case against SoCalGas Company following the [[Aliso Canyon gas leak]] in California.<ref>Cruz, Nancy (February 18, 2016) \"Porter Ranch Gas Leak With Attorney Robert F. Kennedy\". KTLA5.</ref>  In 2017, Kennedy and his partners sued Monsanto in federal court in San Francisco, on behalf of plaintiffs seeking to recover damages for [[non-Hodgkin's lymphoma]], that, the plaintiffs allege, were a result of exposure to Monsanto's [[glyphosate]]-based herbicide, Roundup. Kennedy and his team also filed a class action lawsuit against [[Monsanto]] for failing to warn consumers about the dangers allegedly posed by exposure to Roundup.<ref>Stecker, Tiffany (June 29, 2017). \"Monsanto's Foes Are Branching Out\". Environment, Health & Safety.</ref> In September 2018, Kennedy and his partners filed a class-action lawsuit against [[Columbia Gas of Massachusetts]] alleging negligence following [[Merrimack Valley gas explosions|gas explosions]] in three towns north of Boston. Of Columbia Gas, Kennedy said \u201cas they build new miles of pipe, the same company is ignoring its existing infrastructure, which we now know is eroding and is dilapidated.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://gazette.com/mass-families-file-class-action-days-after-gas-explosions/article_f1b671b8-bc7c-11e8-ae39-4787469086e9.html | title=Mass. Families file class action days after gas explosions | access-date=October 14, 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181014091538/https://gazette.com/mass-families-file-class-action-days-after-gas-explosions/article_f1b671b8-bc7c-11e8-ae39-4787469086e9.html | archive-date=October 14, 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Cleantech and renewable energy infrastructure entrepreneurship===\n\nIn 1998, Kennedy, Chris Bartle and John Hoving created a [[Bottled water|bottled-water]] company, Keeper Springs, which donated all of its profits to Waterkeeper Alliance.<ref>{{cite news |author1= Patricia Winters Lauro |title=Robert F. Kennedy Jr. is pushing supermarkets to sell a new brand of bottled water, with a twist |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/06/03/business/media-business-advertising-robert-f-kennedy-jr-pushing-supermarkets-sell-new.html |accessdate= 13 January 2020 |work= New York Times |date=3 June 1999}}</ref> In 2013, Kennedy and his partner sold the brand to [[Nestl\u00e9]] in exchange for a donation to local Waterkeepers.<ref>\"Nestle Waters Announces Partnership with Waterkeeper Alliance\". May 22, 2014. Nestle Waters.</ref>\n\nKennedy was a venture partner and senior advisor at [[VantagePoint Capital Partners]], one of the world's largest [[Clean technology|cleantech]] [[venture capital]] firms. Among other activities, VantagePoint was the original and largest pre-[[IPO]] institutional investor in [[Tesla, Inc.|Tesla]]. VantagePoint also backed BrightSource Energy and Solazyme, amongst others. Kennedy is a board member and counselor to several of Vantage Point's portfolio companies in the water and energy space, including Ostara, a Vancouver-based company that markets the technology to remove [[phosphorus]] and other excessive nutrients from [[wastewater]], transforming otherwise pollution directly into high-grade fertilizer.<ref>Wesoff, Eric (May 31, 2012) \"[https://www.greentechmedia.com/articles/read/ostara-nutrient-recovery-wins-14-5m-from-vantagepoint-et-al Ostara Nutrient Recovery Wins $14.5M From VantagePoint et al.]\". ''Greentech Media''.</ref>  He is also a senior advisor to Starwood Energy Group, and has played a key role in a number of the firm's investments.<ref>Wesoff, Eric (October 07, 2015) \"Flow Battery Funding: Vionx Teams With Siemens, UTC, 3M, Starwood and Jabil\". ''Greentech Media''.</ref>\n\nHe is on the board of Vionx, a [[Massachusetts]]-based utility scale [[vanadium flow battery]] systems manufacturer. On October 5, 2017, Vionx, [[National Grid plc|National Grid]] and the [[US Department of Energy]] completed the installation of advanced flow batteries at [[Holy Name Central Catholic High School|Holy Name High School]] in the city of [[Worcester, Massachusetts]]. The collaboration also includes [[Siemens]] and the [[United Technologies|United Technologies Research Center]] and constitutes one of the largest energy storage facilities in Massachusetts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20171005006381/en/Vionx-National-Grid-Department-Energy-Complete-Installation| title=Vionx, National Grid, and US Department of Energy Complete Installation of one of the World's Most Advanced Flow Batteries at Holy Name High School, Worcester, MA|website =www.businesswire.com|date=2017-10-05|access-date=October 15, 2017|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171016070018/http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20171005006381/en/Vionx-National-Grid-Department-Energy-Complete-Installation |archive-date=October 16, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nKennedy is a Partner in ColorZen, which offers a turnkey cotton fiber pre-treatment solution that reduces water usage and toxic discharges in the cotton dying process.<ref>Hilburn, Rachel Lewis (June 3, 2016). \"CoastLine: Robert F. Kennedy, Jr. on the Origin of CAFOs, Environmental Justice\". WHQR.</ref>\n\nKennedy was a co-owner and Director of the [[smart grid]] company Utility Integration Solutions (UISol),<ref>\"Robert F. Kennedy, Jr. Joins UISOL Board of Directors\". August 25, 2010. McDonnell Group.</ref>  which was acquired by [[Alstom]]. He is presently a co-owner and Director of GridBright, the market-leading grid management specialist.<ref>\"Robert F. Kennedy, Jr. joins Board of Directors\". November 1, 2016. GridBright.com.</ref>\n\nIn October 2011, Kennedy co-founded ''EcoWatch'', an environmental news site. He resigned from the board of directors in January 2018.<ref>Spear, Stefanie (November 02, 2011). \"EcoWatch and Waterkeeper Launch News Website\". EcoWatch.</ref>\n\n===Minority and poor communities===\nIn his first case as an environmental attorney, Kennedy represented the [[NAACP]] in a lawsuit against a proposal to build a garbage transfer station in a minority neighborhood in [[Ossining, New York (village)|Ossining, New York]].<ref>Melvin, Tessa (April 7, 1991) \"[https://www.nytimes.com/1991/04/07/nyregion/expanded-recycling-site-upsets-an-ossining-neighborhood.html Expanded Recycling Site Upsets an Ossining Neighborhood]\". ''New York Times''. {{Webarchive|url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171016021632/http://www.nytimes.com/1991/04/07/nyregion/expanded-recycling-site-upsets-an-ossining-neighborhood.html |date =October 16, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1987, he successfully sued [[Westchester County, New York|Westchester County]], New York, to reopen the [[Croton Point Park]], which was heavily used primarily by poor and minority communities from [[the Bronx]].<ref>Reed, Susan (July 2, 1990). \"[http://people.com/archive/polluters-beware-riverkeeper-john-cronin-patrols-the-hudson-and-pursues-those-who-foul-its-waters-vol-33-no-26 Polluters, Beware! Riverkeeper John Cronin Patrols the Hudson and Pursues Those Who Foul Its Waters]\". ''People''. {{Webarchive|url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171016014316/http://people.com/archive/polluters-beware-riverkeeper-john-cronin-patrols-the-hudson-and-pursues-those-who-foul-its-waters-vol-33-no-26 |date =October 16, 2017 }}</ref> He then forced the reopening of the [[Pelham Bay Park]] in the [[Bronx]], which New York City had closed to the public and converted to a police firing range.<ref name=\"auto4\"/> Kennedy also led a battle to stop a plan to sell Washington, D.C.'s [[Kingman Island]]\u2014a rare piece of [[National Park Service]] property in a minority neighborhood\u2014to a private developer. In 2004, Kennedy and Riverkeeper successfully sued Exxon to clean up a large oil spill on [[Newton Creek]] in [[Greenpoint, Brooklyn]].<ref>Confessore, Nicholas (November 1, 2005). \"[https://www.nytimes.com/2005/11/01/nyregion/an-old-oil-spill-divides-a-brooklyn-neighborhood.html An Old Oil Spill Divides a Brooklyn Neighborhood]\". ''The New York Times''. {{Webarchive| url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171016021714/http://www.nytimes.com/2005/11/01/nyregion/an-old-oil-spill-divides-a-brooklyn-neighborhood.html |date= October 16, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nKennedy has argued that poor communities shoulder the disproportionate burden of environmental pollution.<ref>Hilburn, Rachel Lewis (Jun 3, 2016). \"[http://whqr.org/post/coastline-robert-f-kennedy-jr-origin-cafos-environmental-justice#stream/0 CoastLine: Robert F. Kennedy, Jr. on the Origin of CAFOs, Environmental Justice]\". WHQR.org. {{Webarchive| url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171016014708/http://whqr.org/post/coastline-robert-f-kennedy-jr-origin-cafos-environmental-justice#stream/0 |date = October 16, 2017 }}</ref> Speaking at the 2016 [[South by Southwest|SXSW]] Eco environment conference in [[Austin, Texas]], he said, \"Polluters always choose the soft target of poverty\", noting that [[Chicago]]'s [[South Side, Chicago|south side]] has the highest concentration of toxic waste dumps in America.<ref>Wang, Ucilia (October 10, 2016) \"[https://www.theguardian.com/sustainable-business/2016/oct/10/robert-f-kennedy-jr-sxsw-eco-climate-change-big-business-economic-policy Robert F Kennedy Jr takes big business to task over pollution at SXSW Eco]\". ''The Guardian''. {{Webarchive|url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171016013920/https://www.theguardian.com/sustainable-business/2016/oct/10/robert-f-kennedy-jr-sxsw-eco-climate-change-big-business-economic-policy |date = October 16, 2017 }}</ref> Furthermore, he added that 80 percent of \"uncontrolled toxic waste dumps\" can be found in black neighborhoods, with the largest site in the United States being in [[Emelle, Alabama]], which is 90 percent black.<ref>Nirenberg, Michael Lee (May 23, 2017). \"[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/conversation-with-robert-kennedy-jr_us_59239362e4b0b28a33f62f03 Conversation with Robert F. Kennedy Jr.]\" ''Huffpost''</ref>\n\n===International and indigenous rights===\nStarting in 1985, Kennedy helped develop the [[Natural Resources Defense Council]] (NRDC)'s international program for environmental, energy, and [[human rights]], traveling to Canada and Latin America to assist indigenous tribes in protecting their homelands and opposing large-scale energy and extractive projects in remote wilderness areas.<ref>Brancaccio, David (January 21, 2005). \"[http://www.pbs.org/now/science/kennedy.html Science and Health: Robert F. Kennedy, Jr.]\". ''PBS NOW''. {{Webarchive| url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171019215936/http://www.pbs.org/now/science/kennedy.html |date= October 19, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1990, Kennedy assisted the [[Pehuenche]] Indians in Chile in a partially successful campaign to stop the construction of a series of dams on Chile's iconic [[Biob\u00edo River]]. That campaign derailed all but one of the proposed dams.<ref>Bowermaster, Jon.  (November 1992). \"[http://www.earthriver.com/library/conservation/11-conservation/town-and-country Last Run Down the Bio Bio]\". ''Town and Country Travel''.  {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171019220247/http://www.earthriver.com/library/conservation/11-conservation/town-and-country |date=October 19, 2017 }}</ref> Beginning in 1992, he assisted the [[Cree]] Indians of northern Quebec in their campaign against [[Hydro-Qu\u00e9bec]] to halt construction of some 600 proposed dams on eleven rivers in [[James Bay]].<ref>Clayton, Mark (April 20, 1994). \"[https://www.csmonitor.com/1994/0420/20042.html Cree Chief Wins Environmental Prize For Anti-Dam Effort]\". ''The Christian Science Monitor''. {{Webarchive| url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171019215821/https://www.csmonitor.com/1994/0420/20042.html |date= October 19, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1993, Kennedy and NRDC, working with the indigenous rights organization [[Cultural Survival]], clashed with other American environmental groups in a dispute about the rights of Indians to govern their own lands in the [[Oriente (Ecuador)|Oriente]] region of Ecuador.<ref name=\"auto6\">Kane, Joe (September 27, 1993). \"[https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/1993/09/27/with-spears-from-all-sides With Spears from All Sides]\". ''The New Yorker''. {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171019220608/https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/1993/09/27/with-spears-from-all-sides |date =October 19, 2017 }}</ref> Kennedy represented the [[CONFENIAE]], a confederation of Indian peoples, in negotiation with the American oil company [[Conoco]] to limit oil development in Ecuadorian Amazon and, at the same time, obtain benefits from resource extraction for Amazonian tribes.<ref name=\"auto6\"/> Kennedy was a vocal critic of [[Texaco]] for its previous record for polluting the Ecuadoran Amazon.<ref>Kennedy Jr., Robert F. (1991). Foreword for ''Amazon Crude'' by Judith Kimerling. Published by Natural Resource Defense Council. February 19, 1991. p.131. {{ISBN|0960935851}}.</ref>\n\nFrom 1993 to 1999, Kennedy worked with five [[Vancouver Island]] Indian tribes in their campaign to end industrial [[logging]] by [[MacMillan Bloedel]] in [[Clayoquot Sound]], [[British Columbia]].<ref>Kennedy Jr., Robert F. (1995). Foreword for ''Clayoquot Mass Trials: Defending the Rainforest'' by Ronald MacIsaac and Anne Champagne (editors), published by New Society Publisher, February 1995, p.208. {{ISBN|0865713200}}.</ref>\n\nIn 1996, Kennedy met with Cuban President [[Fidel Castro]] to persuade the leader to halt his plans to construct a nuclear power plant at [[Juragu\u00e1]].<ref>Rohter, Larry (February 19, 1996). \"[https://www.nytimes.com/1996/02/19/world/kennedy-castro-encounter-touched-by-history.html Kennedy-Castro Encounter Touched by History]\". ''The New York Times''.  {{Webarchive| url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171019221317/http://www.nytimes.com/1996/02/19/world/kennedy-castro-encounter-touched-by-history.html |date= October 19, 2017 }}</ref> During a lengthy latenight encounter, Castro reminisced about Kennedy's father and uncle, speculating that U.S. relations with Cuba would have been far better had President Kennedy not been assassinated.<ref>Rohter, Larry (February 25, 1996). \"[https://www.nytimes.com/1996/02/25/weekinreview/february-18-24-meeting-across-an-old-breach.html February 18\u201324; Meeting Across an Old Breach]\". ''The New York Times''. {{Webarchive|url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171019221730/http://www.nytimes.com/1996/02/25/weekinreview/february-18-24-meeting-across-an-old-breach.html  |date= October 19, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nBetween 1996 and 2000, Kennedy and NRDC helped Mexican commercial fishermen to halt [[Mitsubishi]]'s proposal to build a salt facility in the [[Laguna San Ignacio]], a known area in Baja where [[gray whale]]s bred, and nursed their calves.<ref>Smith, Matt (November 28th, 2001). \"[http://www.sfweekly.com/news/the-unlikely-environmentalists The Unlikely Environmentalists]\". ''SFWeekly''. {{Webarchive|url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171019220231/http://www.sfweekly.com/news/the-unlikely-environmentalists |date= October 19, 2017 }}</ref> Kennedy wrote extensively against the project, and took the campaign to Japan, meeting with the Japanese Prime Minister [[Keizo Obuchi]].<ref>Kennedy Jr., Robert F. (December 3, 1998). \"Rubbing Salt in the World Heritage Plan\". ''Japan Times''</ref>\n\nIn 2000, he assisted local environmental activists to stop proposals by Chaffin Light, a real estate developer, and U.S. engineering giant [[Bechtel]] from building a large hotel and resort development that, Kennedy argued, threatened [[coral reef]]s and public beaches used extensively by local Bahamians, at Clifton Bay, [[New Providence]] Island.<ref>Roberts, Bradley, MP, PLP (November 20, 2005). \"[http://reearth.org/index.php?p=n&sectid=4&subcat=38&aid=107 Bradley Roberts on Clifton]\". Address to Bahamas House of Assembly. {{Webarchive |url = https://web.archive.org/web/20171020002712/http://reearth.org/index.php?p=n&sectid=4&subcat=38&aid=107 |date =October 20, 2017 }}</ref> Following this, the new Bahamian government designated the area a Heritage Park.{{citation needed| date= October 2017}}\n\nKennedy was one of the early editors of ''[[Indian Country Today]]'', North America's largest [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Native American]] newspaper.<ref>Kennedy Jr., Robert F. (November 29, 2016). \"[https://www.ecowatch.com/kennedy-dakota-access-pipeline-2118593345.html?page=2 'I'll See You at Standing Rock']\". ''EcoWatch''. {{Webarchive| url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171020032256/https://www.ecowatch.com/kennedy-dakota-access-pipeline-2118593345.html?page=2 |date=October 20, 2017 }}</ref> He helped lead the opposition to the damming of the [[Futaleuf\u00fa River]] in the [[Patagonia]] region of Chile.<ref>Schaffer, Grayson (August 30, 2016). \"[https://www.outsideonline.com/2110076/chiles-best-whitewater-rivers-wont-be-dammed-now Chile's Best Whitewater Rivers Won't Be Damned \u2013 For Now]\". ''Outside''. {{Webarchive| url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171019220353/https://www.outsideonline.com/2110076/chiles-best-whitewater-rivers-wont-be-dammed-now |date = October 19, 2017 }}</ref> In 2016, citing the pressure precipitated by the Futaleuf\u00fa Riverkeeper's campaign against the dams, the Spanish power company, [[Endesa]], which owned the right to dam the river, reversed its decision and relinquished all claims to the Futaleuf\u00fa.<ref>Kennedy Jr., Robert F. (September 12, 2016). \"[https://www.ecowatch.com/futaleufu-whitewater-rafting-2002171427.html 20 Year David and Goliath Fist Fight Saves Patagonia's Futaleuf\u00fa]\". ''EcoWatch''. {{Webarchive| url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171007221222/https://www.ecowatch.com/futaleufu-whitewater-rafting-2002171427.html |date = October 7, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n===Military and Vieques===\nKennedy has been a critic of environmental damage by the U.S. military.<ref>Zukowski, Dan (June 22, 2017). \"[https://www.environews.tv/062217-act-war-rfk-jr-puts-u-s-military-cafos-blast-trashing-americas-waterways 'An Act of War': RFK Jr. Puts U.S. Military and CAFOs on Blast for Trashing America's Waterways]\". ''EnviroNews''. {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171022033952/https://www.environews.tv/062217-act-war-rfk-jr-puts-u-s-military-cafos-blast-trashing-americas-waterways/ |date=October 22, 2017 }}</ref><ref>Kennedy Jr., Robert F. (May 16, 2003). \"[http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2003-05-16/news/0305160280_1_superfund-sites-epa-report-pentagon Defending our Environment and Health from the U.S. Military]\". ''Chicago Tribune''. {{ Webarchive|url = https://web.archive.org/web/20171021220307/http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2003-05-16/news/0305160280_1_superfund-sites-epa-report-pentagon |date =October 21, 2017 }}</ref> In 1993, he successfully represented the [[Suquamish]] and [[Duwamish tribe|Duwamish]] Indian tribes in a lawsuit against the U.S. [[Puget Sound Naval Shipyard]] in [[Bremerton]], Washington, to stop polluting [[Puget Sound]].<ref>Le, Phuong (June 14, 2017). \"[http://www.kitsapsun.com/story/news/local/2017/06/14/suquamish-tribe-environmental-groups-sue-navy-over-hull-cleaning/397994001 Squamish Tribe, environmental groups sue Navy over hull cleaning]\". ''Kitsap Sun''. {{Webarchive| url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190420120650/https://www.kitsapsun.com/story/news/local/2017/06/14/suquamish-tribe-environmental-groups-sue-navy-over-hull-cleaning/397994001 |date= April 20, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nIn a 2001 article, Kennedy described how he sued the [[U.S. Navy]] on behalf of fishermen and residents of [[Vieques]], an island off [[Puerto Rico]], to stop weapons testing, bombing, and other military exercises. Kennedy argued that the activities were unnecessary, and that the Navy had illegally destroyed several endangered species, polluted the island's waters, harmed the residents' health, and damaged its economy.<ref name=\"vieques\">{{cite news |author1=Robert F. Kennedy Jr. |title=Why Are We in Vieques? |url=https://www.outsideonline.com/1819831/why-are-we-vieques |accessdate= 13 January 2020 |work=Outside |date=10 January 2001}}</ref> He was arrested for trespassing at [[Camp Garcia Vieques]], the [[U.S. Navy]] training facility, where he and others were protesting the use of a section of the island for training. Kennedy served 30 days in a maximum security prison in Puerto Rico.<ref>Greenhouse, Steven (July 16, 2001). \"[https://www.nytimes.com/2001/07/16/nyregion/he-s-in-charge-in-demand-and-in-prison.html He's in Charge, in Demand, in Prison]\". ''The New York Times''. {{Webarchive| url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171021221049/http://www.nytimes.com/2001/07/16/nyregion/he-s-in-charge-in-demand-and-in-prison.html |date= October 21, 2017 }}</ref> The trespassing incident forced the suspension of [[live-fire exercise]]s for almost three hours.<ref>\"[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/1470871.stm US Navy resumes Vieques war games]\". August 2, 2001. ''BBC News'' {{Webarchive |url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170629181314/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/1470871.stm |date=June 29, 2017 }}</ref> The lawsuits and protests by Kennedy, and hundreds of Puerto Ricans who were also imprisoned, eventually forced the termination of naval bombing in Vieques announced by president George Bush in 2001, and enacted in 2003.<ref>Hernandez, Raymond (June 15, 2001). \"[https://www.nytimes.com/2001/06/15/us/both-sides-attack-bush-plan-to-halt-bombing-on-vieques.html Both Sides Attack Bush Plan To Halt Bombing on Vieques]\". ''The New York Times''. {{Webarchive|url = https://web.archive.org/web/20171021221048/http://www.nytimes.com/2001/06/15/us/both-sides-attack-bush-plan-to-halt-bombing-on-vieques.html |date = October 21, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nIn a 2003 article for the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'', Kennedy accused the U.S. federal government of being \"America's biggest polluter\" and the [[U.S. Department of Defense]] as the worst offender. Citing the [[Environmental Protection Agency|EPA]], he said that \"unexploded ordnance waste can be found on 16,000 military ranges...and more than half may contain biological or chemical weapons\".<ref>Kennedy Jr., Robert F., (May 16, 2003). \"[http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2003-05-16/news/0305160280_1_superfund-sites-epa-report-pentagon Defending our environment and health from the U.S. military]\". ''Chicago Tribune''. {{Webarchive |url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171021220307/http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2003-05-16/news/0305160280_1_superfund-sites-epa-report-pentagon |date= October 21, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n===Factory farms===\nFor almost twenty years, Kennedy and his Waterkeepers waged a legal and public relations battle against pollution by factory farms. In the 1990s, he rallied opposition to factory farms among small independent farmers, convened a series of \"National Summits\" on factory meat products, and conducted press conference whistle stop tours across North Carolina, Iowa, Kansas, Missouri, Illinois, Ohio and in Washington DC. Beginning in 2000, Kennedy sued factory farms in North Carolina, Oklahoma, Maryland, and Iowa.<ref name=\"porkchop\">Hahn Niman, Nicolette (February 17, 2009). ''Righteous Porkchop: Finding a Life and Good Food beyond Factory Farms''. Published by William Morrow. p.336 {{ISBN|0061466492}}.</ref> He wrote numerous articles on the subject, arguing that factory farms produce lower-quality, less healthy food, and are harmful to independent family farmers by poisoning their air and water, reducing their property values, and using extensive state and federal subsidies to impose unfair competition against smaller farmers.<ref>{{cite news |author1= Robert F. Kennedy Jr. |author2=Eric Schaeffer |title= An Ill Wind From Factory Farms |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2003/09/20/opinion/an-ill-wind-from-factory-farms.html |accessdate= 13 January 2020 | work = New York Times |date=20 September 2003}}</ref>\n\nIn 1995, Premier [[Ralph Klein]] of Alberta declared Kennedy persona non grata in the province due to Kennedy's activism against Alberta's large-scale hog production facilities.<ref>Rogers, Shelagh, host, and Carty, Bob, reporter (Feb 12, 2001). \"Robert F. Kennedy Jr. warns Canada about Pollution from Pork Industry\". This Morning: CBC Digital Archives.</ref>  In 2002, [[Smithfield Foods]] filed a lawsuit against Kennedy in Poland, under a Polish law that makes criticizing a corporation illegal, after Kennedy denounced the company in a debate with Smithfield's Polish director before the Polish parliament.<ref name=\"porkchop\"/>\n\n===Oil, gas, and pipelines===\nKennedy has been an advocate for a global transition away from fossil fuels toward renewable energy.<ref>Ruf, Cory (May 25, 2013). \"Robert Kennedy Jr. on his crusade for a 'green' economy\". ''CBC News''.</ref><ref>Overheard with Evan Smith. (May 5, 2011). \"Robert F. Kennedy, Jr. \u2013 Fossil Fuels\". PBS</ref>  He has been particularly critical of the oil industry. He began his career at Riverkeeper during the time that the organization discovered that Exxon was using its oil tankers in order to steal fresh water from the Hudson River for use in its Aruba refinery and to sell to Caribbean Islands. Riverkeeper won a $2 million settlement against Exxon and lobbied successfully for a state law outlawing the practice.<ref>AP (April 26, 1984). \"Exxon is Sued by New York over Use of Hudson Water\". The New York Times.</ref> In one of his first environmental cases, Kennedy filed a lawsuit against [[Mobil Oil]] for polluting the Hudson.<ref>Cronin, John; Kennedy Jr., Robert F. (1997). ''The Riverkeepers: Two Activists Fight to Reclaim Our Environment as a Basic Human Right''. New York: Scribner. p.304. {{ISBN|0684839083}}.</ref>\n\nKennedy helped lead the battle against fracking in New York State.<ref>AP (March 02, 2013). \"New York fracking held as Gov. Andrew Cuomo, Robert F. Kennedy Jr. talk health, AP sources say\". Syracuse.com.</ref>  He had been an early supporter of natural gas as viable bridge fuel to renewables, and a cleaner alternative to coal.<ref>Isensee, Laura (October 28, 2009). \"Robert Kennedy Jr: solar and natural gas belong together\". Reuters</ref> However, he said he turned against this controversial extraction method after investigating its cost to public health; climate and road infrastructure.<ref>Marie Cusick (October 3, 2013). \"Robert F. Kennedy Jr. calls natural gas a 'catastrophe'\". StateImpact Pennsylvania</ref> As a member of Governor [[Andrew Cuomo]]'s fracking commission, Kennedy helped engineer the Governor's 2013 ban on fracking in New York State.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hakim |first1 =Danny |title =Shift by Cuomo on Gas Drilling Prompts Both Anger and Praise |url = https://www.nytimes.com/2012/10/01/nyregion/with-new-delays-a-growing-sense-that-gov-andrew-cuomo-will-not-approve-gas-drilling.html |accessdate =13 January 2020 |work= New York Times |date= 30 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nKennedy mounted a national effort against the construction of liquefied natural gas facilities.<ref>Staff writer (May 19, 2015). \"Rally Against Pipelines\". ''Salem Weekly''.</ref>  Waterkeepers maintains a national watch that documents numerous crude oil spills annually.  In Alaska, Kennedy was active in the fight to save the [[Arctic National Wildlife Refuge]] (ANWR), the largest undisturbed ecosystem in North America, from drilling.<ref>{{cite news |last1= Jones |first1 =Susan |title= ANWR Protest: 'Don't Drill, Storm Capitol Hill' |url= https://www.cnsnews.com/news/article/anwr-protest-dont-drill-storm-capitol-hill |accessdate =13 January 2020 |work=CNS News |date= 7 July 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Kennedy assisted the [[Chipewyan|Chipewyan First Nation]] and the [[Beaver Lake Cree Nation|Beaver Lake Cree]] fighting to protect their land from [[Oil sands|tar sands]] production.<ref name=\"macleans\">{{cite news |last1=Weber |first1=Bob |title= Prominent U.S. Keystone critic Robert F. Kennedy Jr. to visit oilsands |url =https://www.macleans.ca/news/prominent-u-s-keystone-critic-robert-f-kennedy-jr-to-visit-oilsands |accessdate =13 January 2020 |work= Macleans |date= 12 June 2013}}</ref> In February 2013, while protesting the [[Keystone XL Pipeline]] Kennedy, along with his son, Conor, was arrested for blocking a thoroughfare in front of the White House during a protest.<ref>Spear, Stefanie (February 13, 2013). \"Robert F. Kennedy, Jr., Bill McKibben, Michael Brune, Among Others Will Risk Arrest Today at White House to Stop Tar Sands, Keystone XL Pipeline\". ''EcoWatch''.</ref>  In August 2016, Kennedy and Waterkeeper participated in protests to block the extension of the [[Dakota Access pipeline]] across the [[Sioux]] Indian [[Standing Rock Reservation]]'s water supply.<ref>Manning, Sarah Sunshine (November 16, 2016). \"Robert F. Kennedy Jr. Visits Standing Rock on #NoDAPL Day of Action\". ''Indian Country Today''.</ref>\n\nKennedy claims that the only reason the oil industry is able to remain competitive against renewables and electric cars is through massive direct and indirect subsidies and political interventions on behalf of the oil industry. In a June 2017 interview on ''EnviroNews'', Kennedy said about the oil industry, \"That's what their strategy is: build as many miles of pipeline as possible. And what the industry is trying to do is to increase that level of infrastructure investment so our country won't be able to walk away from it.<ref>Zukowski, Dan (June 26, 2017). \"Robert F. Kennedy Jr. Talks Tesla, Electric Big Rigs and the Impending Death of Fossil Fuels\". ''EnivroNews''.</ref>\n\n===Coal===\nUnder Kennedy's leadership, Waterkeeper launched its \"Clean Coal is a Deadly Lie\"<ref>Baxter, Brandon (June 3, 2014). \"Robert F. Kennedy Jr. Praises Obama's Carbon Rules, Blasts Koch Brothers on 'The Ed Show'\". ''EcoWatch''.</ref> campaign in 2001, bringing dozens of lawsuits targeting mining practices, which include [[mountaintop removal]],<ref>Perks, Rob (March 11, 2010). \"[https://www.nrdc.org/experts/rob-perks/mountaintop-removal-redux-bobby-vs-blankenship-ii Mountaintop Removal Redux: Bobby vs. Blankenship II]\". NRDC.</ref> [[slurry]] pond construction, and targeting mercury emissions and [[coal ash]] piles by coal-burning utilities.<ref>\"Bobby Kennedy, Jr. Speaks on Coal Ash at Mt. Island Lake\". July 25, 2013. ''Clean Air Carolina''.</ref> Kennedy's Waterkeeper alliance has also been leading the fight against coal export, including from terminals in the Pacific Northwest.<ref>Yaggi, Marc, Waterkeeper Alliance (Winter 2013). \"Around the World a Coalition Against Coal: Waterkeepers from Idaho to India Unite to Stop the Deadly International Coal Trade\". ''Waterkeeper Magazine''</ref>\n\nKennedy has promoted replacing coal energy with renewable energy, which, he argues, would thereby reduce costs and greenhouse gases while improving air and water quality, the health of the citizens, and the number and quality of jobs.<ref>Staff writer (2015). \"At Pennsylvania Coal Mine, Feds Come to Rescue after State Fails\". ''Waterkeeper Magazine'' Vol. 11. Issue 1.</ref>\nIn June 2011, film producer Bill Haney televised his award-winning film ''[[The Last Mountain]]'', co-written by Haney and Peter Rhodes, depicting Kennedy's fight to stop [[Appalachian Mountains|Appalachian]] mountaintop removal mining.<ref>''[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1787816/ The Last Mountain]'' (2011) IMDb.</ref>\n\n===Nuclear power===\nKennedy has been an opponent of conventional nuclear power, arguing that it is unsafe and not economically competitive.<ref>Zukowski, Dan (June 23, 2017). \"Robert F. Kennedy Jr.: 'I love James Hansen, but he is wrong on [the nuclear power issue]'\". ''EniroNews''.</ref><ref>Brooks, Jon (June 22, 2011). \"Interview: Robert F. Kennedy Jr. on 'Uninsurable' Nuke Energy Industry, BrightSource Solar Project\". KQED.</ref> On June 15, 1981, he made international news when he spoke at an anti-nuclear rally at the [[Hollywood Bowl]], with [[Stephen Stills]], [[Bonnie Raitt]] and [[Jackson Browne]].<ref>Paul Chin photograph. (June 15, 1981). Caption reads, \"Robert F. Kennedy, Jr. speaks out against nuclear power\". Archivegrid, Los Angeles Public Library.</ref>\n\nHis thirty-year battle to close [[Indian Point Energy Center|Indian Point]] nuclear power plant in New York ended in victory in January 2017, when Kennedy signed onto an agreement with New York State Governor Andrew Cuomo and [[Entergy]], the plant's operator, to close the plant by 2021.<ref>Admin (April 4, 2017). \"Nuclear Ticking Time Bomb 28 Miles From NYC \u2013 America's Lawyer\". Indian Point Safe Energy Coalition.</ref> Kennedy was featured in a 2004 documentary, ''Indian Point: Imagining the Unimaginable'', directed by his sister and documentary filmmaker [[Rory Kennedy]].<ref>''[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0426493/ Indian Point: Imagining the Unimaginable]'', (TV movie 2004). IMDb.</ref>\n\n===Hydro===\nKennedy has been an outspoken opponent of dams, particularly of dam projects that affect indigenous communities.\n\nIn 1991, Kennedy helped lead a campaign to block [[Hydro-Qu\u00e9bec]] from building the James Bay Hydro-project, a massive dam project in northern Quebec.<ref>{{cite news |last1= Trueheart |first1= Charles |title= Quebec Power Company Finds Its High-Voltage Plans Short-Circuited |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1994/04/07/quebec-power-company-finds-its-high-voltage-plans-short-circuited/4ba36f07-d34b-4105-b3b4-849b08e1431b | accessdate= 13 January 2020 |work = Washington Post |date= 7 April 1994}}</ref>\n\nHis campaigns helped block dams on [[Chile]]'s [[Biob\u00edo River]] in 1990<ref>Bowermaster, Jon (November 1992). \"Last Run Down the Bio Bio\". ''Town and Country''.</ref> and its [[Futaleuf\u00fa River]] in 2016. In 2002, he mounted what was ultimately an unsuccessful battle against building a dam on [[Belize]]'s [[Macal River]]. Kennedy termed the [[Chalillo Dam]] \"a boondoggle\", and brought a high-profile legal challenge against [[Fortis Inc.]], a Canadian power company and the monopoly owner of Belize's electric utility.<ref name=\"auto7\">Guynup, Sharon (June 7, 2002). \"Belize Dam Fight Heats Up as Court Prepares to Rule\". ''National Geographic Today''.</ref> In a 3&ndash;2 ruling in 2003, the [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom]] upheld the Belizean government's decision to permit dam construction.<ref name=\"auto7\"/><ref>Leaney, Stephen (April 11, 2003). \"British finding 'secret war' in green laws by Kennedy\". ''International Press Service''.</ref><ref>Ari Hershowitz, \"[https://scholarship.law.berkeley.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1858&context=elq A Solid Foundation: Belize's Chalillo Dam and Environmental Decisionmaking]\", ''Ecology Law Quarterly'', Vol. 35, pp. 73-106.</ref> \n\nIn 2004, Kennedy met with Provincial officials and brought foreign media and political visitors to Canada to protest the building of [[hydroelectric]] dams on Quebec's [[Magpie River (Quebec)|Magpie River]].<ref>\"Robert F. Kennedy Jr. on the river along with numerous leaders of conservation organizations\". August 02, 2004. Canadian Parks And Wilderness Society \u2013 Quebec Chapter.</ref> [[Hydro-Quebec]] dropped plans for the dam in 2017.<ref>Goujard, Clothilde (September 14, 2017). \"Hydro-Quebec abandons dam project on majestic Magpie River\". ''National Observer''.</ref>\n\nIn November 2017, the Spanish hydroelectric syndicate [[Endesa]] announced its decision to abandon [[HydroAysen]], a massive project to construct dams on dozens of [[Patagonia]]'s rivers accompanied by thousands of miles of roads, power lines and other infrastructure. Endesa returned its [[water right]]s to the Chilean government. The Chilean press credits advocacy by Kennedy and Riverkeeper as critical factors in the company's decision.<ref>Martinez, Rodrigo (November 19, 2017). \"[http://www.latercera.com/noticia/robert-kennedy-jr-los-beneficios-economicos-unos-millonarios Robert Kennedy Jr por Hidroays\u00e9n: 'Los beneficios econ\u00f3micos eran para unos pocos millonarios']\". ''La Tercera''. {{Webarchive | url = https://web.archive.org/web/20171120084704/http://www.latercera.com/noticia/robert-kennedy-jr-los-beneficios-economicos-unos-millonarios  | date =November 20, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n===Cape Wind===\nIn 2005, Kennedy clashed with national environmental groups over his opposition to a wind farm off [[Cape Cod]]. Taking the side of Cape Cod's commercial fishing industry, Kennedy argued that the [[Cape Wind Project]] in [[Nantucket Sound]] was a costly [[boondoggle]]. This position angered some environmentalists, and brought Kennedy criticism by industry groups and Republicans{{who|date=October 2017}}.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://radioequalizer.blogspot.com/2007/07/rfk-jr-tirade-air-america-john-stossel.html |title= The Radio Equalizer: Brian Maloney: RFK Jr Tirade, Air America, John Stossel, Rush Limbaugh, Sean Hannity |access-date = October 25, 2017 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20171025132306/http://radioequalizer.blogspot.com/2007/07/rfk-jr-tirade-air-america-john-stossel.html | archive-date = October 25, 2017| url-status= live}}</ref> Kennedy argued in an opinion piece in the ''Wall Street Journal'' that \"[[Vermont]] wants to take its nuclear plant off line and replace it with clean, green power from [[Hydro-Qu\u00e9bec|HydroQu\u00e9bec]]\u2014power available to [[Massachusetts Department of Public Utilities|Massachusetts utilities]]\u2014at a cost of six cents per kilowatt hour (kwh). Cape Wind electricity, by a conservative estimate and based on figures they filed with the state, comes in at 25 cents per kwh.\"<ref>https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702304521304576447541604359376</ref>\n\n==Personal views==\n\n[[File:RfkjrOCT2017.jpg|thumb|Kennedy in 2017]]\n\n===Political criticisms===\nThroughout the [[presidency of George W. Bush]], Kennedy was a persistent critic of Bush's environmental and energy policies. He accused Bush of defunding and corrupting federal science projects.<ref>Griscom, Amanda (October/November 2004). \"Environmental Justice\". ''Mother Earth News''.</ref>\n \nKennedy was also critical of Bush's 2003 [[Hydrogen vehicle|hydrogen car]] initiative,<ref>{{cite news |last1 =Roberts |first1= Joel |title = Bush: $1.2 Billion For Hydrogen Cars |url= https://www.cbsnews.com/news/bush-12-billion-for-hydrogen-cars |accessdate =13 January 2020 |work = CBS News |date =29 January 2003}}</ref> noting that it was a gift to the fossil fuel industry disguised as a green automobile.<ref>{{cite news |author1= Robert F. Kennedy Jr. |title=A Bad Element |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2003/02/16/opinion/a-bad-element.html |accessdate =13 January 2020 |work =New York Times | date= 16 February 2003}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, Kennedy wrote an article in ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' about Bush's environmental record,<ref name=\"must-be-done\">{{cite news |title=Robert F. Kennedy Jr. on the Climate Crisis: What Must Be Done |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/politics-news/robert-f-kennedy-jr-on-the-climate-crisis-what-must-be-done-192191 |accessdate=13 January 2020 |work=Rolling Stone |date=28 June 2007}}</ref> which he subsequently expanded into a ''New York Times'' bestselling book.<ref>Kennedy, Jr., Robert F. (2004). ''Crimes Against Nature: How George W. Bush and His Corporate Pals Are Plundering the Country and Hijacking Our Democracy''. HarperCollins. {{ISBN|0060746882}}.</ref> His opposition to the environmental policies of the Bush administration earned him recognition as one of ''Rolling Stone''{{'s}} \"100 Agents of Change\" on April 2, 2009.<ref>{{cite web | url= https://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/26754176/the_rs_100_agents_of_change/4 |title= The 100 People Who Are Changing America |author= | website =Rolling Stone| accessdate = October 15, 2017|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090503094135/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/26754176/the_rs_100_agents_of_change/4 |archive-date=May 3, 2009 | url-status = live}}</ref><ref name=\"mercurynews.com\">{{cite web| url= http://www.mercurynews.com/2010/10/14/robert-f-kennedy-jr-advocates-for-green-power |title = Robert F. Kennedy Jr. advocates for green power |author =|date= October 14, 2010 |website= The Mercury News |accessdate = October 15, 2017|archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20171010055245/http://www.mercurynews.com/2010/10/14/robert-f-kennedy-jr-advocates-for-green-power |archive-date = October 10, 2017| url-status =live}}</ref>\n\nDuring an October 2012 interview with ''[[Politico]]'', Kennedy called on environmentalists to direct their dissatisfaction towards the [[U.S. Congress]] rather than President [[Barack Obama]], reasoning that Obama \"didn't deliver\" due to having a partisan U.S. Congress \"like we haven't seen before in American history\".<ref>Dixon, Darius (October 12, 2012). \"RFK Jr. to greens: Not Obama's fault\". ''Politico''.</ref>  He also accused politicians who failed to act on climate change policy as serving special interests and, selling out the public trust. He accused [[Koch family|Charles and David Koch]], the owners of [[Koch Industries]], Inc., the nation's largest privately owned oil company, of subverting democracy and for \"making themselves billionaires by impoverishing the rest of us\".<ref>Robert F. Kennedy, Jr. (2015) \"What State Attorneys General can do about Climate-Change Deniers\" Letter from the President\", ''Waterkeeper Magazine'' Vol. 11. Issue 1.</ref>  Kennedy has spoken of the Koch Brothers as leading \"the apocalyptical forces of Ignorance and Greed\".<ref>Spear, Stefanie (September 10, 2015). \"Koch Brothers: Apocalyptical Forces of Ignorance and Greed, Says RFK Jr.\" ''EcoWatch''.</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2014 People's Climate March]], Kennedy said, \"American politics is driven by two forces: One is intensity, and the other is money. The Koch brothers have all the money. They're putting $300 million this year into their efforts to stop the climate bill. And the only thing we have in our power is people power, and that's why we need to put this demonstration on the street\".<ref>Goodman, Amy (September 22, 2014). \"Robert F. Kennedy Jr.: \"The Only Thing We Have in Our Power is People Power\". ''Democracy Now''.</ref>\n\n===Food allergies===\nKennedy was a founding board member of the [[Food Allergy Initiative]]. His son Conor suffers from anaphylaxis peanut allergies. Kennedy wrote the foreword to ''The Peanut Allergy Epidemic'', in which he and the authors link increasing food allergies in children to certain vaccines that were approved beginning in 1989.<ref>Kennedy Jr., Robert F. (June 6, 2017). Foreword for ''The Peanut Allergy Epidemic: What's Causing It And How To Stop It''. Third Edition. by Heather Fraser, New York: Skyhorse Publishing. {{ISBN|1510726314}}.</ref>\n\n=== Views on autism and vaccines ===\nKennedy is the chairman of [[Children's Health Defense]] (formerly the World Mercury Project), an advocacy group alleging that a large proportion of American children are suffering from conditions as diverse as autism, [[attention deficit hyperactivity disorder]], [[Food allergy|food allergies]], [[cancer]] and [[autoimmune disease]]s, all allegedly caused by exposure to a variety of chemicals. In addition to vaccines, Children's Health Defense has been campaigning against [[Water fluoridation|fluoridation of drinking water]], [[Paracetamol|acetaminophen]], [[aluminum]], and [[Wireless|wireless communications]], among others. Kennedy's group has been identified as one of two major buyers of anti-vaccine Facebook advertising in late 2018 and early 2019.<ref name=journ>{{Cite journal | last = Jamison |first= A.M.| last2= Broniatowski |first2= D. A. |last3= Dredze |first3=M. |date= 2019-11-13 |title= Vaccine-related advertising in the Facebook Ad Archive |journal = Vaccine |volume= 38|issue= 3|pages= 512\u2013520|doi= 10.1016/j.vaccine.2019.10.066|pmid= 31732327|pmc= 6954281}}</ref><ref name=study>{{Cite news |url= https://web.archive.org/web/20191117003403/https://www.washingtonpost.com/health/2019/11/15/majority-anti-vaccine-ads-facebook-were-funded-by-two-groups |title = Majority of anti-vaccine ads on Facebook were funded by two groups |last= Sun| first = Lena H. |date= 2019-11-15 |work= Washington Post| access-date= 2019-11-16 |url-status =live |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20191117003403/https://www.washingtonpost.com/health/2019/11/15/majority-anti-vaccine-ads-facebook-were-funded-by-two-groups |archive-date =2019-11-16}}</ref>\n\nIn their early years, the group focused on the perceived issue of [[Mercury (element)|mercury]], in industry and medicine, especially the ethylmercury compound [[thimerosal]] in [[vaccine]]s, proposed by discredited former doctor [[Andrew Wakefield]] as a mechanism for the disproved link between vaccines and autism. Despite Kennedy's claims that he is in fact not against vaccines,<ref name=notav1>{{Cite news| url = https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/08/health/vaccines-kennedy-measles.html |title =Brother and Sister of Robert F. Kennedy Jr. Accuse Him of Spreading Misinformation on Vaccines |last= Rabin| first= Roni Caryn| date= May 8, 2019|work=The New York Times |access-date=June 21, 2019| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190621221444/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/08/health/vaccines-kennedy-measles.html|archive-date= June 21, 2019 | url-status =live}}</ref><ref name=notav2>{{Cite news |url= https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/entry/siblings-oped-calls-robert-f-kennedy-jrs-vaccine-views-tragically-wrong_n_5cd2ca19e4b07ce6ef78850e |title = Robert Kennedy Jr.'s Vaccine Views Slammed As 'Tragically Wrong' By Family |last =Golgowski| first= Nina| date = May 8, 2019 |work= Huffington Post | access-date=June 21, 2019|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190621221641/https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/entry/siblings-oped-calls-robert-f-kennedy-jrs-vaccine-views-tragically-wrong_n_5cd2ca19e4b07ce6ef78850e |archive-date= June 21, 2019|url-status =live}}</ref> critics point out he and his organization spread common anti-vaccine arguments as part of their core messages. Kennedy has stated the media and governments are engaged in a conspiracy to deny that vaccines cause autism.<ref name=glob>{{Cite web| url=https://globalnews.ca/news/3253840/robert-de-niro-robert-f-kennedy-jr-offer-100g-to-anyone-who-can-provide-proof-vaccines-are-safe |title= Robert De Niro, Robert F. Kennedy Jr. offer $100K to anyone who can provide proof vaccines are safe| last=Scott| first= Katie|date= February 16, 2017|website= Global TV|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190303172615/https://globalnews.ca/news/3253840/robert-de-niro-robert-f-kennedy-jr-offer-100g-to-anyone-who-can-provide-proof-vaccines-are-safe |archive-date =March 3, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=March 3, 2019}}</ref><ref name=SBM1>{{Cite web|url= https://sciencebasedmedicine.org/autism-prevalence-increases-to-1-in-59-and-antivaxers-lose-it-yet-again |title=Autism prevalence increases to 1 in 59, and antivaxers lose it\u2026yet again |last=Gorski |first=David| authorlink=David Gorski|date=April 30, 2018| website=Science-Based medicine | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190227151319/https://sciencebasedmedicine.org/autism-prevalence-increases-to-1-in-59-and-antivaxers-lose-it-yet-again |archive-date= February 27, 2019| url-status= live| access-date = February 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | url = https://www.cbc.ca/news/opinion/kennedy-surrey-1.5206701 |title= The Surrey Board of Trade shouldn't help anti-vaxxer Robert F. Kennedy Jr. build his brand | last = Cadeski |first=Eric| date= July 11, 2019|work = CBC News| access-date= 2019-11-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news| url= https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/robert-f-kennedy-jr-surrey-speaking-event-1.5178877 |title= Robert F. Kennedy Jr. will speak at Surrey event despite outcry, board of trade says |last = Schmunk |first =Rhianna |date=2019-06-17 |work =CBC News |access-date =2019-11-18}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2005, Kennedy authored an article in ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' and ''[[Salon (website)|Salon]]'' called \"[[Deadly Immunity]]\", alleging a government conspiracy to conceal a connection between thimerosal and the epidemic of childhood [[neurodevelopmental disorders]], including [[autism]].<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite news |author1= Robert F. Kennedy Jr. |title=Deadly Immunity |url= https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/politics-news/deadly-immunity-180037  |accessdate=13 January 2020 |work=Rolling Stone |date=8 February 2011}}</ref> The article contained five factual errors, leading ''Salon'' to issue corrections.<ref name=\"auto2\">Lauerman, Kerry (January 16, 2011). \"[http://www.salon.com/2011/01/16/dangerous_immunity Correcting our Record]\". ''Salon''. {{Webarchive |url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171104122950/https://www.salon.com/2011/01/16/dangerous_immunity |date=November 4, 2017 }}</ref> Six years later, on January 16, 2011, ''Salon'' retracted the article completely.<ref name=\"auto2\"/> According to ''Salon'', the retraction was motivated by accumulating evidence of alleged errors and [[scientific fraud]] underlying the vaccine-autism claim.<ref>Oransky, Ivan (January 16, 2011) \"[http://retractionwatch.com/2011/01/16/salon-retracts-2005-robert-f-kennedy-jr-piece-on-alleged-autism-vaccine-link ''Salon'' retracts 2005 Robert F. Kennedy Jr. piece on alleged autism-vaccine link]\". ''Retraction Watch''. {{Webarchive| url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170831053935/http://retractionwatch.com/2011/01/16/salon-retracts-2005-robert-f-kennedy-jr-piece-on-alleged-autism-vaccine-link |date = August 31, 2017 }}</ref> ''Rolling Stone'' stands by Kennedy's story.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nIn May 2013, Kennedy delivered the keynote address at the vaccination information<ref>{{Cite web |url= https://blogs.plos.org/thepanicvirus/2012/05/15/more-media-stupidity-chicago-sun-times-runs-propaganda-piece-for-jenny-mccarthys-anti-vaccine-conference |title = More media stupidity: ''Chicago Sun-Times'' runs propaganda piece for Jenny McCarthy's anti-vaccine conference |website = The Panic Virus |access-date =2019-01-28 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190129064155/https://blogs.plos.org/thepanicvirus/2012/05/15/more-media-stupidity-chicago-sun-times-runs-propaganda-piece-for-jenny-mccarthys-anti-vaccine-conference |archive-date =January 29, 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref> AutismOne / [[Generation Rescue]] conference.<ref name=\"Slate_2013\">{{Cite journal| last1= Plait |first1= Phil| authorlink1 = Phil Plait| title= Robert F. Kennedy Jr.: Anti-Vaxxer | url= http://www.slate.com/blogs/bad_astronomy/2013/06/05/robert_f_kennedy_jr_advocate_for_antiscience_and_antivaccination.html |journal = Slate | accessdate =13 February 2018 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20180208145313/http://www.slate.com/blogs/bad_astronomy/2013/06/05/robert_f_kennedy_jr_advocate_for_antiscience_and_antivaccination.html | archivedate =8 February 2018 |date= 5 June 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"AutismOne_2013\">{{cite web |title= Generation Rescue Conference 2013| url = http://www.autismone.org/content/autismone-generation-rescue-conference-2013 | website= AutismOne | accessdate = 13 February 2018 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130730131034/http://www.autismone.org/content/autismone-generation-rescue-conference-2013 | archivedate = 30 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014 Kennedy published a book, ''Thimerosal: Let the Science Speak: The Evidence Supporting the Immediate Removal of Mercury\u2014a Known Neurotoxin\u2014from Vaccines''. While methylmercury is a potent neurotoxin, ethylmercury, as used in vaccine preservatives, is safer.<ref>{{cite web | title = Thimerosal and Vaccines |url= https://www.fda.gov/vaccines-blood-biologics/safety-availability-biologics/thimerosal-and-vaccines#pres |publisher= U.S. Food and Drug Administration |access-date=August 24, 2019 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190825041528/https://www.fda.gov/vaccines-blood-biologics/safety-availability-biologics/thimerosal-and-vaccines#pres |archive-date = August 25, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>  The preface to the book is written by [[Mark Hyman (doctor)|Mark Hyman]], a proponent of the [[Alternative medicine|alternative medical treatment]] called [[functional medicine]].<ref name=\"Cracked31\">{{cite AV media | title = Functional Medicine (CS31) | url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3EDW_upV3ZU |website=YouTube |accessdate=18 April 2019 | publisher = McGill Office for Science and Society | date=13 April 2019 | time =6:18}}</ref> Kennedy has published many articles on the inclusion of the mercury-based preservative thimerosal in vaccines, which have appeared in ''[[Huffington Post]]'',<ref>Kennedy Jr., Robert F. (May 11, 2010). \"[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/robert-f-kennedy-jr/central-figure-in-cdc-vac_b_494303.html Central Figure in CDC Vaccine Cover-Up Absconds With $2M]\". ''Huffpost''. {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171017141128/https://www.huffingtonpost.com/robert-f-kennedy-jr/central-figure-in-cdc-vac_b_494303.html |date=October 17, 2017 }}</ref> ''EcoWatch'',<ref>Kennedy Jr., Robert F. (Feb. 8, 2017). \"[https://www.ecowatch.com/yale-vaccine-study-kennedy-2246059411.html Yale University Study Shows Association Between Vaccines and Brain Disorders]\". ''EcoWatch''. {{Webarchive| url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171013120638/https://www.ecowatch.com/yale-vaccine-study-kennedy-2246059411.html | date = October 13, 2017 }}</ref><ref>Kennedy Jr., Robert F. (Jan. 18, 2017) \"[https://www.ecowatch.com/cdc-mercury-vaccines-kennedy-2199157054.html CDC Knew its Vaccine Program Was Exposing Children to Dangerous Mercury Levels Since 1999]\". ''EcoWatch''. {{Webarchive | url = https://web.archive.org/web/20171007220719/https://www.ecowatch.com/cdc-mercury-vaccines-kennedy-2199157054.html |date= October 7, 2017 }}</ref> and ''[[The Boston Globe]]''.<ref>Kennedy Jr., Robert F. (July 10, 2005). \"[http://archive.boston.com/news/globe/editorial_opinion/oped/articles/2005/07/01/autism_mercury_and_politics Autism, Mercury, and Politics]\". ''The Boston Globe''. {{Webarchive| url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170304051731/http://archive.boston.com/news/globe/editorial_opinion/oped/articles/2005/07/01/autism_mercury_and_politics | date = March 4, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nIn April 2015, Kennedy participated in a Speakers' Forum to promote the film ''[[Trace Amounts]]'', which promotes the link between autism and mercury in vaccinations. At a film screening, Kennedy described the autism epidemic as a \"holocaust\".<ref>White, Jeremy B. (April 7, 2015). \"[http://www.sacbee.com/news/politics-government/capitol-alert/article17814440.html Robert Kennedy Jr. warns of vaccine-linked 'holocaust']\". ''Sacramento Bee''.{{Webarchive |url =https://web.archive.org/web/20150411002553/http://www.sacbee.com/news/politics-government/capitol-alert/article17814440.html |date= April 11, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nOn January 10, 2017, incoming [[White House Press Secretary]] [[Sean Spicer]] confirmed that Kennedy and [[President-elect]] [[Donald Trump]] met to discuss a position in the Trump administration. Kennedy accepted an offer made by Trump to become the chairman of the Vaccine Safety Task Force. A spokeswoman for Trump's transition said that no final decision had been made.<ref name=\"skeptic\">{{Cite news |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/trump-to-meet-with-proponent-of-debunked-tie-between-vaccines-and-autism/2017/01/10/4a5d03c0-d752-11e6-9f9f-5cdb4b7f8dd7_story.html |authors = Phillip, Abby; Sun, Lena H. and Bernstein, Lenny |date = 10 January 2017| title= Vaccine skeptic Robert Kennedy Jr. says Trump asked him to lead commission on 'vaccine safety' | work = The Washington Post |access-date =January 11, 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170111010144/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/trump-to-meet-with-proponent-of-debunked-tie-between-vaccines-and-autism/2017/01/10/4a5d03c0-d752-11e6-9f9f-5cdb4b7f8dd7_story.html | archive-date =January 11, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> In an August 2017 interview with ''[[Stat (website)|STAT News]]'' reporter Helen Branwell, Kennedy said that he had been meeting with the federal public health regulators to discuss defects in vaccine safety science, at the White House's request.<ref>\"[https://worldmercuryproject.org/news/interview-stat-news-august-14-2017 An interview with Robert Kennedy Jr. on vaccines]\". Interviewed by [[Helen Branswell]]. August 21, 2017. World Mercury Project.{{Webarchive| url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171013172227/https://worldmercuryproject.org/news/interview-stat-news-august-14-2017 |date=October 13, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nOn February 15, 2017, Kennedy and actor [[Robert De Niro]] gave a press conference at the [[National Press Club (United States)|National Press Club]] in Washington, D.C., in which they accused the press of acting as propagandists for the $35 billion vaccination industry and refusing to allow debates on vaccination science. They offered a $100,000 reward to any journalist or other citizen who could point to a study showing that it is safe to inject mercury into babies and pregnant women at levels currently contained in [[Influenza vaccine|flu vaccines]]. Craig Foster, a psychology professor who studies [[pseudoscience]], deemed the challenge \"not science\", noting that it was a \"carefully constructed 'contest' that allows its creators to generate the misleading outcome they presumably want to see\". He also stated that \"Proving that something is safe is importantly different than proving that something is harmful\".<ref name=\"Craig Foster\">{{cite journal |last1=Foster |first1= Craig |title =The $100,000 vaccine challenge: Another method of promoting anti-vaccination pseudoscience |journal= Vaccine |date=2017 |volume= 35 |issue=32 |pages= 3905\u20133906 |doi=10.1016/j.vaccine.2017.06.012 |pmid=28624304 }}</ref>\n\nOn May 8, 2019, [[Kathleen Kennedy Townsend]], [[Joseph P. Kennedy II|Joseph P. Kennedy]] and [[Maeve Kennedy McKean]] wrote an open letter stating that while their relative has championed many admirable causes, he \"has helped to spread dangerous misinformation over social media and is complicit in sowing distrust of the science behind vaccines\".<ref name=ff>{{Cite news |url = https://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2019/05/08/robert-kennedy-jr-measles-vaccines-226798 |title= RFK Jr. Is Our Brother and Uncle. He's Tragically Wrong About Vaccines |last1 = Kennedy Townsend | first1=Kathleen| author-link1= Kathleen Kennedy Townsend | date =May 8, 2019| work = Politico | access-date =May 8, 2019|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190508183738/https://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2019/05/08/robert-kennedy-jr-measles-vaccines-226798 | archive-date = May 8, 2019 |url-status =live |last2= Kennedy |first2 =Joseph P.| author-link2 = Joseph P. Kennedy II |last3= Kennedy McKean| first3 = Maeve}}</ref>\n\nIn June 4, 2019, during a visit to [[Samoa]] coinciding with that nation's 57th independence celebration, Kennedy appeared in an Instagram photo with Australian-Samoan anti-vaccine activist [[Taylor Winterstein]]. Kennedy's charity and Winterstein have both perpetuated the lie that that the [[MMR vaccine]] played a role in the 2018 deaths of two Samoan infants, despite the subsequent revelation that the infants had received a [[muscle relaxant]] along with the vaccine by mistake. Kennedy has drawn criticism for fueling vaccine hesitancy amid a social climate which gave rise to the [[2019 Samoa measles outbreak]], which killed over 70 people, and the [[2019 Tonga measles outbreak]].<ref>{{cite news |last1= Lanuola |first1= Tusani Tupufia |title= John F. Kennedy's nephew joins Samoa's Independence celebration |url= https://www.samoaobserver.ws/category/samoa/42888 |accessdate = 30 November 2019 | publisher= Samoa Observer |date= 1 June 2019 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20191130201157/https://www.samoaobserver.ws/category/samoa/42888 | archivedate =30 November 2019 |ref = SamoaObserver_20190601 |url-status =live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1 = Guarino |first1=Ben |last2= Satija |first2= Neena |last3 =Sun |first3 = Lena H. |title = Deadly measles outbreak hits children in Samoa after anti-vaccine fears |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/health/2019/11/26/deadly-measles-outbreak-hits-children-samoa-after-anti-vaccine-fears  |accessdate= 30 November 2019 | work = The Washington Post |date= 27 November 2019 |ref=WaPo_Samoa_measles_20191127 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20191130201455/https://www.washingtonpost.com/health/2019/11/26/deadly-measles-outbreak-hits-children-samoa-after-anti-vaccine-fears |archivedate =30 November 2019 |url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nKennedy is listed as executive producer of ''Vaxxed II: The People's Truth'', the 2019 sequel to [[Andrew Wakefield]]'s and [[Del Bigtree]]'s anti-vaccination documentary ''[[Vaxxed]]''.<ref>{{Cite news| url= https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/oct/31/vaxxed-2-movie-sequel-release-fears-propaganda |title=Release of ''Vaxxed'' sequel prompts fears dangerous propaganda will spread again |last =Pilkington| first= Ed |date= 2019-10-31| work= The Guardian |access-date=2019-11-18}}</ref>\n\n===Views on the murder of Martha Moxley===\nIn January 2003, Kennedy wrote a controversial article in ''[[The Atlantic]]'' Monthly about the 1975 [[murder of Martha Moxley]] in Greenwich, Connecticut, in which he insists that Michael Skakel's indictment \"was triggered by an inflamed media, and that an innocent man is now in prison\". Skakel and Kennedy are first cousins, as Kennedy's mother and Skakel's father are siblings. The article argues that there is more evidence suggesting that Kenneth Littleton, the Skakel family's live-in tutor, killed Moxley. He also calls [[Dominick Dunne]] the \"driving force\" behind Skakel's prosecution.<ref name=\"miscarriage\">{{cite news |author1=Robert F. Kennedy Jr. |title=A Miscarriage of Justice |url= https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2003/01/a-miscarriage-of-justice/304759 |accessdate=13 January 2020 |work=The Atlantic |date=January\u2013February 2003}}</ref> In July 2016, Kennedy released a book titled ''Framed: Why Michael Skakel Spent over a Decade in Prison for a Murder He Didn't Commit''.<ref>{{cite news |first =Michael |last =Melia |date= July 12, 2016 |newspaper = Hartford Courant |title = RFK Jr. Book Stokes Intrigue In Michael Skakel Murder Case |url= http://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-skakel-book-0713-20160712-story.html |accessdate =July 12, 2016 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160713175621/http://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-skakel-book-0713-20160712-story.html |archive-date = July 13, 2016 |url-status =live }}</ref> In September 2017, the rights to Kennedy's book were optioned by FX Productions to develop a multi-part television series.<ref>Schneider, Michael (September 20, 2017). \"[http://www.indiewire.com/2017/09/robert-f-kennedy-framed-michael-skakel-martha-moxley-fx-1201876985 FX Prods. To Develop 'Framed,' Robert F. Kennedy Jr's Crusade to Clear His Cousin's Murder Conviction \u2013 Exclusive]\". ''IndieWire''.{{Webarchive| url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171011072523/http://www.indiewire.com/2017/09/robert-f-kennedy-framed-michael-skakel-martha-moxley-fx-1201876985 |date= October 11, 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.imdb.com/news/ni61529212 |title= FX Prods. to Develop 'Framed,' Robert F. Kennedy Jr's Crusade to Clear His Cousin's Murder Conviction | website =IMDb}}</ref>\n\n===Views on JFK assassination and the Warren Commission===\nOn the evening of January 11, 2013, [[Charlie Rose]] interviewed Kennedy and his sister [[Rory Kennedy|Rory]] at the [[Margot and Bill Winspear Opera House|Winspear Opera House]] in [[Dallas]] as a part of then Dallas Mayor [[Mike Rawlings]]' hand-chosen committee's yearlong program of celebrating the life and presidency of John F. Kennedy.<ref>DiEugenio, Jim (February 3, 2013). \u201cThe MSM and RFK Jr.: Only 45 years late this time\u201d. Kennedy and King (formerly CTKA).</ref> Robert F. Kennedy Jr. said that he was convinced that [[Lee Harvey Oswald]] was not solely responsible for the [[Assassination of John F. Kennedy|assassination]] of his uncle, President John F. Kennedy; and said his father [[Robert Kennedy]] was \"fairly convinced\" that others besides Oswald were involved in his brother's assassination and privately believed the [[Warren Commission]] report was a \"shoddy piece of craftsmanship\".<ref>{{cite web |url= http://bigstory.ap.org/article/rfk-children-speak-about-assassination-dallas-0 |title= RFK children speak about assassination in Dallas |work= The Big Story | accessdate= October 23, 2014| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150108084445/http://bigstory.ap.org/article/rfk-children-speak-about-assassination-dallas-0| archive-date = January 8, 2015| url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news| url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/retropolis/wp/2018/05/26/who-killed-bobby-kennedy-his-son-rfk-jr-doesnt-believe-it-was-sirhan-sirhan |title = Who killed Bobby Kennedy? His son RFK Jr. doesn't believe it was Sirhan Sirhan |last= |first= |date =June 5, 2018 |work= [[The Washington Post]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20181007092707/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/retropolis/wp/2018/05/26/who-killed-bobby-kennedy-his-son-rfk-jr-doesnt-believe-it-was-sirhan-sirhan |archive-date =October 7, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>DiEugenio, Jim (February 3, 2013). \u201cThe MSM and RFK Jr.: Only 45 years late this time\u201d. Kennedy and King (formerly CTKA).</ref> In an extended commentary on JFK's presidency on the 50th anniversary of his death, Kennedy referenced only one book, ''[[JFK and the Unspeakable]]''.<ref name=\"vision-peace\">{{cite news |title=John F. Kennedy's Vision of Peace |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/politics-news/john-f-kennedys-vision-of-peace-109020 |accessdate=13 January 2020 |work=Rolling Stone |date=20 November 2013}}</ref> The 2013 edition of the book was endorsed by Kennedy, who said it had moved him to visit [[Dealey Plaza]], the site of his uncle's assassination, for the first time.<ref name=Orbis>[[Orbis Books]], [http://www.orbisbooks.com/jfk-and-the-unspeakable.html ''JFK and the Unspeakable'']</ref> \n\n===Views on U.S. foreign policy===\nKennedy has written extensively on foreign policy, beginning with a 1974 ''Atlantic Monthly'' article titled, \"Poor Chile\", discussing the overthrow of Chilean President [[Salvador Allende]].<ref>Kennedy Jr., Robert F. (February 1974). \"Poor Chile\". ''Atlantic Monthly''.</ref>  Kennedy also wrote editorials against the execution of Pakistan President [[Zulfikar Ali Bhutto]] by General [[Muhammad Zia-ul-Haq]].<ref>Kennedy Jr. Robert F. (February 25, 1979). \"Plea to Pakistan\". ''The Washington Post''.</ref><ref>Kennedy Jr., Robert F. (February 23, 1979). \"Legacy at Stake in Pakistan\". ''The Boston Globe''.</ref>  In 1975, he published an article in ''The Wall Street Journal'', criticizing the use of assassination as a foreign policy tool.<ref>Kennedy Jr., Robert F. (Robert F. Kennedy, Jr. (December 16, 1975) \"Politics and Assassinations\". ''The Wall Street Journal''</ref>  In 2005, he wrote an article for the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' decrying President Bush's use of torture as anti-American.<ref>Kennedy Jr., Robert F. (December 17, 2005). \"America's anti-torture tradition\". ''Los Angeles Times''.</ref> Senator Edward Kennedy entered the article into the ''[[Congressional Record]]''.<ref>Congressional Record Index. (Vol 151 \u2013 Part 23). January 4, 2005 - December 30, 2005. by Senator Edward M. Kennedy. P.2054</ref>\n\nIn an article titled \"Why the Arabs Don't Want Us in Syria\", published in ''[[Politico]]'' in February 2016, Kennedy referred to the \"bloody history that modern [[Interventionism (politics)|interventionists]] like [[George W. Bush]], [[Ted Cruz]] and [[Marco Rubio]] miss when they recite their narcissistic trope that Mideast nationalists 'hate us for our freedoms.' For the most part they don't; instead they hate us for the way we betrayed those freedoms \u2014 our own ideals \u2014 within their borders\".<ref>{{cite news |author1 = Robert F. Kenney Jr. |title= Why the Arabs Don't Want Us in Syria |url = https://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2016/02/rfk-jr-why-arabs-dont-trust-america-213601 |accessdate =13 January 2020 |work = Politico |date = 22 February 2016}}</ref>  Kennedy blames the Syrian war on a pipeline dispute. He cites wiki-leaks documents alleging that the CIA-led military and intelligence planners to foment a [[Sunni]] uprising against [[Syria]]'s president, [[Bashar al-Assad]], following his rejection of a proposed [[Qatar-Turkey pipeline]] through Syria in 2009, well before the [[Arab Spring]].<ref>Kennedy Jr., Robert F. (February 25, 2016). \"Syria: Another Pipeline War\". ''EcoWatch''.</ref>  In 2013, Kennedy wrote an article for ''Rolling Stone'' exploring President John F. Kennedy's difficult struggle with his own military and intelligence apparatus to keep America out of war and from becoming an imperial state.<ref name=\"vision-peace\"/>\n\n===Political endorsements===\nKennedy was on the National Staff and a State Coordinator for [[Ted Kennedy#1980 presidential campaign|Edward M. Kennedy for President]] from 1979 to 1980. Prior to that he had been on Senator Kennedy's 1970 and 1976 Massachusetts Senatorial Campaigns. He was a co-founder and a former board member of the New York [[League of Conservation Voters]].<ref>Brancaccio, David (January 21, 2005). \"Science and Health: Robert F. Kennedy, Jr.\". ''PBS NOW''.</ref><ref>New York League of Conservative Voters. June 18, 2014. NYLCV Letterhead.</ref>\n\nKennedy endorsed and campaigned extensively for Vice President [[Al Gore]] during his [[Al Gore 2000 presidential campaign|2000 presidential campaign]], and openly opposed his friend [[Ralph Nader]]'s [[Green Party of the United States|Green Party]] [[Ralph Nader 2000 presidential campaign|presidential campaign]], predicting that it could sink the Gore campaign and put George W. Bush into the White House.  In the 2004 American presidential election, Kennedy endorsed [[John Kerry]], noting his strong environmental record.<ref>elch, Craig (October 29, 2003). \"RFK Jr. blasts Bush, champions Kerry\". ''The Seattle Times''.</ref>\n\n[[File:RFK DNC etown (1).jpg|thumb|right|Kennedy at a taping of [[ETown]] during the [[2008 Democratic National Convention]]]]\n\nIn late 2007, Kennedy and his sisters [[Kerry Kennedy|Kerry]] and [[Kathleen Kennedy Townsend|Kathleen]] announced that they would be endorsing [[Hillary Clinton]] in the [[2008 Democratic Party presidential primaries]].<ref>{{cite news |author1 =Jeff Zeleny |author2= Carl Hulse |title = Kennedy Chooses Obama, Spurning Plea by Clintons |url = https://www.nytimes.com/2008/01/28/us/politics/28kennedy.html | accessdate =13 January 2020 |work = New York Times |date =28 January 2008}}</ref> After the [[2008 Democratic National Convention|Democratic Convention]], Kennedy campaigned for Obama across the country.<ref>\"eTown at the 2008 Democratic National Convention (Denver)\". October 8, 2008. etown.org</ref>  After the election, he was named as a front-runner for Obama's [[Administrator of the Environmental Protection Agency|EPA administrator]].<ref>Lance, Jennifer (December 3, 2008). \"The Most Important Barack Obama Appointee: EPA Administrator Short List\". ''Red Green and Blue''.</ref>\n\nKennedy has been critical of the integrity of the voting process. In June 2006 he published an article in ''Rolling Stone'' purporting to show that GOP operatives stole the [[2004 United States presidential election|2004 election]] for President George W Bush. [[Farhad Manjoo]] countered Kennedy's conclusions,<ref>{{cite news |author1=Farhad Manjoo | authorlink1 =Farhad Manjoo |title=Was the 2004 election stolen? No. |url= https://www.salon.com/2006/06/03/kennedy_39/ |accessdate=13 January 2020 |work= Salon |date=3 June 2006}}</ref> but there were other people who argued otherwise.<ref>Zuesse, Eric (October 25, 2016). \"How the 2004 Presidential 'Election' Was Stolen by George W. Bush\". Washington's Blog.</ref>\n\nKennedy has written frequent warnings about the ease of election hacking and the dangers of voter purges and [[Voter ID laws in the United States|voter ID laws]]. He wrote the introduction and a chapter in ''Billionaires and Ballot Bandits'', a 2012 book on election hacking by investigative journalist [[Greg Palast]].<ref>Greg Palast (Author) Ted Rall (Illustrator). Introduction by Robert F. Kennedy, Jr. (2012). ''Billionaires & Ballot Bandits: How to Steal an Election in 9 Easy Steps''. Penguin Random House. p 300. {{ISBN|978-1609804787}}</ref>\n\n===Political aspirations===\nKennedy first considered running for political office in 2000, when New York Senator [[Daniel Patrick Moynihan]] announced he would not seek re-election to the [[List of United States Senators from New York|U.S. Senate seat]] formerly held by Kennedy's father.<ref>{{cite news |last1 = Bumiller |first1 =Elisabeth |title = Public Lives: Putting Family Life Ahead of a Senate Seat |url= https://www.nytimes.com/1998/11/24/nyregion/public-lives-putting-family-life-ahead-of-a-senate-seat.html |accessdate =13 January 2020 | work= New York Times |date = 24 November 1988}}</ref> His father was elected to the same seat in 1964, and held it for 41 months, until his death in 1968.\n\nIn 2005, Kennedy considered running for [[New York Attorney General]], which would have meant a possible run against his then brother-in-law [[Andrew Cuomo]], but in the end he decided against entering the race, even though he had been considered the frontrunner.<ref>{{cite news | author1 = Jonathan P. Hicks |title= Robert Kennedy Won't Run for State Attorney General |url = https://www.nytimes.com/2005/01/25/nyregion/robert-kennedy-wont-run-for-state-attorney-general.html |accessdate= 13 January 2020 |work =New York Times | date =25 January 2005}}</ref>\n\nOn December 2, 2008, Kennedy announced that he did not wish to be appointed to the U.S. Senate by New York Governor [[David Paterson]]. He felt that it would take too much time away from his family.<ref>{{cite news |author1= Jonathan P. Hicks |title = Robert F. Kennedy's Son Not Interested in Senate Seat |url= https://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2008/12/02/robert-f-kennedys-son-not-interested-in-senate-seat |accessdate = 13 January 2020 |work= New York Times |date=2 December 2008 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20191006100343/https://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2008/12/02/robert-f-kennedys-son-not-interested-in-senate-seat  | archivedate =6 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\n=== General interests ===\nKennedy is a licensed master [[Falconry|falconer]] and has trained hawks since he was 11. He breeds hawks and falcons and is also licensed as a raptor propagator and a wildlife rehabilitator.<ref>Rubinowitz, Susan. (December 10, 2014). \"Robert F. Kennedy Jr. \u2013 The Bird Rehabilitator\". Pet Place.</ref> He holds permits for Federal Game Keeper, Bird Bander, and Scientific Collector. He was President of the New York State Falconry Association from 1988 to 1991. In 1987, while on Governor Mario Cuomo's New York State Falconry Advising Committee, Kennedy authored the examination to qualify apprentice falconers given by New York State. Later that year he wrote the ''New York State Apprentice Falconer's Manual'',  which was published by the New York State Department of Environmental Conservation, and continues in use today.<ref>News Staff (February 15, 2002). \"Robert F. Kennedy Jr. to speak at Syracuse University\". Syracuse University News.</ref>\n\nKennedy is also a [[Whitewater kayaking|whitewater kayaker]]. His father introduced him and his siblings to whitewater kayaking during early trips down the [[Green River (Colorado River)|Green]] and [[Yampa River]]s in Utah and Colorado, the [[Columbia River]], the [[Middle Fork Salmon River|Middle Fork Salmon]] in Idaho, and the Upper Hudson Gorge. From 1976 to 1981, Kennedy was a partner and guide at a whitewater company, \"Utopian\", based in [[West Forks, Maine]]. He organized and led several \"first-descent\" whitewater expeditions to Latin America including three hitherto unexplored rivers: the [[Apur\u00edmac River|Apurimac]], Peru, in 1975; the [[Atrato]], Colombia, in 1979; and the [[Caron\u00ed River|Caroni]], Venezuela, in 1982.<ref>Collier, Peter and Horowitz, David (1984). ''The Kennedys: An American Drama''. Published by Summit Books. p. 576. {{ISBN|0671447939}}.</ref> He made an early descent of [[Great Whale River]] in Northern Quebec, in 1993,<ref>Bowermaster, Jon (May 1993). \"Sacrificial People\u2013Will Quebec's Indians be Driven from Their Land?\". ''Conde Nast Traveller''.</ref> and has made many trips to Patagonia, Chile, to run the Biob\u00edo River, the Futaleuf\u00fa and other whitewater rivers.\n\nIn 2015, he took two of his sons to the [[Yukon]] to visit [[Mount Kennedy]] and run the [[Alsek River]], a whitewater river fed by the [[Alsek Glacier]]. Mount Kennedy had been Canada's highest unclimbed peak, when the Canadian Government named it for the assassinated American president, in 1964.<ref>Jourdan, Michael (August 5, 2015). \"Mountain Tribute to JFK Evoked by Kennedy Trip to Yukon\". ''National Geographic''.</ref> In 1965, his father [[Robert F. Kennedy]] was the first person to climb Mount Kennedy.<ref>Kennedy, Robert (April 9, 1965). \"Our Climb Up Mt. Kennedy\". ''Life''.</ref>\n\n===Marriages and children===\nOn April 3, 1982, Kennedy married Emily Ruth Black (b. 1957), whom he had met at the [[University of Virginia School of Law]].<ref>{{cite news |title = Robert F. Kennedy Jr. Weds Law Classmate |url= https://www.nytimes.com/1982/04/04/us/robert-f-kennedy-jr-weds-law-classmate.html | accessdate =13 January 2020 |work= New York Times |agency= UPI |date =4 April 1982}}</ref> They had two children: Robert Francis \"Bobby\" Kennedy III (b. 1984, married writer, peace activist and former [[Central Intelligence Agency|CIA]] officer Amaryllis Fox) and Kathleen Alexandra Kennedy (b. 1988). The couple separated in 1992 and divorced in 1994.<ref>Shaw, Dan (March 28, 1994). \"Chronicle\". ''The New York Times''.</ref>\n\nOn April 15, 1994, Kennedy married [[Mary Richardson Kennedy|Mary Kathleen Richardson]] (1959\u20132012) aboard a research vessel on the [[Hudson River]].<ref>Brozan, Nadine (April 20, 1994). \"Chronicle\". ''The New York Times''.</ref>  They had four children: Conor Richardson Kennedy (b. 1994), [[Kyra Kennedy|Kyra LeMoyne Kennedy]] (b. 1995), William Finbar \"Finn\" Kennedy (b. 1997), and Aidan Caohman Vieques Kennedy (b. 2001). On May 12, 2010, Kennedy filed for divorce from Mary; three days later she was charged with drunk driving. On May 16, 2012, Mary was found dead in a building on the grounds of her home in [[Mount Kisco, New York]].  The Westchester County Medical Examiner ruled the death to be a [[Suicide by hanging|suicide due to asphyxiation from hanging]].<ref>Hall, Christine. (May 17, 2012). \"Police: Mary Kennedy Committed Suicide\". ''The Bedford Daily Voice''.</ref>\n\nKennedy married his third wife, actress-director [[Cheryl Hines]], on August 2, 2014, at the [[Kennedy Compound|Kennedy compound]] in [[Hyannis Port, Massachusetts]]. They were first introduced by [[Larry David]], whose wife Hines played in the HBO series ''[[Curb Your Enthusiasm]]'' and began dating in 2012.<ref>{{cite news |last1 =Woletz |first1= Bob |title= No Curbs on Their Enthusiasm |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2014/08/03/fashion/weddings/no-curbs-on-their-enthusiasm.html |accessdate =13 January 2020 |issue = New York Times | date = 3 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1= Andrews-Dyer |first1 = Helena |title= Actress Cheryl Hines marries Robert F. Kennedy Jr. at Kennedy family compound in Cape Code |url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/reliable-source/wp/2014/08/03/actress-cheryl-hines-marries-robert-f-kennedy-jr-at-kennedy-family-compound-in-cape-cod |accessdate =13 January 2020 |work = Washington Post |date =3 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Controversies===\nIn the summer of 1970, Kennedy was charged in [[Hyannis, Massachusetts]] for marijuana possession. In August 1971, he was arrested for loitering, also in Hyannis, and pleaded no contest to the charge.<ref>\"[https://www.nytimes.com/1971/08/24/archives/robert-kennedy-17-fined-for-loitering-pleads-no-contest.html Robert Kennedy, 17, Fined for Loitering; Pleads No Contest]\". August 24, 1971. ''New York Times''. {{Webarchive |url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171006161855/http://www.nytimes.com/1971/08/24/archives/robert-kennedy-17-fined-for-loitering-pleads-no-contest.html |date=October 6, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1983, at age 29, Kennedy was arrested in a [[Rapid City, South Dakota]] airport for [[heroin]] possession after a search of his carry-on bag uncovered the drug, following a near overdose in flight.<ref name=\"heroin\">{{cite news |title=Robert Kennedy Jr. Admits He Is Guilty In Possessing Heroin |url = https://www.nytimes.com/1984/02/18/us/robert-kennedy-jr-admits-he-is-guilty-in-possessing-heroin.html |accessdate =13 January 2020 | work = New York Times | date= 18 February 1984}}</ref> Kennedy entered a guilty [[plea]] to Presiding Judge Marshall P. Young, who sentenced him to two years' [[probation]] and 1,500 hours of [[community service]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Kennedy Son Given Probation in Drug Case | url = https://www.nytimes.com/1984/03/17/us/around-the-nation-kennedy-son-givenprobation-in-drug-case.html | accessdate = 13 January 2020 | work = New York Times |date =17 March 1984 }}</ref> Following his arrest, Kennedy entered a drug treatment center and left employment as a government prosecutor.<ref name= \"living-dangerously\">{{cite news |author1 =Mark Leibovich |authorlink1= Mark Leibovich |title = Another Kennedy Living Dangerously |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2006/06/25/fashion/25bobby.html |accessdate=13 January 2020 |work= New York Times |date =25 June 2006}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, Kennedy hired William Wegner to work for Riverkeeper. He was a [[fishery]] scientist and falconer who had been sentenced to five years in prison; he served three years after pleading guilty to federal criminal charges for smuggling bird eggs from Australia.<ref name= \"bird-smuggler\">{{cite news |last1= Pool |first1=Bob |title= Bird Smuggler Sentenced to Prison |url= https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1996-04-02-me-53997-story.html |accessdate= 13 January 2020 |work=Los Angeles Times |date= 2 April 1996}}</ref> In 2000, Robert Boyle, Riverkeeper's founder and former president, fired Wegner, citing his criminal conviction, but Kennedy re-hired Wegner, believing he should be given a second chance. A majority of the Riverkeeper Board supported Kennedy's decision, but seven members joined Boyle in resigning.<ref>{{cite news |last1 =Roberts |first1 =Sam |title =Robert H. Boyle, a Watchdog of the Hudson River, Dies at 88 |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/22/nyregion/robert-h-boyle-founder-of-hudson-riverkeeper.html |accessdate =13 January 2020 |work=New York Times | date =22 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2013, ''The New York Post'' released excerpts from Kennedy's 2001 diary, in which Kennedy described multiple affairs,<ref>{{cite news | url =https://nypost.com/2013/09/08/rfk-jr-s-sex-diary-of-adultery |title = RFK's sex diary: His secret journal of affairs  |date= September 8, 2013 |work = New York Post| accessdate =October 23, 2014 |first1 =Isabel |last1= Vincent| first2 = Melissa| last2= Klein | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20141022041713/http://nypost.com/2013/09/08/rfk-jr-s-sex-diary-of-adultery |archive-date =October 22, 2014 | url-status = live}}</ref> and penned his opinions about public figures.<ref name=\"New York Post\">{{cite news| url= https://nypost.com/2013/09/09/diary-bombshell-rfks-secret-slams-against-al-sharpton-jesse-jackson-and-gov-cuomo | title= Diary bombshell: RFK's slams against Al Sharpton, Jesse Jackson and Gov. Cuomo | date = September 9, 2013| work= New York Post| accessdate = October 23, 2014 | first1 = Isabel |last1 =Vincent | first2= Melissa |last2 = Klein| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141025005337/http://nypost.com/2013/09/09/diary-bombshell-rfks-secret-slams-against-al-sharpton-jesse-jackson-and-gov-cuomo | archive-date = October 25, 2014 |url-status = live}}</ref> Kennedy said the paper had indeed printed his diary.<ref name=\"New York Post\"/>\n\n===Health===\nKennedy suffers from [[spasmodic dysphonia]], which causes his voice to [[:wikt:quaver|quaver]] and makes speech difficult. It is a form of an involuntary movement disorder called [[dystonia]] that affects only the [[larynx]].<ref name= \"voice-disorder\">{{cite news |last1=Cox |first1 = Lauren |title =Kennedy's Voice Draws Attention to Rare Disorder | url= https://abcnews.go.com/Health/story?id=5296702&page=1 |accessdate =13 January 2020 |work =ABC News |date= 7 January 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\nKennedy has authored or edited ten books on subjects such as the environment, science, biography, and American heroes, including two [[bestseller]]s and three children's books. \n*{{cite book |last1=Russel l|first1= Dick |title= Horsemen of the Apocalypse: The Men Who Are Destroying Life on Earth And What it Means for Our Children |publisher= [[Charles Scribner's Sons| Scribner]]|year=2017|location=New York| page= 304|isbn = 9781510721753}}\n*{{cite book |title= Framed: Why Michael Skakel Spent Over a Decade in Prison For a Murder He Didn't Commit | publisher= [[Skyhorse Publishing]]|year=2016| location=New York|page=240|isbn=9781510701779}}\n*{{cite book |title=Thimerosal: Let the Science Speak: The Evidence Supporting the Immediate Removal of Mercury\u2013a Known Neurotoxin\u2013from Vaccines|publisher=[[Skyhorse Publishing]]|year=2014|location=New York|page=224|isbn=978-1632206015 |title-link= Thimerosal}}\n*{{cite book |title=Crimes Against Nature: How George W. Bush and His Corporate Pals Are Plundering the Country and Highjacking Our Democracy|publisher=[[HarperCollins]]|year=2005|location=New York|page=[https://archive.org/details/crimesagainstnat00kenn/page/256 256]|isbn=978-0-06-074687-2|url=https://archive.org/details/crimesagainstnat00kenn/page/256}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Cronin|first1=John |title=The Riverkeepers: Two Activists Fight to Reclaim Our Environment as a Basic Human Right|publisher=[[Charles Scribner's Sons|Scribner]]|year=1997|location=New York|page=[https://archive.org/details/riverkeeperstwoa00cron/page/304 304]|isbn=978-0684839080|url=https://archive.org/details/riverkeeperstwoa00cron/page/304}}\n*{{cite book|title=The Billings Collection|publisher=[[John F. Kennedy Library]]|year=1992|location=Boston|url=https://www.jfklibrary.org/Asset-Viewer/Archives/KLBPP.aspx?f=1}}\n*{{cite book|title=Judge Frank M. Johnson Jr.: A biography|publisher=[[G. P. Putnam's Sons|Putnam]]|year=1978|isbn=978-0-399-12123-4|title-link=Frank Minis Johnson}}\n\n=== Children's books ===\n*{{cite book|title=Robert Smalls: The Boat Thief|publisher=[[Hyperion (publisher)|Hyperion]]|year=2008|location=New York|page=48|isbn=978-1423108023|title-link=Robert Smalls}}\n*{{cite book|title=Robert F. Kennedy Jr.'s American Heroes: The Story of Joshua Chamberlain and the American Civil War|publisher=[[Hyperion (publisher)|Hyperion]]|year=2007|location=New York|page=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9781423107712/page/48 48]|isbn=978-1-4231-0771-2|title-link=Joshua Chamberlain}}\n*{{cite book|author =Dennis Nolan (Illustrator)|title =St. Francis of Assisi: A Life of Joy|publisher=[[Hyperion (publisher)|Hyperion]]|year=2004|isbn=978-0-7868-1875-4|title-link=St. Francis of Assisi}}\n\n=== Selected articles ===\n\nKennedy has penned numerous academic and general interest articles as well as op-eds on oil, coal, green energy, election integrity, politics, the media, falconry, foreign policy, and civil rights. His writing has been published in ''[[The New York Times]]'', ''[[The Washington Post]]'', ''[[Time (magazine)|Time Magazine]]'', ''[[Newsweek]]'', ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', ''[[The Atlantic Monthly]]'', and ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'', among others. Kennedy is also a frequently published travel writer.\n\n* {{cite news |title=Meet the horsemen of our environmental apocalypse |url=https://www.salon.com/2017/06/25/meet-the-horsemen-of-our-environmental-apocalypse |accessdate=13 January 2020 |work=Salon |date=25 June 2017}}\n* {{cite news |title=John F. Kennedy's Vision of Peace |url= https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/politics-news/john-f-kennedys-vision-of-peace-109020 |accessdate=13 January 2020 |work=Rolling Stone |date=20 November 2013}}\n* {{cite news |title=The Next President's First Task [A Manifesto] |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2008/05/rfk_manifesto200805 |accessdate=13 January 2020 |work=Vanity Fair |date=8 December 2009}}\n* {{cite news |title =Robert F. Kennedy Jr. on the Climate Crisis: What Must Be Done |url= https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/politics-news/robert-f-kennedy-jr-on-the-climate-crisis-what-must-be-done-192191 |accessdate =13 January 2020 |work= Rolling Stone |date=28 June 2007}}\n* {{cite news |title=Texas Chainsaw Management |url= https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2007/05/revolvingdoor200705 |accessdate=13 January 2020 |work =Vanity Fair |date=4 April 2007}}\n* {{cite news |title=Deadly Immunity |url= https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/politics-news/deadly-immunity-180037  |accessdate=13 January 2020 |work=Rolling Stone |date= 8 February 2011}}\n*{{cite news |title= The Junk Science of George W. Bush |url=https://www.thenation.com/article/junk-science-george-w-bush/ |accessdate=13 January 2020 |work= The Nation |date=19 February 2004}}<ref name=\"junk\">{{cite news |title=The Junk Science of George W. Bush |url= https://www.thenation.com/article/junk-science-george-w-bush |accessdate=13 January 2020 |work=The Nation |date=19 February 2004}}</ref>\n* {{cite news |title= Crimes Against Nature |url= http://www.maryellenmark.com/text/magazines/rolling%20stone/920S-000-048.html |accessdate=13 January 2020 |work= Rolling Stone |date=11 December 2003}}\n* {{cite news |title=A Miscarriage of Justice |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2003/01/a-miscarriage-of-justice/304759/ |accessdate=13 January 2020 |work=The Atlantic |date=January\u2013February 2003}}\n* {{cite news |title =Why Are We in Vieques? |url= https://www.outsideonline.com/1819831/why-are-we-vieques |accessdate= 13 January 2020 |work=Outside |date=10 January 2001}}\n*August 26, 1992 \u2013 \"Driving Out Conoco Disservice to Rain Forests\". ''The Houston Chronicle''\n\n==Select awards and recognition==\nOver the course of his career, Kennedy has received numerous awards in his name and on behalf of organizations and causes that he has championed.\n\n*2018, The National Trial Lawyers, Mass Tort Trial Team of the Year - for \u201cgroundbreaking case of Dewayne \u201cLee\u201d Johnson v. Monsanto Company\u201d<ref name=\"Millican, Scott\"/>\n*2017, Earth Justice Mountain Heroes<ref>{{cite web|url =https://earthjustice.org/mountain-heroes/robert-f-kennedy-jr |title= Mountain Heroes: Robert F. Kennedy, Jr.|author=|date=May 16, 2012|website =earthjustice.org|accessdate=October 15, 2017|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171012150139/https://earthjustice.org/mountain-heroes/robert-f-kennedy-jr |archive-date=October 12, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> \n*2017, Foro La Region Award for \"La Proteccion de los Recrsos Naturales\"<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.laregion.es/album/ourense/foro-region-robert-kennedy-jr-imagenes/20170515222421708600.html |title = El Foro La Regi\u00f3n sobre la protecci\u00f3n de los recursos naturales, en im\u00e1genes | first= La |last =Regi\u00f3n|date= |website = La Regi\u00f3n| accessdate =October 15, 2017|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20171012100305/http://www.laregion.es/album/ourense/foro-region-robert-kennedy-jr-imagenes/20170515222421708600.html |archive-date = October 12, 2017|url-status= live}}</ref> \n*2017, Moms Across America Healthy Communities Award\n*2014, Stroud Award of Freshwater Excellence<ref>{{cite web|url=https://stroudcenter.org/news/robert-f-kennedy-jr-honored/|title=Robert F. Kennedy, Jr. Honored at Water's Edge Gala - Stroud Water Research Center|author= |date=December 22, 2014|website=stroudcenter.org |accessdate = October 15, 2017| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20171012095347/https://stroudcenter.org/news/robert-f-kennedy-jr-honored | archive-date = October 12, 2017 |url-status= live}}</ref> \n*2009, ''Rolling Stone'' \"100 Agents of Change\"<ref name=\"mercurynews.com\"/> \n*2008, USC Dornsife Sustainability Champion Award<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dornsife.usc.edu/news/stories/477/waterkeeper-alliance-and-robert-f-kennedy-jr-honored | title= Waterkeeper Alliance and Robert F. Kennedy Jr. Honored |author=|date=|website=usc.edu| accessdate= October 15, 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171012095550/https://dornsife.usc.edu/news/stories/477/waterkeeper-alliance-and-robert-f-kennedy-jr-honored |archive-date =October 12, 2017| url-status =live}}</ref> \n*2008, Theodre Gordon Flyfishers Conservation Award<ref name=\"pace.edu\">{{cite web|url = http://www.law.pace.edu/clinic-awards|title=Clinic Awards | author=| date=| website =www.law.pace.edu |accessdate=October 15, 2017 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20171012100249/http://www.law.pace.edu/clinic-awards |archive-date=October 12, 2017 |url-status= live}}</ref> \n*2007, ''Vanity Fair'' \"The Green Team\"<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2006/05/onthecover200605 |title= The Green Team| author=|date=| website= Vanity Fair |accessdate= October 15, 2017 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160726131455/http://www.vanityfair.com/news/2006/05/onthecover200605 |archive-date= July 26, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> \n*2005, William O. Douglas Award, on behalf of the Waterkeeper Alliance<ref>{{cite web|url=http://williamodouglas.org/robert-f-kennedy-jr-on-william-o-douglas |title = Robert F. Kennedy, Jr. on William O. Douglas |author=|date=|website= williamodouglas.org|accessdate=October 15, 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171012104519/http://williamodouglas.org/robert-f-kennedy-jr-on-william-o-douglas | archive-date= October 12, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> \n*2004, Riverkeeper's Environmental Excellence Award\n*2004, Marshall P. Madison Award\n*2003, Professional Resource Award, NY State Council of Trout Unlimited<ref name=\"pace.edu\"/>\n*2001, Distinguished Service Award presented at [[Pace Law School]]'s 25th Anniversary<ref>{{cite web| url= https://newswire.blogs.pace.edu/2001/10/23/25th-anniversary-alumni-leadership-awards-dinner-honors-robert-f-kennedy-jr-the-honorable-terry-jane-ruderman-and-peter-john-sacripanti | title= 25th Anniversary Alumni Leadership Awards Dinner Honors: Robert F. Kennedy, Jr., the Honorable Terry Jane Ruderman, and Peter John Sacripanti  |author =|date =|website =newswire.blogs.pace.edu |accessdate=October 15, 2017| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20171012100343/https://newswire.blogs.pace.edu/2001/10/23/25th-anniversary-alumni-leadership-awards-dinner-honors-robert-f-kennedy-jr-the-honorable-terry-jane-ruderman-and-peter-john-sacripanti |archive-date =October 12, 2017| url-status=live}}</ref> \n*2001, ''Men's Journal'' \"Heroes\" Award<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bizbash.com/a-manly-awards-party-for-mens-journal/new-york/story/891/#.Wa0aT4opBE5| title= A Manly Awards Party for Men's Journal|author=|date=April 13, 2001|website=bizbash.com|accessdate=October 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171012100131/https://www.bizbash.com/a-manly-awards-party-for-mens-journal/new-york/story/891/#.Wa0aT4opBE5|archive-date=October 12, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> \n*2001, Louisiana Environmental Action Award\n*2000, 12th Annual Manhattan Award<ref name=\"pace.edu1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.law.pace.edu/clinic-awards |title=Clinic Awards - Pace Law School| website =www.law.pace.edu| access-date =October 22, 2017|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20171012100249/http://www.law.pace.edu/clinic-awards |archive-date = October 12, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*2000, Jacques Sartisky Peace Award<ref name=\"pace.edu1\"/>\n*2000, New York State Champion of the Environment<ref>{{cite web|url= http://waterkeeper.org/staff-member/robert-f-kennedy-jr |title =Robert F. Kennedy, Jr.| author=|date=|website= Waterkeeper Alliance |accessdate=October 15, 2017| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171012151538/http://waterkeeper.org/staff-member/robert-f-kennedy-jr |archive-date =October 12, 2017 |url-status= live}}</ref> \n*1999, ''[[Time (magazine)|Time Magazine]]''{{'s}} \"Heroes of the Planet\"<ref name=\"mercurynews.com\"/> \n*1999, Aquarium Conservation Award\n*1998, William E. Ricker Resource Conservation Award<ref>{{cite web | url= https://fisheries.org/about/awards-recognition/call-for-award-nominations/william-e-ricker-resource-conservation-award | title= William E. Ricker Resource Conservation Award &#124; American Fisheries Society | access-date=October 12, 2017 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171012101226/https://fisheries.org/about/awards-recognition/call-for-award-nominations/william-e-ricker-resource-conservation-award | archive-date=October 12, 2017 | url-status =live }}</ref> \n*1998, Water Watch Award \u2013 New York National Boat Show Awards, on behalf of the Pace Environmental Litigation Clinic\n*1997, EPA Environmental Quality Award<ref name=\"pace.edu1\"/>\n*1997, The Brave 40 Award from NYC Department of Environmental Conservation<ref name=\"pace.edu1\"/>\n*1997, Thomas Berry Environmental Award, presented to Robert F. Kennedy Jr. and the Pace Environmental Litigation Clinic<ref name=\"auto5\">{{cite web| url= http://www.law.pace.edu/clinic-awards | title=Clinic Awards |website= Pace Law School |access-date=October 12, 2017|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20171012100249/http://www.law.pace.edu/clinic-awards|archive-date=October 12, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> \n*1996, Great Steward of the Hudson Valley - Storm King Award for New York City Watershed Agreement{{citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n*1995, Green Star Award presented by the Environmental Action Coalition<ref name=\"auto5\"/>\n*1991, Eleanor Roosevelt Val-Kill Award<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.midhudsonnews.com/News/2017/October/10/ValKill_awards-10Oct17.html |title = Val-Kill awards to be presented on Sunday|author=|date=|website =www.midhudsonnews.com |accessdate=October 15, 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171012095005/https://www.midhudsonnews.com/News/2017/October/10/ValKill_awards-10Oct17.html |archive-date = October 12, 2017 |url-status =live}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Deadly Immunity]]\n* [[Environmental law]]\n* [[Kennedy family]]\n* [[Waterkeeper Alliance]]\n* [[Vaccines and autism]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category}}\n* [https://law.pace.edu/faculty/robert-kennedy Pace Law School Profile]\n* [https://childrenshealthdefense.org Children's Health Defense]\n\n{{AAR}}\n{{Robert F. Kennedy}}\n{{Kennedy family}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kennedy, Robert F. Jr.}}\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American lawyers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the London School of Economics]]\n[[Category:American biographers]]\n[[Category:American bloggers]]\n[[Category:American conspiracy theorists]]\n[[Category:American environmentalists]]\n[[Category:American legal scholars]]\n[[Category:American male bloggers]]\n[[Category:American male writers]]\n[[Category:American non-fiction environmental writers]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of drug offenses]]\n[[Category:American people of Dutch descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:American political writers]]\n[[Category:American Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:American talk radio hosts]]\n[[Category:Anti-vaccination activists]]\n[[Category:Environmental bloggers]]\n[[Category:Environmental lawyers]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Kennedy family]]\n[[Category:Natural Resources Defense Council people]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Democrats]]\n[[Category:New York (state) lawyers]]\n[[Category:Pace University School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:People with voice disorders]]\n[[Category:Thiomersal and vaccines]]\n[[Category:University of Virginia School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:Washington, D.C. Democrats]]\n[[Category:Writers from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Writers from Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:American Book Award winners]]\n[[Category:Prisoners and detainees of the United States federal government]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American anti-vaccine pseudoscientific activist}}\n{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Robert F. Kennedy Jr.\n|image       = Robert F. Kennedy Jr. by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n|caption     = Kennedy in 2017\n|party       = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]]\n|birth_name  = Robert Francis Kennedy Jr.\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1954|1|17}}\n|birth_place = [[Washington, D.C.]], U.S.\n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|spouse      = {{marriage|Emily Black|1982|1994|reason=divorce}}<br/>{{marriage|[[Mary Richardson Kennedy|Mary Richardson]]|1994|2012|reason=died}}<br/>{{marriage|[[Cheryl Hines]]|2014}}\n|children    = 6 (including [[Kyra Kennedy]])\n|relatives = ''See [[Kennedy family]]''\n|education  = [[Harvard College|Harvard University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br/>[[London School of Economics]]<br/>[[University of Virginia School of Law|University of Virginia]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])<br/>[[Pace University School of Law|Pace University]] ([[Master of Laws|LLM]])\n|parents     = [[Robert F. Kennedy]]<br/>[[Ethel Kennedy|Ethel Skakel]]\n}}\n\n'''Robert Francis Kennedy Jr.''' (born January 17, 1954) is an American environmental attorney, author, and opponent of vaccination. Kennedy is a son of [[Robert F. Kennedy]] and nephew of former president [[John F. Kennedy]]. He is the president of the board of [[Waterkeeper Alliance]], a non-profit environmental group that he helped found in 1999.\n\nFrom 1986 until 2017, Kennedy was a senior attorney for the [[Natural Resources Defense Council|Natural Resources Defense Council (NRDC)]], a non-profit environmental organization. From 1984 until 2017, he was a board member and chief prosecuting attorney for [[Hudson Valley|Hudson]] [[Riverkeeper]].<ref>Agee, J'nelle (March 18, 2017) \"[http://spectrumlocalnews.com/nys/hudson-valley/news/2017/03/17/robert-kennedy-jr-resigns-from-riverkeeper Robert F. Kennedy, Jr. Resigns From Riverkeeper]\". ''Spectrum News'' {{Webarchive |url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171004135637/http://spectrumlocalnews.com/nys/hudson-valley/news/2017/03/17/robert-kennedy-jr-resigns-from-riverkeeper |date=October 4, 2017 }}</ref> For over thirty years, Kennedy has been an adjunct professor of [[Environmental law]] at [[Pace University School of Law]]. Until August 2017, he also held the post as supervising attorney and co-director of Pace Law School's Environmental Litigation Clinic, which he founded in 1987.<ref>Smith, Steve (April 29, 2015). \"[http://news.unl.edu/newsrooms/today/article/rfk-jr-to-address-college-of-law-graduates RFK Jr. to address College of Law graduates]\". ''Nebraska Today''. {{Webarchive |url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171004085140/http://news.unl.edu/newsrooms/today/article/rfk-jr-to-address-college-of-law-graduates |date= October 4, 2017 }}</ref>  He is currently professor [[emeritus]] at Pace.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://law.pace.edu/faculty/robert-f-kennedy-jr+-|title = Faculty |website= Pace Law School|access-date=November 20, 2017|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171201033134/http://law.pace.edu/faculty/robert-f-kennedy-jr+-|archive-date=December 1, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nKennedy co-hosts ''[[Ring of Fire (radio program)|Ring of Fire]]'', a nationally syndicated American radio program, and has written or edited ten books, including two [[The New York Times Best Seller list|''New York Times'' bestsellers]].\n\nHe is a prominent [[Vaccine hesitancy|anti-vaccine]] activist and believes in [[pseudoscience|pseudoscientific]] speculation of a link between [[vaccines and autism]].<ref>{{Cite web| url = https://arstechnica.com/science/2019/07/anti-vaxxers-lose-again-ny-judge-upholds-ban-on-religious-exemptions |title =Prominent anti-vaxxers lose New York court case over religious exemptions|last=Mole|first=Beth |date= 2019-07-12| website= Ars Technica | access-date=2019-11-15 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20191115030802/https://arstechnica.com/science/2019/07/anti-vaxxers-lose-again-ny-judge-upholds-ban-on-religious-exemptions |archive-date= November 15, 2019| url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url = https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/13/us/california-vaccine-bill.html |title = Here Is What Jessica Biel Opposes in California's Vaccine Bill | last = Hassan |first =Adeel|date= 2019-06-13|work=The New York Times |access-date= 2019-11-15| issn= 0362-4331|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20191114205822/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/13/us/california-vaccine-bill.html|archive-date=November 14, 2019| url-status =live}}</ref> Kennedy has denied such characterization.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sciencemag.org/news/2017/01/exclusive-qa-robert-f-kennedy-jr-trumps-proposed-vaccine-commission |title=Exclusive Q&A: Robert F. Kennedy Jr. on Trump's proposed vaccine commission|last=Wadman |first = Meredith|date= 2017-01-10|website=Science|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dispatch.com/opinion/20190627/letter-stronger-testing-required-to-make-vaccines-safe|title= Stronger testing required to make vaccines safe|last=Kennedy Jr.|first=Robert F.|date=2019-06-27|website=The Columbus Dispatch|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nKennedy was born in [[Washington, D.C.]], on January 17, 1954. He is the third of eleven children of Senator and Attorney General [[Robert F. Kennedy]] and [[Ethel Kennedy]].\n\nAdditionally, he is a nephew of [[Joseph P. Kennedy Jr.]], President [[John F. Kennedy]], and Senator [[Ted Kennedy]]. His aunt [[Eunice Kennedy Shriver]] founded [[Special Olympics]], and another aunt, [[Jean Kennedy Smith]], is a former U.S. Ambassador to Ireland.<ref>{{Cite newspaper | url=https://articles.latimes.com/1995-11-26/opinion/op-7471_1_jean-kennedy-smith| title=Los Angeles Times Interview : Jean Kennedy Smith : This Kennedy Returned to Ireland| journal=Los Angeles Times| date=1995-11-26| last1=Tuohy| first1=William| access-date=October 14, 2017 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180405092429/http://articles.latimes.com/1995-11-26/opinion/op-7471_1_jean-kennedy-smith| archive-date=April 5, 2018| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nKennedy grew up at his family's homes in [[McLean, Virginia]], and [[Cape Cod, Massachusetts]].<ref>{{cite book |title =American Values: Lessons I Learned from My Family|first=Robert F. |last=Kennedy Jr. |pages=3\u20138|year=2018|isbn=978-0062845917 |publisher= HarperLuxe}}</ref> He was 9 years old in 1963 when his uncle, President John F. Kennedy, [[Assassination of John F. Kennedy|was assassinated]], and 14 years old in 1968 when his [[Assassination of Robert F. Kennedy|father was assassinated]] while running for president in the [[Democratic Party presidential primaries, 1968|1968 Democratic presidential primaries]].\n\nKennedy learned of his father's shooting when he was at [[Georgetown Preparatory School]], a Jesuit boarding school in North Bethesda, Maryland.<ref>\"Oprah Talks to Bobby Kennedy Jr.\". February 2007. ''O, The Oprah Magazine''</ref> A few hours later, he flew to Los Angeles on vice-president [[Hubert Humphrey|Hubert Humphrey's plane]], along with his elder sister [[Kathleen Kennedy Townsend|Kathleen]] and elder brother [[Joseph P. Kennedy II|Joseph]], and was with his father when he died. Kennedy was a pallbearer in his father's funeral, where he spoke and read excerpts from his father's speeches at the Mass commemorating his death at [[Arlington National Cemetery]].<ref>Storrin, Matt. (June 7, 1969). \"[https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/boston/doc/506180659.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Jun%2007,%201969&author=&pub=Boston%20Globe%20(1960-1979)&edition=&startpage=&desc=Folk%20Mass%20Honors%20RFK Folk Mass Honors RFK]\". ''Boston Globe''.   {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170918202156/https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/boston/doc/506180659.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Jun%2007,%201969&author=&pub=Boston%20Globe%20(1960-1979)&edition=&startpage=&desc=Folk%20Mass%20Honors%20RFK |date =September 18, 2017 }}</ref><ref>Special to The New York Times (June 7, 1970) \"[https://www.nytimes.com/1970/06/07/archives/robert-kennedys-words-sung-in-mass-marking-assassination.html Robert Kennedy's Words Sung In Mass Marking Assassination]\". ''New York Times''. {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171006113141/http://www.nytimes.com/1970/06/07/archives/robert-kennedys-words-sung-in-mass-marking-assassination.html |date=October 6, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nAfter obtaining his high school diploma from the Palfrey Street School in [[Massachusetts]],<ref>{{cite book|title=RFK Jr.: Robert F. Kennedy Jr. and the Dark Side of the Dream|first=Jerry |last=Oppenheimer|pages=129\u2013147|year=2015|isbn=978-1250096661|publisher=St. Martin's Griffin}}</ref> Kennedy continued his education at [[Harvard University|Harvard]] and the [[London School of Economics]], graduating from [[Harvard College]] in 1976 with a Bachelor of Arts in American History and Literature. He went on to earn a [[Juris Doctor]] from the [[University of Virginia School of Law|University of Virginia]] and a [[Master of Laws]] from [[Pace University School of Law|Pace University]].<ref>[http://www.backbonecampaign.org/cabinet/nominee.cfm?ID=62 The Backbone Cabinet \u2013 A Progressive Cabinet Roster] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929042337/http://www.backbonecampaign.org/cabinet/nominee.cfm?ID=62 |date=September 29, 2007 }}, backbonecampaign.org</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\nIn 1983, Kennedy was an Assistant District Attorney in Manhattan. In 1984, Kennedy joined Riverkeeper as an investigator, and was promoted to senior prosecuting attorney<ref name=\"auto4\">Cronin, John; Kennedy Jr., Robert F. (1997). ''The Riverkeepers: Two Activists Fight to Reclaim Our Environment as a Basic Human Right''. New York: Scribner. p. 304. {{ISBN|0684839083}}.</ref>  when he was admitted to the New York bar in 1985.<ref>Dunlap, David W. and Perlez, Jane (June 4, 1985). \"[https://www.nytimes.com/1985/06/04/nyregion/new-york-day-by-day-a-quiet-victory-for-robert-f-kennedy-jr.html A Quiet Victory For Robert F. Kennedy Jr]\". ''The New York Times''.{{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171007070349/http://www.nytimes.com/1985/06/04/nyregion/new-york-day-by-day-a-quiet-victory-for-robert-f-kennedy-jr.html |date=October 7, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nKennedy is an environmental law specialist and partner in the law firms of Morgan & Morgan PA and of Kennedy & Madonna, LLP,<ref>Slansky, Dov (April 01, 2016). \"Robert F. Kennedy, Jr. and Kevin J. Madonna Join Morgan & Morgan\". PRWEB.</ref> and is an advocate for environmental justice.\n\nThrough litigation, lobbying, teaching, and public campaigns and activism, Kennedy has advocated for the protection of waterways, indigenous rights, and renewable energy.<ref>Little, Amanda (July 14, 2004). \"An interview with Robert F. Kennedy Jr., environmental advocate and Bush basher\". Grist.org. http://grist.org/article/griscom-kennedy/ {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171007120150/http://grist.org/article/griscom-kennedy/ |date=October 7, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2018 the National Trial Lawyers Association awarded Kennedy and his trial team Trial Team of the Year for their work winning a $289 million jury verdict in Dewayne \"Lee\" Johnson v Monsanto.<ref name=\"Millican, Scott\">{{cite web|url=https://trofire.com/2019/03/04/ring-of-fires-rfk-jr-wins-award-for-monsanto-trial/|title=Ring of Fire's RFK Jr. Wins Award for Monsanto Trial|author=Millican, Scott|date=March 4, 2019|website =trofire.com|accessdate=March 5, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190305115249/https://trofire.com/2019/03/04/ring-of-fires-rfk-jr-wins-award-for-monsanto-trial |archive-date=March 5, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Riverkeeper===\nKennedy litigated and supervised environmental enforcement lawsuits on the east coast estuaries on behalf of Hudson Riverkeeper and the [[Soundkeeper|Long Island Soundkeeper]],<ref>\"Our core mission: Environmental enforcement\". 2016. ''Riverkeeper Journal''.</ref> where he was also a board member. Long Island Soundkeeper brought numerous lawsuits against cities and industries along the Connecticut and New York coastlines.<ref>Gordon, Maggie (April 2, 2014). \"[https://www.stamfordadvocate.com/news/article/Soundkeeper-sues-state-in-Stamford-boatyard-battle-5371462.php Soundkeeper sues state in Stamford boatyard battle]\". ''Stamford Advocate''.</ref>  In 1986, Kennedy won a landmark case against Remington Arms Trap and Skeet Gun Club in [[Stratford, Connecticut]], that ended the practice of shooting lead shot into Long Island Sound.<ref>777 F. Supp. 173 (1981) ''Connecticut Coastal Fisherman's Association v. Remington Arms Company, Inc. and E.I. Dupont DeNemours and Company''. Civ. No. B-87-250 (EBB). United States District Court, D. Connecticut. September 11, 1991. Justia US Law.</ref>  Kennedy also filed federal lawsuits to close the Pelham Bay landfill and the New York Athletic clubs, arguing that those facilities were interfering with public use of Long Island Sound.<ref>Venezia, Todd (July 5, 2005). \"Bx. Dump Poisoned, Killed Kids \u2013 Now City Must Pay: Residents\". New York Post.</ref>  On the Hudson, Kennedy brought a series of lawsuits against municipalities, including New York City, to properly treat sewage, and against industries, including, [[Consolidated Edison]], [[General Electric]] and [[Exxon]], to stop discharging pollution and to clean up legacy contamination.<ref>Navasky, Bruno (August 11, 2016). \"[https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2016/08/robert-f-kennedy-jr-on-the-environment-election-and-donald-trump Robert F. Kennedy Jr. On The Environment, The Election, And A 'Dangerous' Donald Trump]\". ''Vanity Fair''.</ref>\n\nIn 1995, Kennedy advocated for repeal of the anti-environmental legislation during the 104th Congress.<ref name=\"auto\">Werth, Barry (May 2, 2004). \"[https://www.outsideonline.com/1886331/somewhere-down-crazy-river Somewhere Down the Crazy River]\". ''Outside''.</ref> In 1997, Kennedy worked with John Cronin to write ''The Riverkeepers'', a history of the early Riverkeepers and a primer for the Waterkeeper movement.<ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n\nDrawing on his experience investigating and prosecuting polluters on behalf of the Waterkeepers, Kennedy has written extensively about environmental law enforcement.<ref name=\"watershed\">{{cite news |last1 =Worth |first1=Robert |title= Watershed Warrior |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2001/07/01/nyregion/watershed-warrior.html |accessdate=13 January 2020 |work= New York Times |date=1 July 2001}}</ref>\n\n===Pace Environmental Litigation Clinic===\nIn 1987, Kennedy founded the Environmental Litigation Clinic at Pace University School of Law, where for three decades he was the clinic's supervising attorney and co-director, and as Clinical Professor of Law.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.law.pace.edu/pace-environmental-litigation-clinic|title=Pace Environmental Litigation Clinic - Pace Law School|author=|date=|website=www.law.pace.edu|accessdate=October 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171013103626/http://www.law.pace.edu/pace-environmental-litigation-clinic|archive-date=October 13, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>  Kennedy obtained a special order from the New York State Court of Appeals that permitted his 10 clinic students\u2013second- and third-year law students\u2013to practice law and to try cases against Hudson River polluters in state and federal court, under the supervision of Kennedy and his co-director, Professor Karl Coplan. The clinic's full-time clients are Riverkeeper and Long Island Soundkeeper.<ref name=\"oregon\">Kennedy Jr., Robert F., Solow, Steven P. (1993). \"Environmental Litigation as Clinical Education: A Case Study\". ''University of Oregon Journal of Environmental Law and Litigation'' Volume 8</ref>\n\nThe clinic has prosecuted numerous governments and companies for polluting Long Island Sound and the Hudson River and its tributaries.<ref>\"A conversation with the authors of 'The Riverkeepers: Two Activists Fight to Reclaim Our Environment as a Basic Human Right'\". November 10, 1997. Charlie Rose.</ref>  The clinic argued cases to expand citizen access to the shoreline, and won hundreds of settlements for the Hudson Riverkeeper.<ref>Cronin, John and Kennedy Jr., Robert F. (July 26, 1997). \"It's Our River \u2013 Let Us Get to It\". The New York Times</ref>  Kennedy and his students also sued dozens of municipal waste-water treatment plants to force compliance with the [[Clean Water Act]].<ref name=\"oregon\"/> In 2010, a Pace lawsuit forced [[ExxonMobil]] to clean up tens of millions of gallons of oil from legacy refinery spills in Newtown Creek in Brooklyn, New York.<ref>Brown, Kim (July 8, 2004). \"ExxonMobil Sued Over 55-Acre Oil Spill In Newtown Creek\". ''Queens Chronicle''.</ref>\n\nOn April 11, 2001, ''[[Men's Journal]]'' recognized Kennedy with its \"Heroes\" Award for his creation of the Pace Environmental Litigation Clinic.<ref>Kaydo, Chad (April 13, 2001). \"A Manly Awards Party for ''[[Men's Journal]]''\". BizBash.</ref>  Kennedy and his Pace Environmental Litigation Clinic received other awards for successful legal work cleaning up the environment.<ref>Pace Environmental Litigation Clinic. \"Clinic Awards\". Pace Law.</ref>  The Pace Clinic became a model for similar environmental law clinics throughout the country including Rutgers,<ref>Rutgers School of Law Environmental Law Clinic. \"About this Organization\". Justia Lawyers.</ref>  Golden Gate, UCLA,<ref>Environmental Law Courses and Clinics. UCLA Law.</ref>  Widener,<ref>Environmental Law Clinic. Widener Environmental Law Center. Widener Law.</ref> and Boalt Hall at Berkeley.<ref>Environmental Law Clinic. Berkeley Law.</ref>\n\n===Waterkeepers Alliance===\nIn June 1999, as Riverkeeper's success on the Hudson began inspiring the creation of Waterkeepers across North America, Kennedy and a few dozen Riverkeepers gathered in Southampton, Long Island, to found the Waterkeeper Alliance, which is now the umbrella group for the 344 licensed Waterkeeper programs<ref>Gallay, Paul. May 3, 2018. \u201cChina enlists local groups in environmental enforcement push\u201c. Waterkeeper.org.</ref> located in 44 countries.<ref>Yaggi, Marc, Waterkeeper Alliance. August 2, 2018. \u201cLet Our Rivers Run Free: A Global Look at How Dams are Destroying our Waterways\u201d. Waterkeeper Magazine</ref> As President of the Alliance, Kennedy oversees its legal, membership, policy and fundraising programs. The Alliance states that it is dedicated to promoting \"swimmable, fishable, drinkable waterways, worldwide,\"<ref>\"Robert F. Kennedy, Jr. Honored at Water's Edge Gala\". (2014). Stroudcenter.org.</ref> and is also a clearinghouse, approving new Keeper programs and licensing use of the trademarked \"Waterkeeper,\" \"Riverkeeper,\" \"Soundkeeper,\" \"Lakekeeper,\" \"Baykeeper,\" \"Bayoukeeper,\" \"Canalkeeper,\" \"Coastkeeper,\" etc. names.<ref>Wilke, Chris (March 19, 2012) \"The Clean Water Act \u2013 A Story of Activism and Change\". Read the Dirt.</ref>\n\nKennedy and his environmental work have been the focus of several films including ''The Hudson Riverkeepers'' (1998)<ref>\"The Hudson Riverkeepers (1998)\". IMDb.</ref> and ''The Waterkeepers'' (2000),<ref>\"The Waterkeepers (TV Movie 2000)\". IMDb.</ref> both directed by Les Guthman. In 2008, he appeared in the [[IMAX]] documentary film ''[[Grand Canyon Adventure: River at Risk]]'', riding the length of the [[Grand Canyon]] in a wooden dory with his daughter Kick and with anthropologist [[Wade Davis (anthropologist)|Wade Davis]].<ref>\"Grand Canyon Adventure: River at Risk (2008)\". IMDb.</ref>\n\n===New York City Watershed Agreement===\nBeginning in 1991, Kennedy represented environmentalists and New York City watershed consumers in a series of lawsuits against New York City, New York State, and upstate watershed polluters. Kennedy authored a series of articles and reports<ref>Gordon, David K. and Kennedy, Jr., Robert F. (September 1991). \"The Legend of City Water: Recommendations For Rescuing the New York City Water Supply\". The Hudson Riverkeeper Fund.</ref><ref>Kennedy Jr., Robert F. (August 22, 1989). \"New York City's Water: Down the Drain\". ''The New York Times''.</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www1.nyc.gov/assets/planning/download/pdf/about/cpc/990237.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=October 14, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929044431/http://www1.nyc.gov/assets/planning/download/pdf/about/cpc/990237.pdf |archive-date=September 29, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> alleging that New York State was abdicating its responsibility to protect the water repository and supply. In 1996, he helped orchestrate the $1.2 billion New York City Watershed Agreement, which ''[[New York Magazine]]'' recognized in its cover story, \"The Kennedy Who Matters\".<ref>Wechsler, Pat (Nov 27, 1995). \"The Kennedy Who Matters\". ''New York Magazine''.</ref>  This agreement, which Kennedy negotiated on behalf of environmentalists and New York City watershed consumers, is regarded as an international model in stakeholder consensus negotiations and sustainable development.<ref>Schneeweiss, Jonathan (1997). \"Watershed Protection Strategies: A Case Study of the New York City Watershed in Light of the 1996 Amendments to the Safe Drinking Water Act\". 8 Vill. ''Environmental Law Journal'' 77.</ref>\n\n===Kennedy & Kevin Madonna===\n[[File:R.F.K._jr_2000.jpg|thumb|Kennedy in 2000]]\n\nIn 2000, Kennedy and environmental lawyer Kevin Madonna founded the [[environmental law]] firm Kennedy & Madonna, LLP, to represent private [[plaintiffs]] against polluters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kennedy-madonna-1zcf.squarespace.com/team/|title=Team|author=|date=|website=Kennedy & Madonna, LLP| accessdate=October 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929001322/http://kennedy-madonna-1zcf.squarespace.com/team/|archive-date=September 29, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The firm litigates environmental contamination cases on behalf of individuals, non-profit organizations, school districts, public water suppliers, Indian tribes, municipalities and states. In 2001, Kennedy & Madonna organized a team of prestigious plaintiff law firms to challenge pollution from industrial pork and poultry production.<ref>\"Farmers Worried by Suits Targeting Hog Producers\". January 7, 2001. ''Des Moines Register''. P.9.</ref>  In 2004, the firm was part of a legal team that secured a $70 million settlement for property owners in Pensacola, Florida whose properties were contaminated by chemicals from an adjacent [[Superfund]] site.<ref>\"ConocoPhillips agrees to $70M settlement for former Fla. facility\". April 7, 2004 EENews.net.</ref>\n\nKennedy & Madonna is profiled in the 2010 HBO documentary ''Mann v. Ford''<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1498566/ \"Mann v. Ford\"] (2010). IMDb.</ref> that chronicles four years of litigation brought by the firm on behalf of the [[Ramapough Mountain Indians|Ramapough Mountain Indian Tribe]] against the [[Ford Motor Company]] over the dumping of toxic waste on tribal lands in northern New Jersey.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hbo.com/documentaries/mann-v-ford/synopsis.html|title=Mann v. Ford: Synopsis|website=HBO| accessdate=October 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171006145520/http://www.hbo.com/documentaries/mann-v-ford/synopsis.html|archive-date=October 6, 2017|url-status=dead |df=mdy-all}}</ref>  In addition to a monetary settlement for the tribe, the lawsuit contributed to the community's land being re-listed on the federal Superfund list, the first time in the nation's history that a de-listed site was re-listed.<ref>Strunsky, Steve (October 14, 2006). \"[https://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/14/nyregion/nyregionspecial2/15njringwood.html Superfund Site Is Relisted, and Inquiry Begins]\". ''New York Times''.</ref>  In 2007 Kennedy was one of three finalists nominated as \"Trial Lawyer of the Year\" by Public Justice for his role in the $396 million jury verdict against [[DuPont]] for contamination from its [[Spelter]], West Virginia zinc plant.<ref>\"DuPont Fined $196.2M In Class-Action Suit\". October 19, 2007. CBSNews.com.</ref> In 2017, the firm was part of the trial team that secured a $670 million settlement on behalf of over 3,000 residents from Ohio and West Virginia whose drinking water was contaminated with the toxic chemical, C8, which was released into the environment by [[DuPont]] in [[Parkersburg]], West Virginia.<ref>Rinehart, Earl (February 13, 2017). \"DuPont to pay $670 million to settle C8 lawsuits\". ''The Columbus Dispatch''.</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Kennedy became counsel to the Morgan & Morgan PA|Morgan & Morgan P.A. law firm.<ref>{{cite web | url= https://www.forthepeople.com/attorneys/robert-f-kennedy-jr/ | title=Attorney Robert F. Kennedy, Jr | access-date=October 14, 2017 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929001139/https://www.forthepeople.com/attorneys/robert-f-kennedy-jr/ | archive-date=September 29, 2017 | url-status=live }}</ref>  The partnership arose from the two firms' successful collaboration on the case against SoCalGas Company following the [[Aliso Canyon gas leak]] in California.<ref>Cruz, Nancy (February 18, 2016) \"Porter Ranch Gas Leak With Attorney Robert F. Kennedy\". KTLA5.</ref>  In 2017, Kennedy and his partners sued Monsanto in federal court in San Francisco, on behalf of plaintiffs seeking to recover damages for [[non-Hodgkin's lymphoma]], that, the plaintiffs allege, were a result of exposure to Monsanto's [[glyphosate]]-based herbicide, Roundup. Kennedy and his team also filed a class action lawsuit against [[Monsanto]] for failing to warn consumers about the dangers allegedly posed by exposure to Roundup.<ref>Stecker, Tiffany (June 29, 2017). \"Monsanto's Foes Are Branching Out\". Environment, Health & Safety.</ref> In September 2018, Kennedy and his partners filed a class-action lawsuit against [[Columbia Gas of Massachusetts]] alleging negligence following [[Merrimack Valley gas explosions|gas explosions]] in three towns north of Boston. Of Columbia Gas, Kennedy said \u201cas they build new miles of pipe, the same company is ignoring its existing infrastructure, which we now know is eroding and is dilapidated.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://gazette.com/mass-families-file-class-action-days-after-gas-explosions/article_f1b671b8-bc7c-11e8-ae39-4787469086e9.html | title=Mass. Families file class action days after gas explosions | access-date=October 14, 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181014091538/https://gazette.com/mass-families-file-class-action-days-after-gas-explosions/article_f1b671b8-bc7c-11e8-ae39-4787469086e9.html | archive-date=October 14, 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Cleantech and renewable energy infrastructure entrepreneurship===\n\nIn 1998, Kennedy, Chris Bartle and John Hoving created a [[Bottled water|bottled-water]] company, Keeper Springs, which donated all of its profits to Waterkeeper Alliance.<ref>{{cite news |author1= Patricia Winters Lauro |title=Robert F. Kennedy Jr. is pushing supermarkets to sell a new brand of bottled water, with a twist |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/06/03/business/media-business-advertising-robert-f-kennedy-jr-pushing-supermarkets-sell-new.html |accessdate= 13 January 2020 |work= New York Times |date=3 June 1999}}</ref> In 2013, Kennedy and his partner sold the brand to [[Nestl\u00e9]] in exchange for a donation to local Waterkeepers.<ref>\"Nestle Waters Announces Partnership with Waterkeeper Alliance\". May 22, 2014. Nestle Waters.</ref>\n\nKennedy was a venture partner and senior advisor at [[VantagePoint Capital Partners]], one of the world's largest [[Clean technology|cleantech]] [[venture capital]] firms. Among other activities, VantagePoint was the original and largest pre-[[IPO]] institutional investor in [[Tesla, Inc.|Tesla]]. VantagePoint also backed BrightSource Energy and Solazyme, amongst others. Kennedy is a board member and counselor to several of Vantage Point's portfolio companies in the water and energy space, including Ostara, a Vancouver-based company that markets the technology to remove [[phosphorus]] and other excessive nutrients from [[wastewater]], transforming otherwise pollution directly into high-grade fertilizer.<ref>Wesoff, Eric (May 31, 2012) \"[https://www.greentechmedia.com/articles/read/ostara-nutrient-recovery-wins-14-5m-from-vantagepoint-et-al Ostara Nutrient Recovery Wins $14.5M From VantagePoint et al.]\". ''Greentech Media''.</ref>  He is also a senior advisor to Starwood Energy Group, and has played a key role in a number of the firm's investments.<ref>Wesoff, Eric (October 07, 2015) \"Flow Battery Funding: Vionx Teams With Siemens, UTC, 3M, Starwood and Jabil\". ''Greentech Media''.</ref>\n\nHe is on the board of Vionx, a [[Massachusetts]]-based utility scale [[vanadium flow battery]] systems manufacturer. On October 5, 2017, Vionx, [[National Grid plc|National Grid]] and the [[US Department of Energy]] completed the installation of advanced flow batteries at [[Holy Name Central Catholic High School|Holy Name High School]] in the city of [[Worcester, Massachusetts]]. The collaboration also includes [[Siemens]] and the [[United Technologies|United Technologies Research Center]] and constitutes one of the largest energy storage facilities in Massachusetts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20171005006381/en/Vionx-National-Grid-Department-Energy-Complete-Installation| title=Vionx, National Grid, and US Department of Energy Complete Installation of one of the World's Most Advanced Flow Batteries at Holy Name High School, Worcester, MA|website =www.businesswire.com|date=2017-10-05|access-date=October 15, 2017|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171016070018/http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20171005006381/en/Vionx-National-Grid-Department-Energy-Complete-Installation |archive-date=October 16, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nKennedy is a Partner in ColorZen, which offers a turnkey cotton fiber pre-treatment solution that reduces water usage and toxic discharges in the cotton dying process.<ref>Hilburn, Rachel Lewis (June 3, 2016). \"CoastLine: Robert F. Kennedy, Jr. on the Origin of CAFOs, Environmental Justice\". WHQR.</ref>\n\nKennedy was a co-owner and Director of the [[smart grid]] company Utility Integration Solutions (UISol),<ref>\"Robert F. Kennedy, Jr. Joins UISOL Board of Directors\". August 25, 2010. McDonnell Group.</ref>  which was acquired by [[Alstom]]. He is presently a co-owner and Director of GridBright, the market-leading grid management specialist.<ref>\"Robert F. Kennedy, Jr. joins Board of Directors\". November 1, 2016. GridBright.com.</ref>\n\nIn October 2011, Kennedy co-founded ''EcoWatch'', an environmental news site. He resigned from the board of directors in January 2018.<ref>Spear, Stefanie (November 02, 2011). \"EcoWatch and Waterkeeper Launch News Website\". EcoWatch.</ref>\n\n===Minority and poor communities===\nIn his first case as an environmental attorney, Kennedy represented the [[NAACP]] in a lawsuit against a proposal to build a garbage transfer station in a minority neighborhood in [[Ossining, New York (village)|Ossining, New York]].<ref>Melvin, Tessa (April 7, 1991) \"[https://www.nytimes.com/1991/04/07/nyregion/expanded-recycling-site-upsets-an-ossining-neighborhood.html Expanded Recycling Site Upsets an Ossining Neighborhood]\". ''New York Times''. {{Webarchive|url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171016021632/http://www.nytimes.com/1991/04/07/nyregion/expanded-recycling-site-upsets-an-ossining-neighborhood.html |date =October 16, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1987, he successfully sued [[Westchester County, New York|Westchester County]], New York, to reopen the [[Croton Point Park]], which was heavily used primarily by poor and minority communities from [[the Bronx]].<ref>Reed, Susan (July 2, 1990). \"[http://people.com/archive/polluters-beware-riverkeeper-john-cronin-patrols-the-hudson-and-pursues-those-who-foul-its-waters-vol-33-no-26 Polluters, Beware! Riverkeeper John Cronin Patrols the Hudson and Pursues Those Who Foul Its Waters]\". ''People''. {{Webarchive|url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171016014316/http://people.com/archive/polluters-beware-riverkeeper-john-cronin-patrols-the-hudson-and-pursues-those-who-foul-its-waters-vol-33-no-26 |date =October 16, 2017 }}</ref> He then forced the reopening of the [[Pelham Bay Park]] in the [[Bronx]], which New York City had closed to the public and converted to a police firing range.<ref name=\"auto4\"/> Kennedy also led a battle to stop a plan to sell Washington, D.C.'s [[Kingman Island]]\u2014a rare piece of [[National Park Service]] property in a minority neighborhood\u2014to a private developer. In 2004, Kennedy and Riverkeeper successfully sued Exxon to clean up a large oil spill on [[Newton Creek]] in [[Greenpoint, Brooklyn]].<ref>Confessore, Nicholas (November 1, 2005). \"[https://www.nytimes.com/2005/11/01/nyregion/an-old-oil-spill-divides-a-brooklyn-neighborhood.html An Old Oil Spill Divides a Brooklyn Neighborhood]\". ''The New York Times''. {{Webarchive| url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171016021714/http://www.nytimes.com/2005/11/01/nyregion/an-old-oil-spill-divides-a-brooklyn-neighborhood.html |date= October 16, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nKennedy has argued that poor communities shoulder the disproportionate burden of environmental pollution.<ref>Hilburn, Rachel Lewis (Jun 3, 2016). \"[http://whqr.org/post/coastline-robert-f-kennedy-jr-origin-cafos-environmental-justice#stream/0 CoastLine: Robert F. Kennedy, Jr. on the Origin of CAFOs, Environmental Justice]\". WHQR.org. {{Webarchive| url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171016014708/http://whqr.org/post/coastline-robert-f-kennedy-jr-origin-cafos-environmental-justice#stream/0 |date = October 16, 2017 }}</ref> Speaking at the 2016 [[South by Southwest|SXSW]] Eco environment conference in [[Austin, Texas]], he said, \"Polluters always choose the soft target of poverty\", noting that [[Chicago]]'s [[South Side, Chicago|south side]] has the highest concentration of toxic waste dumps in America.<ref>Wang, Ucilia (October 10, 2016) \"[https://www.theguardian.com/sustainable-business/2016/oct/10/robert-f-kennedy-jr-sxsw-eco-climate-change-big-business-economic-policy Robert F Kennedy Jr takes big business to task over pollution at SXSW Eco]\". ''The Guardian''. {{Webarchive|url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171016013920/https://www.theguardian.com/sustainable-business/2016/oct/10/robert-f-kennedy-jr-sxsw-eco-climate-change-big-business-economic-policy |date = October 16, 2017 }}</ref> Furthermore, he added that 80 percent of \"uncontrolled toxic waste dumps\" can be found in black neighborhoods, with the largest site in the United States being in [[Emelle, Alabama]], which is 90 percent black.<ref>Nirenberg, Michael Lee (May 23, 2017). \"[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/conversation-with-robert-kennedy-jr_us_59239362e4b0b28a33f62f03 Conversation with Robert F. Kennedy Jr.]\" ''Huffpost''</ref>\n\n===International and indigenous rights===\nStarting in 1985, Kennedy helped develop the [[Natural Resources Defense Council]] (NRDC)'s international program for environmental, energy, and [[human rights]], traveling to Canada and Latin America to assist indigenous tribes in protecting their homelands and opposing large-scale energy and extractive projects in remote wilderness areas.<ref>Brancaccio, David (January 21, 2005). \"[http://www.pbs.org/now/science/kennedy.html Science and Health: Robert F. Kennedy, Jr.]\". ''PBS NOW''. {{Webarchive| url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171019215936/http://www.pbs.org/now/science/kennedy.html |date= October 19, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1990, Kennedy assisted the [[Pehuenche]] Indians in Chile in a partially successful campaign to stop the construction of a series of dams on Chile's iconic [[Biob\u00edo River]]. That campaign derailed all but one of the proposed dams.<ref>Bowermaster, Jon.  (November 1992). \"[http://www.earthriver.com/library/conservation/11-conservation/town-and-country Last Run Down the Bio Bio]\". ''Town and Country Travel''.  {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171019220247/http://www.earthriver.com/library/conservation/11-conservation/town-and-country |date=October 19, 2017 }}</ref> Beginning in 1992, he assisted the [[Cree]] Indians of northern Quebec in their campaign against [[Hydro-Qu\u00e9bec]] to halt construction of some 600 proposed dams on eleven rivers in [[James Bay]].<ref>Clayton, Mark (April 20, 1994). \"[https://www.csmonitor.com/1994/0420/20042.html Cree Chief Wins Environmental Prize For Anti-Dam Effort]\". ''The Christian Science Monitor''. {{Webarchive| url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171019215821/https://www.csmonitor.com/1994/0420/20042.html |date= October 19, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1993, Kennedy and NRDC, working with the indigenous rights organization [[Cultural Survival]], clashed with other American environmental groups in a dispute about the rights of Indians to govern their own lands in the [[Oriente (Ecuador)|Oriente]] region of Ecuador.<ref name=\"auto6\">Kane, Joe (September 27, 1993). \"[https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/1993/09/27/with-spears-from-all-sides With Spears from All Sides]\". ''The New Yorker''. {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171019220608/https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/1993/09/27/with-spears-from-all-sides |date =October 19, 2017 }}</ref> Kennedy represented the [[CONFENIAE]], a confederation of Indian peoples, in negotiation with the American oil company [[Conoco]] to limit oil development in Ecuadorian Amazon and, at the same time, obtain benefits from resource extraction for Amazonian tribes.<ref name=\"auto6\"/> Kennedy was a vocal critic of [[Texaco]] for its previous record for polluting the Ecuadoran Amazon.<ref>Kennedy Jr., Robert F. (1991). Foreword for ''Amazon Crude'' by Judith Kimerling. Published by Natural Resource Defense Council. February 19, 1991. p.131. {{ISBN|0960935851}}.</ref>\n\nFrom 1993 to 1999, Kennedy worked with five [[Vancouver Island]] Indian tribes in their campaign to end industrial [[logging]] by [[MacMillan Bloedel]] in [[Clayoquot Sound]], [[British Columbia]].<ref>Kennedy Jr., Robert F. (1995). Foreword for ''Clayoquot Mass Trials: Defending the Rainforest'' by Ronald MacIsaac and Anne Champagne (editors), published by New Society Publisher, February 1995, p.208. {{ISBN|0865713200}}.</ref>\n\nIn 1996, Kennedy met with Cuban President [[Fidel Castro]] to persuade the leader to halt his plans to construct a nuclear power plant at [[Juragu\u00e1]].<ref>Rohter, Larry (February 19, 1996). \"[https://www.nytimes.com/1996/02/19/world/kennedy-castro-encounter-touched-by-history.html Kennedy-Castro Encounter Touched by History]\". ''The New York Times''.  {{Webarchive| url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171019221317/http://www.nytimes.com/1996/02/19/world/kennedy-castro-encounter-touched-by-history.html |date= October 19, 2017 }}</ref> During a lengthy latenight encounter, Castro reminisced about Kennedy's father and uncle, speculating that U.S. relations with Cuba would have been far better had President Kennedy not been assassinated.<ref>Rohter, Larry (February 25, 1996). \"[https://www.nytimes.com/1996/02/25/weekinreview/february-18-24-meeting-across-an-old-breach.html February 18\u201324; Meeting Across an Old Breach]\". ''The New York Times''. {{Webarchive|url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171019221730/http://www.nytimes.com/1996/02/25/weekinreview/february-18-24-meeting-across-an-old-breach.html  |date= October 19, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nBetween 1996 and 2000, Kennedy and NRDC helped Mexican commercial fishermen to halt [[Mitsubishi]]'s proposal to build a salt facility in the [[Laguna San Ignacio]], a known area in Baja where [[gray whale]]s bred, and nursed their calves.<ref>Smith, Matt (November 28th, 2001). \"[http://www.sfweekly.com/news/the-unlikely-environmentalists The Unlikely Environmentalists]\". ''SFWeekly''. {{Webarchive|url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171019220231/http://www.sfweekly.com/news/the-unlikely-environmentalists |date= October 19, 2017 }}</ref> Kennedy wrote extensively against the project, and took the campaign to Japan, meeting with the Japanese Prime Minister [[Keizo Obuchi]].<ref>Kennedy Jr., Robert F. (December 3, 1998). \"Rubbing Salt in the World Heritage Plan\". ''Japan Times''</ref>\n\nIn 2000, he assisted local environmental activists to stop proposals by Chaffin Light, a real estate developer, and U.S. engineering giant [[Bechtel]] from building a large hotel and resort development that, Kennedy argued, threatened [[coral reef]]s and public beaches used extensively by local Bahamians, at Clifton Bay, [[New Providence]] Island.<ref>Roberts, Bradley, MP, PLP (November 20, 2005). \"[http://reearth.org/index.php?p=n&sectid=4&subcat=38&aid=107 Bradley Roberts on Clifton]\". Address to Bahamas House of Assembly. {{Webarchive |url = https://web.archive.org/web/20171020002712/http://reearth.org/index.php?p=n&sectid=4&subcat=38&aid=107 |date =October 20, 2017 }}</ref> Following this, the new Bahamian government designated the area a Heritage Park.{{citation needed| date= October 2017}}\n\nKennedy was one of the early editors of ''[[Indian Country Today]]'', North America's largest [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Native American]] newspaper.<ref>Kennedy Jr., Robert F. (November 29, 2016). \"[https://www.ecowatch.com/kennedy-dakota-access-pipeline-2118593345.html?page=2 'I'll See You at Standing Rock']\". ''EcoWatch''. {{Webarchive| url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171020032256/https://www.ecowatch.com/kennedy-dakota-access-pipeline-2118593345.html?page=2 |date=October 20, 2017 }}</ref> He helped lead the opposition to the damming of the [[Futaleuf\u00fa River]] in the [[Patagonia]] region of Chile.<ref>Schaffer, Grayson (August 30, 2016). \"[https://www.outsideonline.com/2110076/chiles-best-whitewater-rivers-wont-be-dammed-now Chile's Best Whitewater Rivers Won't Be Damned \u2013 For Now]\". ''Outside''. {{Webarchive| url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171019220353/https://www.outsideonline.com/2110076/chiles-best-whitewater-rivers-wont-be-dammed-now |date = October 19, 2017 }}</ref> In 2016, citing the pressure precipitated by the Futaleuf\u00fa Riverkeeper's campaign against the dams, the Spanish power company, [[Endesa]], which owned the right to dam the river, reversed its decision and relinquished all claims to the Futaleuf\u00fa.<ref>Kennedy Jr., Robert F. (September 12, 2016). \"[https://www.ecowatch.com/futaleufu-whitewater-rafting-2002171427.html 20 Year David and Goliath Fist Fight Saves Patagonia's Futaleuf\u00fa]\". ''EcoWatch''. {{Webarchive| url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171007221222/https://www.ecowatch.com/futaleufu-whitewater-rafting-2002171427.html |date = October 7, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n===Military and Vieques===\nKennedy has been a critic of environmental damage by the U.S. military.<ref>Zukowski, Dan (June 22, 2017). \"[https://www.environews.tv/062217-act-war-rfk-jr-puts-u-s-military-cafos-blast-trashing-americas-waterways 'An Act of War': RFK Jr. Puts U.S. Military and CAFOs on Blast for Trashing America's Waterways]\". ''EnviroNews''. {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171022033952/https://www.environews.tv/062217-act-war-rfk-jr-puts-u-s-military-cafos-blast-trashing-americas-waterways/ |date=October 22, 2017 }}</ref><ref>Kennedy Jr., Robert F. (May 16, 2003). \"[http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2003-05-16/news/0305160280_1_superfund-sites-epa-report-pentagon Defending our Environment and Health from the U.S. Military]\". ''Chicago Tribune''. {{ Webarchive|url = https://web.archive.org/web/20171021220307/http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2003-05-16/news/0305160280_1_superfund-sites-epa-report-pentagon |date =October 21, 2017 }}</ref> In 1993, he successfully represented the [[Suquamish]] and [[Duwamish tribe|Duwamish]] Indian tribes in a lawsuit against the U.S. [[Puget Sound Naval Shipyard]] in [[Bremerton]], Washington, to stop polluting [[Puget Sound]].<ref>Le, Phuong (June 14, 2017). \"[http://www.kitsapsun.com/story/news/local/2017/06/14/suquamish-tribe-environmental-groups-sue-navy-over-hull-cleaning/397994001 Squamish Tribe, environmental groups sue Navy over hull cleaning]\". ''Kitsap Sun''. {{Webarchive| url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190420120650/https://www.kitsapsun.com/story/news/local/2017/06/14/suquamish-tribe-environmental-groups-sue-navy-over-hull-cleaning/397994001 |date= April 20, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nIn a 2001 article, Kennedy described how he sued the [[U.S. Navy]] on behalf of fishermen and residents of [[Vieques]], an island off [[Puerto Rico]], to stop weapons testing, bombing, and other military exercises. Kennedy argued that the activities were unnecessary, and that the Navy had illegally destroyed several endangered species, polluted the island's waters, harmed the residents' health, and damaged its economy.<ref name=\"vieques\">{{cite news |author1=Robert F. Kennedy Jr. |title=Why Are We in Vieques? |url=https://www.outsideonline.com/1819831/why-are-we-vieques |accessdate= 13 January 2020 |work=Outside |date=10 January 2001}}</ref> He was arrested for trespassing at [[Camp Garcia Vieques]], the [[U.S. Navy]] training facility, where he and others were protesting the use of a section of the island for training. Kennedy served 30 days in a maximum security prison in Puerto Rico.<ref>Greenhouse, Steven (July 16, 2001). \"[https://www.nytimes.com/2001/07/16/nyregion/he-s-in-charge-in-demand-and-in-prison.html He's in Charge, in Demand, in Prison]\". ''The New York Times''. {{Webarchive| url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171021221049/http://www.nytimes.com/2001/07/16/nyregion/he-s-in-charge-in-demand-and-in-prison.html |date= October 21, 2017 }}</ref> The trespassing incident forced the suspension of [[live-fire exercise]]s for almost three hours.<ref>\"[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/1470871.stm US Navy resumes Vieques war games]\". August 2, 2001. ''BBC News'' {{Webarchive |url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170629181314/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/1470871.stm |date=June 29, 2017 }}</ref> The lawsuits and protests by Kennedy, and hundreds of Puerto Ricans who were also imprisoned, eventually forced the termination of naval bombing in Vieques announced by president George Bush in 2001, and enacted in 2003.<ref>Hernandez, Raymond (June 15, 2001). \"[https://www.nytimes.com/2001/06/15/us/both-sides-attack-bush-plan-to-halt-bombing-on-vieques.html Both Sides Attack Bush Plan To Halt Bombing on Vieques]\". ''The New York Times''. {{Webarchive|url = https://web.archive.org/web/20171021221048/http://www.nytimes.com/2001/06/15/us/both-sides-attack-bush-plan-to-halt-bombing-on-vieques.html |date = October 21, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nIn a 2003 article for the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'', Kennedy accused the U.S. federal government of being \"America's biggest polluter\" and the [[U.S. Department of Defense]] as the worst offender. Citing the [[Environmental Protection Agency|EPA]], he said that \"unexploded ordnance waste can be found on 16,000 military ranges...and more than half may contain biological or chemical weapons\".<ref>Kennedy Jr., Robert F., (May 16, 2003). \"[http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2003-05-16/news/0305160280_1_superfund-sites-epa-report-pentagon Defending our environment and health from the U.S. military]\". ''Chicago Tribune''. {{Webarchive |url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171021220307/http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2003-05-16/news/0305160280_1_superfund-sites-epa-report-pentagon |date= October 21, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n===Factory farms===\nFor almost twenty years, Kennedy and his Waterkeepers waged a legal and public relations battle against pollution by factory farms. In the 1990s, he rallied opposition to factory farms among small independent farmers, convened a series of \"National Summits\" on factory meat products, and conducted press conference whistle stop tours across North Carolina, Iowa, Kansas, Missouri, Illinois, Ohio and in Washington DC. Beginning in 2000, Kennedy sued factory farms in North Carolina, Oklahoma, Maryland, and Iowa.<ref name=\"porkchop\">Hahn Niman, Nicolette (February 17, 2009). ''Righteous Porkchop: Finding a Life and Good Food beyond Factory Farms''. Published by William Morrow. p.336 {{ISBN|0061466492}}.</ref> He wrote numerous articles on the subject, arguing that factory farms produce lower-quality, less healthy food, and are harmful to independent family farmers by poisoning their air and water, reducing their property values, and using extensive state and federal subsidies to impose unfair competition against smaller farmers.<ref>{{cite news |author1= Robert F. Kennedy Jr. |author2=Eric Schaeffer |title= An Ill Wind From Factory Farms |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2003/09/20/opinion/an-ill-wind-from-factory-farms.html |accessdate= 13 January 2020 | work = New York Times |date=20 September 2003}}</ref>\n\nIn 1995, Premier [[Ralph Klein]] of Alberta declared Kennedy persona non grata in the province due to Kennedy's activism against Alberta's large-scale hog production facilities.<ref>Rogers, Shelagh, host, and Carty, Bob, reporter (Feb 12, 2001). \"Robert F. Kennedy Jr. warns Canada about Pollution from Pork Industry\". This Morning: CBC Digital Archives.</ref>  In 2002, [[Smithfield Foods]] filed a lawsuit against Kennedy in Poland, under a Polish law that makes criticizing a corporation illegal, after Kennedy denounced the company in a debate with Smithfield's Polish director before the Polish parliament.<ref name=\"porkchop\"/>\n\n===Oil, gas, and pipelines===\nKennedy has been an advocate for a global transition away from fossil fuels toward renewable energy.<ref>Ruf, Cory (May 25, 2013). \"Robert Kennedy Jr. on his crusade for a 'green' economy\". ''CBC News''.</ref><ref>Overheard with Evan Smith. (May 5, 2011). \"Robert F. Kennedy, Jr. \u2013 Fossil Fuels\". PBS</ref>  He has been particularly critical of the oil industry. He began his career at Riverkeeper during the time that the organization discovered that Exxon was using its oil tankers in order to steal fresh water from the Hudson River for use in its Aruba refinery and to sell to Caribbean Islands. Riverkeeper won a $2 million settlement against Exxon and lobbied successfully for a state law outlawing the practice.<ref>AP (April 26, 1984). \"Exxon is Sued by New York over Use of Hudson Water\". The New York Times.</ref> In one of his first environmental cases, Kennedy filed a lawsuit against [[Mobil Oil]] for polluting the Hudson.<ref>Cronin, John; Kennedy Jr., Robert F. (1997). ''The Riverkeepers: Two Activists Fight to Reclaim Our Environment as a Basic Human Right''. New York: Scribner. p.304. {{ISBN|0684839083}}.</ref>\n\nKennedy helped lead the battle against fracking in New York State.<ref>AP (March 02, 2013). \"New York fracking held as Gov. Andrew Cuomo, Robert F. Kennedy Jr. talk health, AP sources say\". Syracuse.com.</ref>  He had been an early supporter of natural gas as viable bridge fuel to renewables, and a cleaner alternative to coal.<ref>Isensee, Laura (October 28, 2009). \"Robert Kennedy Jr: solar and natural gas belong together\". Reuters</ref> However, he said he turned against this controversial extraction method after investigating its cost to public health; climate and road infrastructure.<ref>Marie Cusick (October 3, 2013). \"Robert F. Kennedy Jr. calls natural gas a 'catastrophe'\". StateImpact Pennsylvania</ref> As a member of Governor [[Andrew Cuomo]]'s fracking commission, Kennedy helped engineer the Governor's 2013 ban on fracking in New York State.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hakim |first1 =Danny |title =Shift by Cuomo on Gas Drilling Prompts Both Anger and Praise |url = https://www.nytimes.com/2012/10/01/nyregion/with-new-delays-a-growing-sense-that-gov-andrew-cuomo-will-not-approve-gas-drilling.html |accessdate =13 January 2020 |work= New York Times |date= 30 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nKennedy mounted a national effort against the construction of liquefied natural gas facilities.<ref>Staff writer (May 19, 2015). \"Rally Against Pipelines\". ''Salem Weekly''.</ref>  Waterkeepers maintains a national watch that documents numerous crude oil spills annually.  In Alaska, Kennedy was active in the fight to save the [[Arctic National Wildlife Refuge]] (ANWR), the largest undisturbed ecosystem in North America, from drilling.<ref>{{cite news |last1= Jones |first1 =Susan |title= ANWR Protest: 'Don't Drill, Storm Capitol Hill' |url= https://www.cnsnews.com/news/article/anwr-protest-dont-drill-storm-capitol-hill |accessdate =13 January 2020 |work=CNS News |date= 7 July 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Kennedy assisted the [[Chipewyan|Chipewyan First Nation]] and the [[Beaver Lake Cree Nation|Beaver Lake Cree]] fighting to protect their land from [[Oil sands|tar sands]] production.<ref name=\"macleans\">{{cite news |last1=Weber |first1=Bob |title= Prominent U.S. Keystone critic Robert F. Kennedy Jr. to visit oilsands |url =https://www.macleans.ca/news/prominent-u-s-keystone-critic-robert-f-kennedy-jr-to-visit-oilsands |accessdate =13 January 2020 |work= Macleans |date= 12 June 2013}}</ref> In February 2013, while protesting the [[Keystone XL Pipeline]] Kennedy, along with his son, Conor, was arrested for blocking a thoroughfare in front of the White House during a protest.<ref>Spear, Stefanie (February 13, 2013). \"Robert F. Kennedy, Jr., Bill McKibben, Michael Brune, Among Others Will Risk Arrest Today at White House to Stop Tar Sands, Keystone XL Pipeline\". ''EcoWatch''.</ref>  In August 2016, Kennedy and Waterkeeper participated in protests to block the extension of the [[Dakota Access pipeline]] across the [[Sioux]] Indian [[Standing Rock Reservation]]'s water supply.<ref>Manning, Sarah Sunshine (November 16, 2016). \"Robert F. Kennedy Jr. Visits Standing Rock on #NoDAPL Day of Action\". ''Indian Country Today''.</ref>\n\nKennedy claims that the only reason the oil industry is able to remain competitive against renewables and electric cars is through massive direct and indirect subsidies and political interventions on behalf of the oil industry. In a June 2017 interview on ''EnviroNews'', Kennedy said about the oil industry, \"That's what their strategy is: build as many miles of pipeline as possible. And what the industry is trying to do is to increase that level of infrastructure investment so our country won't be able to walk away from it.<ref>Zukowski, Dan (June 26, 2017). \"Robert F. Kennedy Jr. Talks Tesla, Electric Big Rigs and the Impending Death of Fossil Fuels\". ''EnivroNews''.</ref>\n\n===Coal===\nUnder Kennedy's leadership, Waterkeeper launched its \"Clean Coal is a Deadly Lie\"<ref>Baxter, Brandon (June 3, 2014). \"Robert F. Kennedy Jr. Praises Obama's Carbon Rules, Blasts Koch Brothers on 'The Ed Show'\". ''EcoWatch''.</ref> campaign in 2001, bringing dozens of lawsuits targeting mining practices, which include [[mountaintop removal]],<ref>Perks, Rob (March 11, 2010). \"[https://www.nrdc.org/experts/rob-perks/mountaintop-removal-redux-bobby-vs-blankenship-ii Mountaintop Removal Redux: Bobby vs. Blankenship II]\". NRDC.</ref> [[slurry]] pond construction, and targeting mercury emissions and [[coal ash]] piles by coal-burning utilities.<ref>\"Bobby Kennedy, Jr. Speaks on Coal Ash at Mt. Island Lake\". July 25, 2013. ''Clean Air Carolina''.</ref> Kennedy's Waterkeeper alliance has also been leading the fight against coal export, including from terminals in the Pacific Northwest.<ref>Yaggi, Marc, Waterkeeper Alliance (Winter 2013). \"Around the World a Coalition Against Coal: Waterkeepers from Idaho to India Unite to Stop the Deadly International Coal Trade\". ''Waterkeeper Magazine''</ref>\n\nKennedy has promoted replacing coal energy with renewable energy, which, he argues, would thereby reduce costs and greenhouse gases while improving air and water quality, the health of the citizens, and the number and quality of jobs.<ref>Staff writer (2015). \"At Pennsylvania Coal Mine, Feds Come to Rescue after State Fails\". ''Waterkeeper Magazine'' Vol. 11. Issue 1.</ref>\nIn June 2011, film producer Bill Haney televised his award-winning film ''[[The Last Mountain]]'', co-written by Haney and Peter Rhodes, depicting Kennedy's fight to stop [[Appalachian Mountains|Appalachian]] mountaintop removal mining.<ref>''[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1787816/ The Last Mountain]'' (2011) IMDb.</ref>\n\n===Nuclear power===\nKennedy has been an opponent of conventional nuclear power, arguing that it is unsafe and not economically competitive.<ref>Zukowski, Dan (June 23, 2017). \"Robert F. Kennedy Jr.: 'I love James Hansen, but he is wrong on [the nuclear power issue]'\". ''EniroNews''.</ref><ref>Brooks, Jon (June 22, 2011). \"Interview: Robert F. Kennedy Jr. on 'Uninsurable' Nuke Energy Industry, BrightSource Solar Project\". KQED.</ref> On June 15, 1981, he made international news when he spoke at an anti-nuclear rally at the [[Hollywood Bowl]], with [[Stephen Stills]], [[Bonnie Raitt]] and [[Jackson Browne]].<ref>Paul Chin photograph. (June 15, 1981). Caption reads, \"Robert F. Kennedy, Jr. speaks out against nuclear power\". Archivegrid, Los Angeles Public Library.</ref>\n\nHis thirty-year battle to close [[Indian Point Energy Center|Indian Point]] nuclear power plant in New York ended in victory in January 2017, when Kennedy signed onto an agreement with New York State Governor Andrew Cuomo and [[Entergy]], the plant's operator, to close the plant by 2021.<ref>Admin (April 4, 2017). \"Nuclear Ticking Time Bomb 28 Miles From NYC \u2013 America's Lawyer\". Indian Point Safe Energy Coalition.</ref> Kennedy was featured in a 2004 documentary, ''Indian Point: Imagining the Unimaginable'', directed by his sister and documentary filmmaker [[Rory Kennedy]].<ref>''[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0426493/ Indian Point: Imagining the Unimaginable]'', (TV movie 2004). IMDb.</ref>\n\n===Hydro===\nKennedy has been an outspoken opponent of dams, particularly of dam projects that affect indigenous communities.\n\nIn 1991, Kennedy helped lead a campaign to block [[Hydro-Qu\u00e9bec]] from building the James Bay Hydro-project, a massive dam project in northern Quebec.<ref>{{cite news |last1= Trueheart |first1= Charles |title= Quebec Power Company Finds Its High-Voltage Plans Short-Circuited |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1994/04/07/quebec-power-company-finds-its-high-voltage-plans-short-circuited/4ba36f07-d34b-4105-b3b4-849b08e1431b | accessdate= 13 January 2020 |work = Washington Post |date= 7 April 1994}}</ref>\n\nHis campaigns helped block dams on [[Chile]]'s [[Biob\u00edo River]] in 1990<ref>Bowermaster, Jon (November 1992). \"Last Run Down the Bio Bio\". ''Town and Country''.</ref> and its [[Futaleuf\u00fa River]] in 2016. In 2002, he mounted what was ultimately an unsuccessful battle against building a dam on [[Belize]]'s [[Macal River]]. Kennedy termed the [[Chalillo Dam]] \"a boondoggle\", and brought a high-profile legal challenge against [[Fortis Inc.]], a Canadian power company and the monopoly owner of Belize's electric utility.<ref name=\"auto7\">Guynup, Sharon (June 7, 2002). \"Belize Dam Fight Heats Up as Court Prepares to Rule\". ''National Geographic Today''.</ref> In a 3&ndash;2 ruling in 2003, the [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom]] upheld the Belizean government's decision to permit dam construction.<ref name=\"auto7\"/><ref>Leaney, Stephen (April 11, 2003). \"British finding 'secret war' in green laws by Kennedy\". ''International Press Service''.</ref><ref>Ari Hershowitz, \"[https://scholarship.law.berkeley.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1858&context=elq A Solid Foundation: Belize's Chalillo Dam and Environmental Decisionmaking]\", ''Ecology Law Quarterly'', Vol. 35, pp. 73-106.</ref> \n\nIn 2004, Kennedy met with Provincial officials and brought foreign media and political visitors to Canada to protest the building of [[hydroelectric]] dams on Quebec's [[Magpie River (Quebec)|Magpie River]].<ref>\"Robert F. Kennedy Jr. on the river along with numerous leaders of conservation organizations\". August 02, 2004. Canadian Parks And Wilderness Society \u2013 Quebec Chapter.</ref> [[Hydro-Quebec]] dropped plans for the dam in 2017.<ref>Goujard, Clothilde (September 14, 2017). \"Hydro-Quebec abandons dam project on majestic Magpie River\". ''National Observer''.</ref>\n\nIn November 2017, the Spanish hydroelectric syndicate [[Endesa]] announced its decision to abandon [[HydroAysen]], a massive project to construct dams on dozens of [[Patagonia]]'s rivers accompanied by thousands of miles of roads, power lines and other infrastructure. Endesa returned its [[water right]]s to the Chilean government. The Chilean press credits advocacy by Kennedy and Riverkeeper as critical factors in the company's decision.<ref>Martinez, Rodrigo (November 19, 2017). \"[http://www.latercera.com/noticia/robert-kennedy-jr-los-beneficios-economicos-unos-millonarios Robert Kennedy Jr por Hidroays\u00e9n: 'Los beneficios econ\u00f3micos eran para unos pocos millonarios']\". ''La Tercera''. {{Webarchive | url = https://web.archive.org/web/20171120084704/http://www.latercera.com/noticia/robert-kennedy-jr-los-beneficios-economicos-unos-millonarios  | date =November 20, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n===Cape Wind===\nIn 2005, Kennedy clashed with national environmental groups over his opposition to a wind farm off [[Cape Cod]]. Taking the side of Cape Cod's commercial fishing industry, Kennedy argued that the [[Cape Wind Project]] in [[Nantucket Sound]] was a costly [[boondoggle]]. This position angered some environmentalists, and brought Kennedy criticism by industry groups and Republicans{{who|date=October 2017}}.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://radioequalizer.blogspot.com/2007/07/rfk-jr-tirade-air-america-john-stossel.html |title= The Radio Equalizer: Brian Maloney: RFK Jr Tirade, Air America, John Stossel, Rush Limbaugh, Sean Hannity |access-date = October 25, 2017 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20171025132306/http://radioequalizer.blogspot.com/2007/07/rfk-jr-tirade-air-america-john-stossel.html | archive-date = October 25, 2017| url-status= live}}</ref> Kennedy argued in an opinion piece in the ''Wall Street Journal'' that \"[[Vermont]] wants to take its nuclear plant off line and replace it with clean, green power from [[Hydro-Qu\u00e9bec|HydroQu\u00e9bec]]\u2014power available to [[Massachusetts Department of Public Utilities|Massachusetts utilities]]\u2014at a cost of six cents per kilowatt hour (kwh). Cape Wind electricity, by a conservative estimate and based on figures they filed with the state, comes in at 25 cents per kwh.\"<ref>https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702304521304576447541604359376</ref>\n\n==Personal views==\n\n[[File:RfkjrOCT2017.jpg|thumb|Kennedy in 2017]]\n\n===Political criticisms===\nThroughout the [[presidency of George W. Bush]], Kennedy was a persistent critic of Bush's environmental and energy policies. He accused Bush of defunding and corrupting federal science projects.<ref>Griscom, Amanda (October/November 2004). \"Environmental Justice\". ''Mother Earth News''.</ref>\n \nKennedy was also critical of Bush's 2003 [[Hydrogen vehicle|hydrogen car]] initiative,<ref>{{cite news |last1 =Roberts |first1= Joel |title = Bush: $1.2 Billion For Hydrogen Cars |url= https://www.cbsnews.com/news/bush-12-billion-for-hydrogen-cars |accessdate =13 January 2020 |work = CBS News |date =29 January 2003}}</ref> noting that it was a gift to the fossil fuel industry disguised as a green automobile.<ref>{{cite news |author1= Robert F. Kennedy Jr. |title=A Bad Element |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2003/02/16/opinion/a-bad-element.html |accessdate =13 January 2020 |work =New York Times | date= 16 February 2003}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, Kennedy wrote an article in ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' about Bush's environmental record,<ref name=\"must-be-done\">{{cite news |title=Robert F. Kennedy Jr. on the Climate Crisis: What Must Be Done |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/politics-news/robert-f-kennedy-jr-on-the-climate-crisis-what-must-be-done-192191 |accessdate=13 January 2020 |work=Rolling Stone |date=28 June 2007}}</ref> which he subsequently expanded into a ''New York Times'' bestselling book.<ref>Kennedy, Jr., Robert F. (2004). ''Crimes Against Nature: How George W. Bush and His Corporate Pals Are Plundering the Country and Hijacking Our Democracy''. HarperCollins. {{ISBN|0060746882}}.</ref> His opposition to the environmental policies of the Bush administration earned him recognition as one of ''Rolling Stone''{{'s}} \"100 Agents of Change\" on April 2, 2009.<ref>{{cite web | url= https://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/26754176/the_rs_100_agents_of_change/4 |title= The 100 People Who Are Changing America |author= | website =Rolling Stone| accessdate = October 15, 2017|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090503094135/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/26754176/the_rs_100_agents_of_change/4 |archive-date=May 3, 2009 | url-status = live}}</ref><ref name=\"mercurynews.com\">{{cite web| url= http://www.mercurynews.com/2010/10/14/robert-f-kennedy-jr-advocates-for-green-power |title = Robert F. Kennedy Jr. advocates for green power |author =|date= October 14, 2010 |website= The Mercury News |accessdate = October 15, 2017|archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20171010055245/http://www.mercurynews.com/2010/10/14/robert-f-kennedy-jr-advocates-for-green-power |archive-date = October 10, 2017| url-status =live}}</ref>\n\nDuring an October 2012 interview with ''[[Politico]]'', Kennedy called on environmentalists to direct their dissatisfaction towards the [[U.S. Congress]] rather than President [[Barack Obama]], reasoning that Obama \"didn't deliver\" due to having a partisan U.S. Congress \"like we haven't seen before in American history\".<ref>Dixon, Darius (October 12, 2012). \"RFK Jr. to greens: Not Obama's fault\". ''Politico''.</ref>  He also accused politicians who failed to act on climate change policy as serving special interests and, selling out the public trust. He accused [[Koch family|Charles and David Koch]], the owners of [[Koch Industries]], Inc., the nation's largest privately owned oil company, of subverting democracy and for \"making themselves billionaires by impoverishing the rest of us\".<ref>Robert F. Kennedy, Jr. (2015) \"What State Attorneys General can do about Climate-Change Deniers\" Letter from the President\", ''Waterkeeper Magazine'' Vol. 11. Issue 1.</ref>  Kennedy has spoken of the Koch Brothers as leading \"the apocalyptical forces of Ignorance and Greed\".<ref>Spear, Stefanie (September 10, 2015). \"Koch Brothers: Apocalyptical Forces of Ignorance and Greed, Says RFK Jr.\" ''EcoWatch''.</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2014 People's Climate March]], Kennedy said, \"American politics is driven by two forces: One is intensity, and the other is money. The Koch brothers have all the money. They're putting $300 million this year into their efforts to stop the climate bill. And the only thing we have in our power is people power, and that's why we need to put this demonstration on the street\".<ref>Goodman, Amy (September 22, 2014). \"Robert F. Kennedy Jr.: \"The Only Thing We Have in Our Power is People Power\". ''Democracy Now''.</ref>\n\n===Food allergies===\nKennedy was a founding board member of the [[Food Allergy Initiative]]. His son Conor suffers from anaphylaxis peanut allergies. Kennedy wrote the foreword to ''The Peanut Allergy Epidemic'', in which he and the authors link increasing food allergies in children to certain vaccines that were approved beginning in 1989.<ref>Kennedy Jr., Robert F. (June 6, 2017). Foreword for ''The Peanut Allergy Epidemic: What's Causing It And How To Stop It''. Third Edition. by Heather Fraser, New York: Skyhorse Publishing. {{ISBN|1510726314}}.</ref>\n\n=== Views on autism and vaccines ===\nKennedy is the chairman of [[Children's Health Defense]] (formerly the World Mercury Project), an advocacy group alleging that a large proportion of American children are suffering from conditions as diverse as autism, [[attention deficit hyperactivity disorder]], [[Food allergy|food allergies]], [[cancer]] and [[autoimmune disease]]s, all allegedly caused by exposure to a variety of chemicals. In addition to vaccines, Children's Health Defense has been campaigning against [[Water fluoridation|fluoridation of drinking water]], [[Paracetamol|acetaminophen]], [[aluminum]], and [[Wireless|wireless communications]], among others. Kennedy's group has been identified as one of two major buyers of anti-vaccine Facebook advertising in late 2018 and early 2019.<ref name=journ>{{Cite journal | last = Jamison |first= A.M.| last2= Broniatowski |first2= D. A. |last3= Dredze |first3=M. |date= 2019-11-13 |title= Vaccine-related advertising in the Facebook Ad Archive |journal = Vaccine |volume= 38|issue= 3|pages= 512\u2013520|doi= 10.1016/j.vaccine.2019.10.066|pmid= 31732327|pmc= 6954281}}</ref><ref name=study>{{Cite news |url= https://web.archive.org/web/20191117003403/https://www.washingtonpost.com/health/2019/11/15/majority-anti-vaccine-ads-facebook-were-funded-by-two-groups |title = Majority of anti-vaccine ads on Facebook were funded by two groups |last= Sun| first = Lena H. |date= 2019-11-15 |work= Washington Post| access-date= 2019-11-16 |url-status =live |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20191117003403/https://www.washingtonpost.com/health/2019/11/15/majority-anti-vaccine-ads-facebook-were-funded-by-two-groups |archive-date =2019-11-16}}</ref>\n\nIn their early years, the group focused on the perceived issue of [[Mercury (element)|mercury]], in industry and medicine, especially the ethylmercury compound [[thimerosal]] in [[vaccine]]s, proposed by discredited former doctor [[Andrew Wakefield]] as a mechanism for the disproved link between vaccines and autism. Despite Kennedy's claims that he is in fact not against vaccines,<ref name=notav1>{{Cite news| url = https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/08/health/vaccines-kennedy-measles.html |title =Brother and Sister of Robert F. Kennedy Jr. Accuse Him of Spreading Misinformation on Vaccines |last= Rabin| first= Roni Caryn| date= May 8, 2019|work=The New York Times |access-date=June 21, 2019| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190621221444/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/08/health/vaccines-kennedy-measles.html|archive-date= June 21, 2019 | url-status =live}}</ref><ref name=notav2>{{Cite news |url= https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/entry/siblings-oped-calls-robert-f-kennedy-jrs-vaccine-views-tragically-wrong_n_5cd2ca19e4b07ce6ef78850e |title = Robert Kennedy Jr.'s Vaccine Views Slammed As 'Tragically Wrong' By Family |last =Golgowski| first= Nina| date = May 8, 2019 |work= Huffington Post | access-date=June 21, 2019|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190621221641/https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/entry/siblings-oped-calls-robert-f-kennedy-jrs-vaccine-views-tragically-wrong_n_5cd2ca19e4b07ce6ef78850e |archive-date= June 21, 2019|url-status =live}}</ref> critics point out he and his organization spread common anti-vaccine arguments as part of their core messages. Kennedy has stated the media and governments are engaged in a conspiracy to deny that vaccines cause autism.<ref name=glob>{{Cite web| url=https://globalnews.ca/news/3253840/robert-de-niro-robert-f-kennedy-jr-offer-100g-to-anyone-who-can-provide-proof-vaccines-are-safe |title= Robert De Niro, Robert F. Kennedy Jr. offer $100K to anyone who can provide proof vaccines are safe| last=Scott| first= Katie|date= February 16, 2017|website= Global TV|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190303172615/https://globalnews.ca/news/3253840/robert-de-niro-robert-f-kennedy-jr-offer-100g-to-anyone-who-can-provide-proof-vaccines-are-safe |archive-date =March 3, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=March 3, 2019}}</ref><ref name=SBM1>{{Cite web|url= https://sciencebasedmedicine.org/autism-prevalence-increases-to-1-in-59-and-antivaxers-lose-it-yet-again |title=Autism prevalence increases to 1 in 59, and antivaxers lose it\u2026yet again |last=Gorski |first=David| authorlink=David Gorski|date=April 30, 2018| website=Science-Based medicine | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190227151319/https://sciencebasedmedicine.org/autism-prevalence-increases-to-1-in-59-and-antivaxers-lose-it-yet-again |archive-date= February 27, 2019| url-status= live| access-date = February 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | url = https://www.cbc.ca/news/opinion/kennedy-surrey-1.5206701 |title= The Surrey Board of Trade shouldn't help anti-vaxxer Robert F. Kennedy Jr. build his brand | last = Cadeski |first=Eric| date= July 11, 2019|work = CBC News| access-date= 2019-11-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news| url= https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/robert-f-kennedy-jr-surrey-speaking-event-1.5178877 |title= Robert F. Kennedy Jr. will speak at Surrey event despite outcry, board of trade says |last = Schmunk |first =Rhianna |date=2019-06-17 |work =CBC News |access-date =2019-11-18}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2005, Kennedy authored an article in ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' and ''[[Salon (website)|Salon]]'' called \"[[Deadly Immunity]]\", alleging a government conspiracy to conceal a connection between thimerosal and the epidemic of childhood [[neurodevelopmental disorders]], including [[autism]].<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite news |author1= Robert F. Kennedy Jr. |title=Deadly Immunity |url= https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/politics-news/deadly-immunity-180037  |accessdate=13 January 2020 |work=Rolling Stone |date=8 February 2011}}</ref> The article contained five factual errors, leading ''Salon'' to issue corrections.<ref name=\"auto2\">Lauerman, Kerry (January 16, 2011). \"[http://www.salon.com/2011/01/16/dangerous_immunity Correcting our Record]\". ''Salon''. {{Webarchive |url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171104122950/https://www.salon.com/2011/01/16/dangerous_immunity |date=November 4, 2017 }}</ref> Six years later, on January 16, 2011, ''Salon'' retracted the article completely.<ref name=\"auto2\"/> According to ''Salon'', the retraction was motivated by accumulating evidence of alleged errors and [[scientific fraud]] underlying the vaccine-autism claim.<ref>Oransky, Ivan (January 16, 2011) \"[http://retractionwatch.com/2011/01/16/salon-retracts-2005-robert-f-kennedy-jr-piece-on-alleged-autism-vaccine-link ''Salon'' retracts 2005 Robert F. Kennedy Jr. piece on alleged autism-vaccine link]\". ''Retraction Watch''. {{Webarchive| url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170831053935/http://retractionwatch.com/2011/01/16/salon-retracts-2005-robert-f-kennedy-jr-piece-on-alleged-autism-vaccine-link |date = August 31, 2017 }}</ref> ''Rolling Stone'' stands by Kennedy's story.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nIn May 2013, Kennedy delivered the keynote address at the vaccination information<ref>{{Cite web |url= https://blogs.plos.org/thepanicvirus/2012/05/15/more-media-stupidity-chicago-sun-times-runs-propaganda-piece-for-jenny-mccarthys-anti-vaccine-conference |title = More media stupidity: ''Chicago Sun-Times'' runs propaganda piece for Jenny McCarthy's anti-vaccine conference |website = The Panic Virus |access-date =2019-01-28 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190129064155/https://blogs.plos.org/thepanicvirus/2012/05/15/more-media-stupidity-chicago-sun-times-runs-propaganda-piece-for-jenny-mccarthys-anti-vaccine-conference |archive-date =January 29, 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref> AutismOne / [[Generation Rescue]] conference.<ref name=\"Slate_2013\">{{Cite journal| last1= Plait |first1= Phil| authorlink1 = Phil Plait| title= Robert F. Kennedy Jr.: Anti-Vaxxer | url= http://www.slate.com/blogs/bad_astronomy/2013/06/05/robert_f_kennedy_jr_advocate_for_antiscience_and_antivaccination.html |journal = Slate | accessdate =13 February 2018 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20180208145313/http://www.slate.com/blogs/bad_astronomy/2013/06/05/robert_f_kennedy_jr_advocate_for_antiscience_and_antivaccination.html | archivedate =8 February 2018 |date= 5 June 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"AutismOne_2013\">{{cite web |title= Generation Rescue Conference 2013| url = http://www.autismone.org/content/autismone-generation-rescue-conference-2013 | website= AutismOne | accessdate = 13 February 2018 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130730131034/http://www.autismone.org/content/autismone-generation-rescue-conference-2013 | archivedate = 30 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014 Kennedy published a book, ''Thimerosal: Let the Science Speak: The Evidence Supporting the Immediate Removal of Mercury\u2014a Known Neurotoxin\u2014from Vaccines''. While methylmercury is a potent neurotoxin, ethylmercury, as used in vaccine preservatives, is safer.<ref>{{cite web | title = Thimerosal and Vaccines |url= https://www.fda.gov/vaccines-blood-biologics/safety-availability-biologics/thimerosal-and-vaccines#pres |publisher= U.S. Food and Drug Administration |access-date=August 24, 2019 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190825041528/https://www.fda.gov/vaccines-blood-biologics/safety-availability-biologics/thimerosal-and-vaccines#pres |archive-date = August 25, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>  The preface to the book is written by [[Mark Hyman (doctor)|Mark Hyman]], a proponent of the [[Alternative medicine|alternative medical treatment]] called [[functional medicine]].<ref name=\"Cracked31\">{{cite AV media | title = Functional Medicine (CS31) | url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3EDW_upV3ZU |website=YouTube |accessdate=18 April 2019 | publisher = McGill Office for Science and Society | date=13 April 2019 | time =6:18}}</ref> Kennedy has published many articles on the inclusion of the mercury-based preservative thimerosal in vaccines, which have appeared in ''[[Huffington Post]]'',<ref>Kennedy Jr., Robert F. (May 11, 2010). \"[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/robert-f-kennedy-jr/central-figure-in-cdc-vac_b_494303.html Central Figure in CDC Vaccine Cover-Up Absconds With $2M]\". ''Huffpost''. {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171017141128/https://www.huffingtonpost.com/robert-f-kennedy-jr/central-figure-in-cdc-vac_b_494303.html |date=October 17, 2017 }}</ref> ''EcoWatch'',<ref>Kennedy Jr., Robert F. (Feb. 8, 2017). \"[https://www.ecowatch.com/yale-vaccine-study-kennedy-2246059411.html Yale University Study Shows Association Between Vaccines and Brain Disorders]\". ''EcoWatch''. {{Webarchive| url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171013120638/https://www.ecowatch.com/yale-vaccine-study-kennedy-2246059411.html | date = October 13, 2017 }}</ref><ref>Kennedy Jr., Robert F. (Jan. 18, 2017) \"[https://www.ecowatch.com/cdc-mercury-vaccines-kennedy-2199157054.html CDC Knew its Vaccine Program Was Exposing Children to Dangerous Mercury Levels Since 1999]\". ''EcoWatch''. {{Webarchive | url = https://web.archive.org/web/20171007220719/https://www.ecowatch.com/cdc-mercury-vaccines-kennedy-2199157054.html |date= October 7, 2017 }}</ref> and ''[[The Boston Globe]]''.<ref>Kennedy Jr., Robert F. (July 10, 2005). \"[http://archive.boston.com/news/globe/editorial_opinion/oped/articles/2005/07/01/autism_mercury_and_politics Autism, Mercury, and Politics]\". ''The Boston Globe''. {{Webarchive| url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170304051731/http://archive.boston.com/news/globe/editorial_opinion/oped/articles/2005/07/01/autism_mercury_and_politics | date = March 4, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nIn April 2015, Kennedy participated in a Speakers' Forum to promote the film ''[[Trace Amounts]]'', which promotes the link between autism and mercury in vaccinations. At a film screening, Kennedy described the autism epidemic as a \"holocaust\".<ref>White, Jeremy B. (April 7, 2015). \"[http://www.sacbee.com/news/politics-government/capitol-alert/article17814440.html Robert Kennedy Jr. warns of vaccine-linked 'holocaust']\". ''Sacramento Bee''.{{Webarchive |url =https://web.archive.org/web/20150411002553/http://www.sacbee.com/news/politics-government/capitol-alert/article17814440.html |date= April 11, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nOn January 10, 2017, incoming [[White House Press Secretary]] [[Sean Spicer]] confirmed that Kennedy and [[President-elect]] [[Donald Trump]] met to discuss a position in the Trump administration. Kennedy accepted an offer made by Trump to become the chairman of the Vaccine Safety Task Force. A spokeswoman for Trump's transition said that no final decision had been made.<ref name=\"skeptic\">{{Cite news |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/trump-to-meet-with-proponent-of-debunked-tie-between-vaccines-and-autism/2017/01/10/4a5d03c0-d752-11e6-9f9f-5cdb4b7f8dd7_story.html |authors = Phillip, Abby; Sun, Lena H. and Bernstein, Lenny |date = 10 January 2017| title= Vaccine skeptic Robert Kennedy Jr. says Trump asked him to lead commission on 'vaccine safety' | work = The Washington Post |access-date =January 11, 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170111010144/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/trump-to-meet-with-proponent-of-debunked-tie-between-vaccines-and-autism/2017/01/10/4a5d03c0-d752-11e6-9f9f-5cdb4b7f8dd7_story.html | archive-date =January 11, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> In an August 2017 interview with ''[[Stat (website)|STAT News]]'' reporter Helen Branwell, Kennedy said that he had been meeting with the federal public health regulators to discuss defects in vaccine safety science, at the White House's request.<ref>\"[https://worldmercuryproject.org/news/interview-stat-news-august-14-2017 An interview with Robert Kennedy Jr. on vaccines]\". Interviewed by [[Helen Branswell]]. August 21, 2017. World Mercury Project.{{Webarchive| url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171013172227/https://worldmercuryproject.org/news/interview-stat-news-august-14-2017 |date=October 13, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nOn February 15, 2017, Kennedy and actor [[Robert De Niro]] gave a press conference at the [[National Press Club (United States)|National Press Club]] in Washington, D.C., in which they accused the press of acting as propagandists for the $35 billion vaccination industry and refusing to allow debates on vaccination science. They offered a $100,000 reward to any journalist or other citizen who could point to a study showing that it is safe to inject mercury into babies and pregnant women at levels currently contained in [[Influenza vaccine|flu vaccines]]. Craig Foster, a psychology professor who studies [[pseudoscience]], deemed the challenge \"not science\", noting that it was a \"carefully constructed 'contest' that allows its creators to generate the misleading outcome they presumably want to see\". He also stated that \"Proving that something is safe is importantly different than proving that something is harmful\".<ref name=\"Craig Foster\">{{cite journal |last1=Foster |first1= Craig |title =The $100,000 vaccine challenge: Another method of promoting anti-vaccination pseudoscience |journal= Vaccine |date=2017 |volume= 35 |issue=32 |pages= 3905\u20133906 |doi=10.1016/j.vaccine.2017.06.012 |pmid=28624304 }}</ref>\n\nOn May 8, 2019, [[Kathleen Kennedy Townsend]], [[Joseph P. Kennedy II|Joseph P. Kennedy]] and [[Maeve Kennedy McKean]] wrote an open letter stating that while their relative has championed many admirable causes, he \"has helped to spread dangerous misinformation over social media and is complicit in sowing distrust of the science behind vaccines\".<ref name=ff>{{Cite news |url = https://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2019/05/08/robert-kennedy-jr-measles-vaccines-226798 |title= RFK Jr. Is Our Brother and Uncle. He's Tragically Wrong About Vaccines |last1 = Kennedy Townsend | first1=Kathleen| author-link1= Kathleen Kennedy Townsend | date =May 8, 2019| work = Politico | access-date =May 8, 2019|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190508183738/https://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2019/05/08/robert-kennedy-jr-measles-vaccines-226798 | archive-date = May 8, 2019 |url-status =live |last2= Kennedy |first2 =Joseph P.| author-link2 = Joseph P. Kennedy II |last3= Kennedy McKean| first3 = Maeve}}</ref>\n\nIn June 4, 2019, during a visit to [[Samoa]] coinciding with that nation's 57th independence celebration, Kennedy appeared in an Instagram photo with Australian-Samoan anti-vaccine activist [[Taylor Winterstein]]. Kennedy's charity and Winterstein have both perpetuated the lie that that the [[MMR vaccine]] played a role in the 2018 deaths of two Samoan infants, despite the subsequent revelation that the infants had received a [[muscle relaxant]] along with the vaccine by mistake. Kennedy has drawn criticism for fueling vaccine hesitancy amid a social climate which gave rise to the [[2019 Samoa measles outbreak]], which killed over 70 people, and the [[2019 Tonga measles outbreak]].<ref>{{cite news |last1= Lanuola |first1= Tusani Tupufia |title= John F. Kennedy's nephew joins Samoa's Independence celebration |url= https://www.samoaobserver.ws/category/samoa/42888 |accessdate = 30 November 2019 | publisher= Samoa Observer |date= 1 June 2019 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20191130201157/https://www.samoaobserver.ws/category/samoa/42888 | archivedate =30 November 2019 |ref = SamoaObserver_20190601 |url-status =live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1 = Guarino |first1=Ben |last2= Satija |first2= Neena |last3 =Sun |first3 = Lena H. |title = Deadly measles outbreak hits children in Samoa after anti-vaccine fears |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/health/2019/11/26/deadly-measles-outbreak-hits-children-samoa-after-anti-vaccine-fears  |accessdate= 30 November 2019 | work = The Washington Post |date= 27 November 2019 |ref=WaPo_Samoa_measles_20191127 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20191130201455/https://www.washingtonpost.com/health/2019/11/26/deadly-measles-outbreak-hits-children-samoa-after-anti-vaccine-fears |archivedate =30 November 2019 |url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nKennedy is listed as executive producer of ''Vaxxed II: The People's Truth'', the 2019 sequel to [[Andrew Wakefield]]'s and [[Del Bigtree]]'s anti-vaccination documentary ''[[Vaxxed]]''.<ref>{{Cite news| url= https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/oct/31/vaxxed-2-movie-sequel-release-fears-propaganda |title=Release of ''Vaxxed'' sequel prompts fears dangerous propaganda will spread again |last =Pilkington| first= Ed |date= 2019-10-31| work= The Guardian |access-date=2019-11-18}}</ref>\n\n===Views on the murder of Martha Moxley===\nIn January 2003, Kennedy wrote a controversial article in ''[[The Atlantic]]'' Monthly about the 1975 [[murder of Martha Moxley]] in Greenwich, Connecticut, in which he insists that Michael Skakel's indictment \"was triggered by an inflamed media, and that an innocent man is now in prison\". Skakel and Kennedy are first cousins, as Kennedy's mother and Skakel's father are siblings. The article argues that there is more evidence suggesting that Kenneth Littleton, the Skakel family's live-in tutor, killed Moxley. He also calls Dominick Dunne the \"driving force\" behind Skakel's prosecution.<ref name=\"miscarriage\">{{cite news |author1=Robert F. Kennedy Jr. |title=A Miscarriage of Justice |url= https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2003/01/a-miscarriage-of-justice/304759 |accessdate=13 January 2020 |work=The Atlantic |date=January\u2013February 2003}}</ref> In July 2016, Kennedy released a book titled ''Framed: Why Michael Skakel Spent over a Decade in Prison for a Murder He Didn't Commit''.<ref>{{cite news |first =Michael |last =Melia |date= July 12, 2016 |newspaper = Hartford Courant |title = RFK Jr. Book Stokes Intrigue In Michael Skakel Murder Case |url= http://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-skakel-book-0713-20160712-story.html |accessdate =July 12, 2016 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160713175621/http://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-skakel-book-0713-20160712-story.html |archive-date = July 13, 2016 |url-status =live }}</ref> In September 2017, the rights to Kennedy's book were optioned by FX Productions to develop a multi-part television series.<ref>Schneider, Michael (September 20, 2017). \"[http://www.indiewire.com/2017/09/robert-f-kennedy-framed-michael-skakel-martha-moxley-fx-1201876985 FX Prods. To Develop 'Framed,' Robert F. Kennedy Jr's Crusade to Clear His Cousin's Murder Conviction \u2013 Exclusive]\". ''IndieWire''.{{Webarchive| url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171011072523/http://www.indiewire.com/2017/09/robert-f-kennedy-framed-michael-skakel-martha-moxley-fx-1201876985 |date= October 11, 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.imdb.com/news/ni61529212 |title= FX Prods. to Develop 'Framed,' Robert F. Kennedy Jr's Crusade to Clear His Cousin's Murder Conviction | website =IMDb}}</ref>\n\n===Views on JFK assassination and the Warren Commission===\nOn the evening of January 11, 2013, [[Charlie Rose]] interviewed Kennedy and his sister [[Rory Kennedy|Rory]] at the [[Margot and Bill Winspear Opera House|Winspear Opera House]] in [[Dallas]] as a part of then Dallas Mayor [[Mike Rawlings]]' hand-chosen committee's yearlong program of celebrating the life and presidency of John F. Kennedy.<ref>DiEugenio, Jim (February 3, 2013). \u201cThe MSM and RFK Jr.: Only 45 years late this time\u201d. Kennedy and King (formerly CTKA).</ref> Robert F. Kennedy Jr. said that he was convinced that [[Lee Harvey Oswald]] was not solely responsible for the [[Assassination of John F. Kennedy|assassination]] of his uncle, President John F. Kennedy; and said his father [[Robert Kennedy]] was \"fairly convinced\" that others besides Oswald were involved in his brother's assassination and privately believed the [[Warren Commission]] report was a \"shoddy piece of craftsmanship\".<ref>{{cite web |url= http://bigstory.ap.org/article/rfk-children-speak-about-assassination-dallas-0 |title= RFK children speak about assassination in Dallas |work= The Big Story | accessdate= October 23, 2014| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150108084445/http://bigstory.ap.org/article/rfk-children-speak-about-assassination-dallas-0| archive-date = January 8, 2015| url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news| url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/retropolis/wp/2018/05/26/who-killed-bobby-kennedy-his-son-rfk-jr-doesnt-believe-it-was-sirhan-sirhan |title = Who killed Bobby Kennedy? His son RFK Jr. doesn't believe it was Sirhan Sirhan |last= |first= |date =June 5, 2018 |work= [[The Washington Post]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20181007092707/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/retropolis/wp/2018/05/26/who-killed-bobby-kennedy-his-son-rfk-jr-doesnt-believe-it-was-sirhan-sirhan |archive-date =October 7, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>DiEugenio, Jim (February 3, 2013). \u201cThe MSM and RFK Jr.: Only 45 years late this time\u201d. Kennedy and King (formerly CTKA).</ref> In an extended commentary on JFK's presidency on the 50th anniversary of his death, Kennedy referenced only one book, ''[[JFK and the Unspeakable]]''.<ref name=\"vision-peace\">{{cite news |title=John F. Kennedy's Vision of Peace |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/politics-news/john-f-kennedys-vision-of-peace-109020 |accessdate=13 January 2020 |work=Rolling Stone |date=20 November 2013}}</ref> The 2013 edition of the book was endorsed by Kennedy, who said it had moved him to visit [[Dealey Plaza]], the site of his uncle's assassination, for the first time.<ref name=Orbis>[[Orbis Books]], [http://www.orbisbooks.com/jfk-and-the-unspeakable.html ''JFK and the Unspeakable'']</ref> \n\n===Views on U.S. foreign policy===\nKennedy has written extensively on foreign policy, beginning with a 1974 ''Atlantic Monthly'' article titled, \"Poor Chile\", discussing the overthrow of Chilean President [[Salvador Allende]].<ref>Kennedy Jr., Robert F. (February 1974). \"Poor Chile\". ''Atlantic Monthly''.</ref>  Kennedy also wrote editorials against the execution of Pakistan President [[Zulfikar Ali Bhutto]] by General [[Muhammad Zia-ul-Haq]].<ref>Kennedy Jr. Robert F. (February 25, 1979). \"Plea to Pakistan\". ''The Washington Post''.</ref><ref>Kennedy Jr., Robert F. (February 23, 1979). \"Legacy at Stake in Pakistan\". ''The Boston Globe''.</ref>  In 1975, he published an article in ''The Wall Street Journal'', criticizing the use of assassination as a foreign policy tool.<ref>Kennedy Jr., Robert F. (Robert F. Kennedy, Jr. (December 16, 1975) \"Politics and Assassinations\". ''The Wall Street Journal''</ref>  In 2005, he wrote an article for the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' decrying President Bush's use of torture as anti-American.<ref>Kennedy Jr., Robert F. (December 17, 2005). \"America's anti-torture tradition\". ''Los Angeles Times''.</ref> Senator Edward Kennedy entered the article into the ''[[Congressional Record]]''.<ref>Congressional Record Index. (Vol 151 \u2013 Part 23). January 4, 2005 - December 30, 2005. by Senator Edward M. Kennedy. P.2054</ref>\n\nIn an article titled \"Why the Arabs Don't Want Us in Syria\", published in ''[[Politico]]'' in February 2016, Kennedy referred to the \"bloody history that modern [[Interventionism (politics)|interventionists]] like [[George W. Bush]], [[Ted Cruz]] and [[Marco Rubio]] miss when they recite their narcissistic trope that Mideast nationalists 'hate us for our freedoms.' For the most part they don't; instead they hate us for the way we betrayed those freedoms \u2014 our own ideals \u2014 within their borders\".<ref>{{cite news |author1 = Robert F. Kenney Jr. |title= Why the Arabs Don't Want Us in Syria |url = https://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2016/02/rfk-jr-why-arabs-dont-trust-america-213601 |accessdate =13 January 2020 |work = Politico |date = 22 February 2016}}</ref>  Kennedy blames the Syrian war on a pipeline dispute. He cites wiki-leaks documents alleging that the CIA-led military and intelligence planners to foment a [[Sunni]] uprising against [[Syria]]'s president, [[Bashar al-Assad]], following his rejection of a proposed [[Qatar-Turkey pipeline]] through Syria in 2009, well before the [[Arab Spring]].<ref>Kennedy Jr., Robert F. (February 25, 2016). \"Syria: Another Pipeline War\". ''EcoWatch''.</ref>  In 2013, Kennedy wrote an article for ''Rolling Stone'' exploring President John F. Kennedy's difficult struggle with his own military and intelligence apparatus to keep America out of war and from becoming an imperial state.<ref name=\"vision-peace\"/>\n\n===Political endorsements===\nKennedy was on the National Staff and a State Coordinator for [[Ted Kennedy#1980 presidential campaign|Edward M. Kennedy for President]] from 1979 to 1980. Prior to that he had been on Senator Kennedy's 1970 and 1976 Massachusetts Senatorial Campaigns. He was a co-founder and a former board member of the New York [[League of Conservation Voters]].<ref>Brancaccio, David (January 21, 2005). \"Science and Health: Robert F. Kennedy, Jr.\". ''PBS NOW''.</ref><ref>New York League of Conservative Voters. June 18, 2014. NYLCV Letterhead.</ref>\n\nKennedy endorsed and campaigned extensively for Vice President [[Al Gore]] during his [[Al Gore 2000 presidential campaign|2000 presidential campaign]], and openly opposed his friend [[Ralph Nader]]'s [[Green Party of the United States|Green Party]] [[Ralph Nader 2000 presidential campaign|presidential campaign]], predicting that it could sink the Gore campaign and put George W. Bush into the White House.  In the 2004 American presidential election, Kennedy endorsed [[John Kerry]], noting his strong environmental record.<ref>elch, Craig (October 29, 2003). \"RFK Jr. blasts Bush, champions Kerry\". ''The Seattle Times''.</ref>\n\n[[File:RFK DNC etown (1).jpg|thumb|right|Kennedy at a taping of [[ETown]] during the [[2008 Democratic National Convention]]]]\n\nIn late 2007, Kennedy and his sisters [[Kerry Kennedy|Kerry]] and [[Kathleen Kennedy Townsend|Kathleen]] announced that they would be endorsing [[Hillary Clinton]] in the [[2008 Democratic Party presidential primaries]].<ref>{{cite news |author1 =Jeff Zeleny |author2= Carl Hulse |title = Kennedy Chooses Obama, Spurning Plea by Clintons |url = https://www.nytimes.com/2008/01/28/us/politics/28kennedy.html | accessdate =13 January 2020 |work = New York Times |date =28 January 2008}}</ref> After the [[2008 Democratic National Convention|Democratic Convention]], Kennedy campaigned for Obama across the country.<ref>\"eTown at the 2008 Democratic National Convention (Denver)\". October 8, 2008. etown.org</ref>  After the election, he was named as a front-runner for Obama's [[Administrator of the Environmental Protection Agency|EPA administrator]].<ref>Lance, Jennifer (December 3, 2008). \"The Most Important Barack Obama Appointee: EPA Administrator Short List\". ''Red Green and Blue''.</ref>\n\nKennedy has been critical of the integrity of the voting process. In June 2006 he published an article in ''Rolling Stone'' purporting to show that GOP operatives stole the [[2004 United States presidential election|2004 election]] for President George W Bush. [[Farhad Manjoo]] countered Kennedy's conclusions,<ref>{{cite news |author1=Farhad Manjoo | authorlink1 =Farhad Manjoo |title=Was the 2004 election stolen? No. |url= https://www.salon.com/2006/06/03/kennedy_39/ |accessdate=13 January 2020 |work= Salon |date=3 June 2006}}</ref> but there were other people who argued otherwise.<ref>Zuesse, Eric (October 25, 2016). \"How the 2004 Presidential 'Election' Was Stolen by George W. Bush\". Washington's Blog.</ref>\n\nKennedy has written frequent warnings about the ease of election hacking and the dangers of voter purges and [[Voter ID laws in the United States|voter ID laws]]. He wrote the introduction and a chapter in ''Billionaires and Ballot Bandits'', a 2012 book on election hacking by investigative journalist [[Greg Palast]].<ref>Greg Palast (Author) Ted Rall (Illustrator). Introduction by Robert F. Kennedy, Jr. (2012). ''Billionaires & Ballot Bandits: How to Steal an Election in 9 Easy Steps''. Penguin Random House. p 300. {{ISBN|978-1609804787}}</ref>\n\n===Political aspirations===\nKennedy first considered running for political office in 2000, when New York Senator [[Daniel Patrick Moynihan]] announced he would not seek re-election to the [[List of United States Senators from New York|U.S. Senate seat]] formerly held by Kennedy's father.<ref>{{cite news |last1 = Bumiller |first1 =Elisabeth |title = Public Lives: Putting Family Life Ahead of a Senate Seat |url= https://www.nytimes.com/1998/11/24/nyregion/public-lives-putting-family-life-ahead-of-a-senate-seat.html |accessdate =13 January 2020 | work= New York Times |date = 24 November 1988}}</ref> His father was elected to the same seat in 1964, and held it for 41 months, until his death in 1968.\n\nIn 2005, Kennedy considered running for [[New York Attorney General]], which would have meant a possible run against his then brother-in-law [[Andrew Cuomo]], but in the end he decided against entering the race, even though he had been considered the frontrunner.<ref>{{cite news | author1 = Jonathan P. Hicks |title= Robert Kennedy Won't Run for State Attorney General |url = https://www.nytimes.com/2005/01/25/nyregion/robert-kennedy-wont-run-for-state-attorney-general.html |accessdate= 13 January 2020 |work =New York Times | date =25 January 2005}}</ref>\n\nOn December 2, 2008, Kennedy announced that he did not wish to be appointed to the U.S. Senate by New York Governor [[David Paterson]]. He felt that it would take too much time away from his family.<ref>{{cite news |author1= Jonathan P. Hicks |title = Robert F. Kennedy's Son Not Interested in Senate Seat |url= https://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2008/12/02/robert-f-kennedys-son-not-interested-in-senate-seat |accessdate = 13 January 2020 |work= New York Times |date=2 December 2008 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20191006100343/https://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2008/12/02/robert-f-kennedys-son-not-interested-in-senate-seat  | archivedate =6 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\n=== General interests ===\nKennedy is a licensed master [[Falconry|falconer]] and has trained hawks since he was 11. He breeds hawks and falcons and is also licensed as a raptor propagator and a wildlife rehabilitator.<ref>Rubinowitz, Susan. (December 10, 2014). \"Robert F. Kennedy Jr. \u2013 The Bird Rehabilitator\". Pet Place.</ref> He holds permits for Federal Game Keeper, Bird Bander, and Scientific Collector. He was President of the New York State Falconry Association from 1988 to 1991. In 1987, while on Governor Mario Cuomo's New York State Falconry Advising Committee, Kennedy authored the examination to qualify apprentice falconers given by New York State. Later that year he wrote the ''New York State Apprentice Falconer's Manual'',  which was published by the New York State Department of Environmental Conservation, and continues in use today.<ref>News Staff (February 15, 2002). \"Robert F. Kennedy Jr. to speak at Syracuse University\". Syracuse University News.</ref>\n\nKennedy is also a [[Whitewater kayaking|whitewater kayaker]]. His father introduced him and his siblings to whitewater kayaking during early trips down the [[Green River (Colorado River)|Green]] and [[Yampa River]]s in Utah and Colorado, the [[Columbia River]], the [[Middle Fork Salmon River|Middle Fork Salmon]] in Idaho, and the Upper Hudson Gorge. From 1976 to 1981, Kennedy was a partner and guide at a whitewater company, \"Utopian\", based in [[West Forks, Maine]]. He organized and led several \"first-descent\" whitewater expeditions to Latin America including three hitherto unexplored rivers: the [[Apur\u00edmac River|Apurimac]], Peru, in 1975; the [[Atrato]], Colombia, in 1979; and the [[Caron\u00ed River|Caroni]], Venezuela, in 1982.<ref>Collier, Peter and Horowitz, David (1984). ''The Kennedys: An American Drama''. Published by Summit Books. p. 576. {{ISBN|0671447939}}.</ref> He made an early descent of [[Great Whale River]] in Northern Quebec, in 1993,<ref>Bowermaster, Jon (May 1993). \"Sacrificial People\u2013Will Quebec's Indians be Driven from Their Land?\". ''Conde Nast Traveller''.</ref> and has made many trips to Patagonia, Chile, to run the Biob\u00edo River, the Futaleuf\u00fa and other whitewater rivers.\n\nIn 2015, he took two of his sons to the [[Yukon]] to visit [[Mount Kennedy]] and run the [[Alsek River]], a whitewater river fed by the [[Alsek Glacier]]. Mount Kennedy had been Canada's highest unclimbed peak, when the Canadian Government named it for the assassinated American president, in 1964.<ref>Jourdan, Michael (August 5, 2015). \"Mountain Tribute to JFK Evoked by Kennedy Trip to Yukon\". ''National Geographic''.</ref> In 1965, his father [[Robert F. Kennedy]] was the first person to climb Mount Kennedy.<ref>Kennedy, Robert (April 9, 1965). \"Our Climb Up Mt. Kennedy\". ''Life''.</ref>\n\n===Marriages and children===\nOn April 3, 1982, Kennedy married Emily Ruth Black (b. 1957), whom he had met at the [[University of Virginia School of Law]].<ref>{{cite news |title = Robert F. Kennedy Jr. Weds Law Classmate |url= https://www.nytimes.com/1982/04/04/us/robert-f-kennedy-jr-weds-law-classmate.html | accessdate =13 January 2020 |work= New York Times |agency= UPI |date =4 April 1982}}</ref> They had two children: Robert Francis \"Bobby\" Kennedy III (b. 1984, married writer, peace activist and former [[Central Intelligence Agency|CIA]] officer Amaryllis Fox) and Kathleen Alexandra Kennedy (b. 1988). The couple separated in 1992 and divorced in 1994.<ref>Shaw, Dan (March 28, 1994). \"Chronicle\". ''The New York Times''.</ref>\n\nOn April 15, 1994, Kennedy married [[Mary Richardson Kennedy|Mary Kathleen Richardson]] (1959\u20132012) aboard a research vessel on the [[Hudson River]].<ref>Brozan, Nadine (April 20, 1994). \"Chronicle\". ''The New York Times''.</ref>  They had four children: Conor Richardson Kennedy (b. 1994), [[Kyra Kennedy|Kyra LeMoyne Kennedy]] (b. 1995), William Finbar \"Finn\" Kennedy (b. 1997), and Aidan Caohman Vieques Kennedy (b. 2001). On May 12, 2010, Kennedy filed for divorce from Mary; three days later she was charged with drunk driving. On May 16, 2012, Mary was found dead in a building on the grounds of her home in [[Mount Kisco, New York]].  The Westchester County Medical Examiner ruled the death to be a [[Suicide by hanging|suicide due to asphyxiation from hanging]].<ref>Hall, Christine. (May 17, 2012). \"Police: Mary Kennedy Committed Suicide\". ''The Bedford Daily Voice''.</ref>\n\nKennedy married his third wife, actress-director [[Cheryl Hines]], on August 2, 2014, at the [[Kennedy Compound|Kennedy compound]] in [[Hyannis Port, Massachusetts]]. They were first introduced by [[Larry David]], whose wife Hines played in the HBO series ''[[Curb Your Enthusiasm]]'' and began dating in 2012.<ref>{{cite news |last1 =Woletz |first1= Bob |title= No Curbs on Their Enthusiasm |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2014/08/03/fashion/weddings/no-curbs-on-their-enthusiasm.html |accessdate =13 January 2020 |issue = New York Times | date = 3 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1= Andrews-Dyer |first1 = Helena |title= Actress Cheryl Hines marries Robert F. Kennedy Jr. at Kennedy family compound in Cape Code |url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/reliable-source/wp/2014/08/03/actress-cheryl-hines-marries-robert-f-kennedy-jr-at-kennedy-family-compound-in-cape-cod |accessdate =13 January 2020 |work = Washington Post |date =3 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Controversies===\nIn the summer of 1970, Kennedy was charged in [[Hyannis, Massachusetts]] for marijuana possession. In August 1971, he was arrested for loitering, also in Hyannis, and pleaded no contest to the charge.<ref>\"[https://www.nytimes.com/1971/08/24/archives/robert-kennedy-17-fined-for-loitering-pleads-no-contest.html Robert Kennedy, 17, Fined for Loitering; Pleads No Contest]\". August 24, 1971. ''New York Times''. {{Webarchive |url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171006161855/http://www.nytimes.com/1971/08/24/archives/robert-kennedy-17-fined-for-loitering-pleads-no-contest.html |date=October 6, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1983, at age 29, Kennedy was arrested in a [[Rapid City, South Dakota]] airport for [[heroin]] possession after a search of his carry-on bag uncovered the drug, following a near overdose in flight.<ref name=\"heroin\">{{cite news |title=Robert Kennedy Jr. Admits He Is Guilty In Possessing Heroin |url = https://www.nytimes.com/1984/02/18/us/robert-kennedy-jr-admits-he-is-guilty-in-possessing-heroin.html |accessdate =13 January 2020 | work = New York Times | date= 18 February 1984}}</ref> Kennedy entered a guilty [[plea]] to Presiding Judge Marshall P. Young, who sentenced him to two years' [[probation]] and 1,500 hours of [[community service]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Kennedy Son Given Probation in Drug Case | url = https://www.nytimes.com/1984/03/17/us/around-the-nation-kennedy-son-givenprobation-in-drug-case.html | accessdate = 13 January 2020 | work = New York Times |date =17 March 1984 }}</ref> Following his arrest, Kennedy entered a drug treatment center and left employment as a government prosecutor.<ref name= \"living-dangerously\">{{cite news |author1 =Mark Leibovich |authorlink1= Mark Leibovich |title = Another Kennedy Living Dangerously |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2006/06/25/fashion/25bobby.html |accessdate=13 January 2020 |work= New York Times |date =25 June 2006}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, Kennedy hired William Wegner to work for Riverkeeper. He was a [[fishery]] scientist and falconer who had been sentenced to five years in prison; he served three years after pleading guilty to federal criminal charges for smuggling bird eggs from Australia.<ref name= \"bird-smuggler\">{{cite news |last1= Pool |first1=Bob |title= Bird Smuggler Sentenced to Prison |url= https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1996-04-02-me-53997-story.html |accessdate= 13 January 2020 |work=Los Angeles Times |date= 2 April 1996}}</ref> In 2000, Robert Boyle, Riverkeeper's founder and former president, fired Wegner, citing his criminal conviction, but Kennedy re-hired Wegner, believing he should be given a second chance. A majority of the Riverkeeper Board supported Kennedy's decision, but seven members joined Boyle in resigning.<ref>{{cite news |last1 =Roberts |first1 =Sam |title =Robert H. Boyle, a Watchdog of the Hudson River, Dies at 88 |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/22/nyregion/robert-h-boyle-founder-of-hudson-riverkeeper.html |accessdate =13 January 2020 |work=New York Times | date =22 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2013, ''The New York Post'' released excerpts from Kennedy's 2001 diary, in which Kennedy described multiple affairs,<ref>{{cite news | url =https://nypost.com/2013/09/08/rfk-jr-s-sex-diary-of-adultery |title = RFK's sex diary: His secret journal of affairs  |date= September 8, 2013 |work = New York Post| accessdate =October 23, 2014 |first1 =Isabel |last1= Vincent| first2 = Melissa| last2= Klein | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20141022041713/http://nypost.com/2013/09/08/rfk-jr-s-sex-diary-of-adultery |archive-date =October 22, 2014 | url-status = live}}</ref> and penned his opinions about public figures.<ref name=\"New York Post\">{{cite news| url= https://nypost.com/2013/09/09/diary-bombshell-rfks-secret-slams-against-al-sharpton-jesse-jackson-and-gov-cuomo | title= Diary bombshell: RFK's slams against Al Sharpton, Jesse Jackson and Gov. Cuomo | date = September 9, 2013| work= New York Post| accessdate = October 23, 2014 | first1 = Isabel |last1 =Vincent | first2= Melissa |last2 = Klein| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141025005337/http://nypost.com/2013/09/09/diary-bombshell-rfks-secret-slams-against-al-sharpton-jesse-jackson-and-gov-cuomo | archive-date = October 25, 2014 |url-status = live}}</ref> Kennedy said the paper had indeed printed his diary.<ref name=\"New York Post\"/>\n\n===Health===\nKennedy suffers from [[spasmodic dysphonia]], which causes his voice to [[:wikt:quaver|quaver]] and makes speech difficult. It is a form of an involuntary movement disorder called [[dystonia]] that affects only the [[larynx]].<ref name= \"voice-disorder\">{{cite news |last1=Cox |first1 = Lauren |title =Kennedy's Voice Draws Attention to Rare Disorder | url= https://abcnews.go.com/Health/story?id=5296702&page=1 |accessdate =13 January 2020 |work =ABC News |date= 7 January 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\nKennedy has authored or edited ten books on subjects such as the environment, science, biography, and American heroes, including two [[bestseller]]s and three children's books. \n*{{cite book |last1=Russel l|first1= Dick |title= Horsemen of the Apocalypse: The Men Who Are Destroying Life on Earth And What it Means for Our Children |publisher= [[Charles Scribner's Sons| Scribner]]|year=2017|location=New York| page= 304|isbn = 9781510721753}}\n*{{cite book |title= Framed: Why Michael Skakel Spent Over a Decade in Prison For a Murder He Didn't Commit | publisher= [[Skyhorse Publishing]]|year=2016| location=New York|page=240|isbn=9781510701779}}\n*{{cite book |title=Thimerosal: Let the Science Speak: The Evidence Supporting the Immediate Removal of Mercury\u2013a Known Neurotoxin\u2013from Vaccines|publisher=[[Skyhorse Publishing]]|year=2014|location=New York|page=224|isbn=978-1632206015 |title-link= Thimerosal}}\n*{{cite book |title=Crimes Against Nature: How George W. Bush and His Corporate Pals Are Plundering the Country and Highjacking Our Democracy|publisher=[[HarperCollins]]|year=2005|location=New York|page=[https://archive.org/details/crimesagainstnat00kenn/page/256 256]|isbn=978-0-06-074687-2|url=https://archive.org/details/crimesagainstnat00kenn/page/256}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Cronin|first1=John |title=The Riverkeepers: Two Activists Fight to Reclaim Our Environment as a Basic Human Right|publisher=[[Charles Scribner's Sons|Scribner]]|year=1997|location=New York|page=[https://archive.org/details/riverkeeperstwoa00cron/page/304 304]|isbn=978-0684839080|url=https://archive.org/details/riverkeeperstwoa00cron/page/304}}\n*{{cite book|title=The Billings Collection|publisher=[[John F. Kennedy Library]]|year=1992|location=Boston|url=https://www.jfklibrary.org/Asset-Viewer/Archives/KLBPP.aspx?f=1}}\n*{{cite book|title=Judge Frank M. Johnson Jr.: A biography|publisher=[[G. P. Putnam's Sons|Putnam]]|year=1978|isbn=978-0-399-12123-4|title-link=Frank Minis Johnson}}\n\n=== Children's books ===\n*{{cite book|title=Robert Smalls: The Boat Thief|publisher=[[Hyperion (publisher)|Hyperion]]|year=2008|location=New York|page=48|isbn=978-1423108023|title-link=Robert Smalls}}\n*{{cite book|title=Robert F. Kennedy Jr.'s American Heroes: The Story of Joshua Chamberlain and the American Civil War|publisher=[[Hyperion (publisher)|Hyperion]]|year=2007|location=New York|page=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9781423107712/page/48 48]|isbn=978-1-4231-0771-2|title-link=Joshua Chamberlain}}\n*{{cite book|author =Dennis Nolan (Illustrator)|title =St. Francis of Assisi: A Life of Joy|publisher=[[Hyperion (publisher)|Hyperion]]|year=2004|isbn=978-0-7868-1875-4|title-link=St. Francis of Assisi}}\n\n=== Selected articles ===\n\nKennedy has penned numerous academic and general interest articles as well as op-eds on oil, coal, green energy, election integrity, politics, the media, falconry, foreign policy, and civil rights. His writing has been published in ''[[The New York Times]]'', ''[[The Washington Post]]'', ''[[Time (magazine)|Time Magazine]]'', ''[[Newsweek]]'', ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', ''[[The Atlantic Monthly]]'', and ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'', among others. Kennedy is also a frequently published travel writer.\n\n* {{cite news |title=Meet the horsemen of our environmental apocalypse |url=https://www.salon.com/2017/06/25/meet-the-horsemen-of-our-environmental-apocalypse |accessdate=13 January 2020 |work=Salon |date=25 June 2017}}\n* {{cite news |title=John F. Kennedy's Vision of Peace |url= https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/politics-news/john-f-kennedys-vision-of-peace-109020 |accessdate=13 January 2020 |work=Rolling Stone |date=20 November 2013}}\n* {{cite news |title=The Next President's First Task [A Manifesto] |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2008/05/rfk_manifesto200805 |accessdate=13 January 2020 |work=Vanity Fair |date=8 December 2009}}\n* {{cite news |title =Robert F. Kennedy Jr. on the Climate Crisis: What Must Be Done |url= https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/politics-news/robert-f-kennedy-jr-on-the-climate-crisis-what-must-be-done-192191 |accessdate =13 January 2020 |work= Rolling Stone |date=28 June 2007}}\n* {{cite news |title=Texas Chainsaw Management |url= https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2007/05/revolvingdoor200705 |accessdate=13 January 2020 |work =Vanity Fair |date=4 April 2007}}\n* {{cite news |title=Deadly Immunity |url= https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/politics-news/deadly-immunity-180037  |accessdate=13 January 2020 |work=Rolling Stone |date= 8 February 2011}}\n*{{cite news |title= The Junk Science of George W. Bush |url=https://www.thenation.com/article/junk-science-george-w-bush/ |accessdate=13 January 2020 |work= The Nation |date=19 February 2004}}<ref name=\"junk\">{{cite news |title=The Junk Science of George W. Bush |url= https://www.thenation.com/article/junk-science-george-w-bush |accessdate=13 January 2020 |work=The Nation |date=19 February 2004}}</ref>\n* {{cite news |title= Crimes Against Nature |url= http://www.maryellenmark.com/text/magazines/rolling%20stone/920S-000-048.html |accessdate=13 January 2020 |work= Rolling Stone |date=11 December 2003}}\n* {{cite news |title=A Miscarriage of Justice |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2003/01/a-miscarriage-of-justice/304759/ |accessdate=13 January 2020 |work=The Atlantic |date=January\u2013February 2003}}\n* {{cite news |title =Why Are We in Vieques? |url= https://www.outsideonline.com/1819831/why-are-we-vieques |accessdate= 13 January 2020 |work=Outside |date=10 January 2001}}\n*August 26, 1992 \u2013 \"Driving Out Conoco Disservice to Rain Forests\". ''The Houston Chronicle''\n\n==Select awards and recognition==\nOver the course of his career, Kennedy has received numerous awards in his name and on behalf of organizations and causes that he has championed.\n\n*2018, The National Trial Lawyers, Mass Tort Trial Team of the Year - for \u201cgroundbreaking case of Dewayne \u201cLee\u201d Johnson v. Monsanto Company\u201d<ref name=\"Millican, Scott\"/>\n*2017, Earth Justice Mountain Heroes<ref>{{cite web|url =https://earthjustice.org/mountain-heroes/robert-f-kennedy-jr |title= Mountain Heroes: Robert F. Kennedy, Jr.|author=|date=May 16, 2012|website =earthjustice.org|accessdate=October 15, 2017|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171012150139/https://earthjustice.org/mountain-heroes/robert-f-kennedy-jr |archive-date=October 12, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> \n*2017, Foro La Region Award for \"La Proteccion de los Recrsos Naturales\"<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.laregion.es/album/ourense/foro-region-robert-kennedy-jr-imagenes/20170515222421708600.html |title = El Foro La Regi\u00f3n sobre la protecci\u00f3n de los recursos naturales, en im\u00e1genes | first= La |last =Regi\u00f3n|date= |website = La Regi\u00f3n| accessdate =October 15, 2017|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20171012100305/http://www.laregion.es/album/ourense/foro-region-robert-kennedy-jr-imagenes/20170515222421708600.html |archive-date = October 12, 2017|url-status= live}}</ref> \n*2017, Moms Across America Healthy Communities Award\n*2014, Stroud Award of Freshwater Excellence<ref>{{cite web|url=https://stroudcenter.org/news/robert-f-kennedy-jr-honored/|title=Robert F. Kennedy, Jr. Honored at Water's Edge Gala - Stroud Water Research Center|author= |date=December 22, 2014|website=stroudcenter.org |accessdate = October 15, 2017| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20171012095347/https://stroudcenter.org/news/robert-f-kennedy-jr-honored | archive-date = October 12, 2017 |url-status= live}}</ref> \n*2009, ''Rolling Stone'' \"100 Agents of Change\"<ref name=\"mercurynews.com\"/> \n*2008, USC Dornsife Sustainability Champion Award<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dornsife.usc.edu/news/stories/477/waterkeeper-alliance-and-robert-f-kennedy-jr-honored | title= Waterkeeper Alliance and Robert F. Kennedy Jr. Honored |author=|date=|website=usc.edu| accessdate= October 15, 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171012095550/https://dornsife.usc.edu/news/stories/477/waterkeeper-alliance-and-robert-f-kennedy-jr-honored |archive-date =October 12, 2017| url-status =live}}</ref> \n*2008, Theodre Gordon Flyfishers Conservation Award<ref name=\"pace.edu\">{{cite web|url = http://www.law.pace.edu/clinic-awards|title=Clinic Awards | author=| date=| website =www.law.pace.edu |accessdate=October 15, 2017 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20171012100249/http://www.law.pace.edu/clinic-awards |archive-date=October 12, 2017 |url-status= live}}</ref> \n*2007, ''Vanity Fair'' \"The Green Team\"<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2006/05/onthecover200605 |title= The Green Team| author=|date=| website= Vanity Fair |accessdate= October 15, 2017 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160726131455/http://www.vanityfair.com/news/2006/05/onthecover200605 |archive-date= July 26, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> \n*2005, William O. Douglas Award, on behalf of the Waterkeeper Alliance<ref>{{cite web|url=http://williamodouglas.org/robert-f-kennedy-jr-on-william-o-douglas |title = Robert F. Kennedy, Jr. on William O. Douglas |author=|date=|website= williamodouglas.org|accessdate=October 15, 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171012104519/http://williamodouglas.org/robert-f-kennedy-jr-on-william-o-douglas | archive-date= October 12, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> \n*2004, Riverkeeper's Environmental Excellence Award\n*2004, Marshall P. Madison Award\n*2003, Professional Resource Award, NY State Council of Trout Unlimited<ref name=\"pace.edu\"/>\n*2001, Distinguished Service Award presented at [[Pace Law School]]'s 25th Anniversary<ref>{{cite web| url= https://newswire.blogs.pace.edu/2001/10/23/25th-anniversary-alumni-leadership-awards-dinner-honors-robert-f-kennedy-jr-the-honorable-terry-jane-ruderman-and-peter-john-sacripanti | title= 25th Anniversary Alumni Leadership Awards Dinner Honors: Robert F. Kennedy, Jr., the Honorable Terry Jane Ruderman, and Peter John Sacripanti  |author =|date =|website =newswire.blogs.pace.edu |accessdate=October 15, 2017| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20171012100343/https://newswire.blogs.pace.edu/2001/10/23/25th-anniversary-alumni-leadership-awards-dinner-honors-robert-f-kennedy-jr-the-honorable-terry-jane-ruderman-and-peter-john-sacripanti |archive-date =October 12, 2017| url-status=live}}</ref> \n*2001, ''Men's Journal'' \"Heroes\" Award<ref>{{