[Category:20th-century American writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the London School of Economics]]\n[[Category:American biographers]]\n[[Category:American bloggers]]\n[[Category:American conspiracy theorists]]\n[[Category:American environmentalists]]\n[[Category:American legal scholars]]\n[[Category:American male bloggers]]\n[[Category:American male writers]]\n[[Category:American non-fiction environmental writers]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of drug offenses]]\n[[Category:American people of Dutch descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:American political writers]]\n[[Category:American Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:American talk radio hosts]]\n[[Category:Anti-vaccination activists]]\n[[Category:Environmental bloggers]]\n[[Category:Environmental lawyers]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Kennedy family]]\n[[Category:Natural Resources Defense Council people]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Democrats]]\n[[Category:New York (state) lawyers]]\n[[Category:Pace University School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:People with voice disorders]]\n[[Category:Thiomersal and vaccines]]\n[[Category:University of Virginia School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:Washington, D.C. Democrats]]\n[[Category:Writers from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Writers from Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:American Book Award winners]]\n[[Category:Prisoners and detainees of the United States federal government]]\n", "name_user": "Bcostley", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eViews on the murder of Martha Moxley:link Dunne", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_F._Kennedy_Jr."}
{"title_page": "Frasca International", "text_new": "{{redirect|Frasca}}\n{{Primary sources|date=February 2011}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name          = Frasca International, Inc.\n| logo          = Frasca International Inc. Logo.png\n| logo_caption  = \n| type          = [[Private company|Private]]\n| owner         = \n| foundation    = [[Champaign, Illinois]] (1958)\n| location      = Champaign, (1958-1990)\n                   [[Urbana, Illinois]] (1990-present)\n| key_people    = John Frasca - CEO and president <br/>[[Rudy Frasca]] - Founder and former President<ref>{{cite web|title=Frasca Appoints New CEO\n|url=http://www.flyingmag.com/news/frasca-appoints-new-ceo|accessdate=5 September 2011}}</ref>\n| industry      = [[Flight Simulation]]\n| products      = Flight training devices, full flight simulators, aviation training devices\n| revenue       = \n| num_employees = Approximately 150<ref>[http://www.frasca.com/web_pages/information/joblist.htm \"Frasca Careers\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100316125317/http://www.frasca.com/web_pages/information/joblist.htm |date=2010-03-16 }}</ref>\n| homepage      = {{url|www.frasca.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Frasca International, Inc.''', is a American manufacturer of [[flight simulation]] training devices, with over 3000 training devices delivered in approximately 70 countries throughout the world.<ref name=\"CAT Magazine, Issue 2/2008\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.frasca.com/pdf/CAT%20article%202008.pdf |title=\"CAT Magazine, Issue 2/2008\" |access-date=2008-12-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100925073341/http://frasca.com/pdf/CAT%20article%202008.pdf |archive-date=2010-09-25 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  Now based in [[Urbana, Illinois]], Frasca International was founded in [[Champaign, IL|Champaign, Illinois]] in 1958 by Rudy Frasca.  Frasca flight simulators are used in all segments of the aviation industry, including their extensive use in many prominent college aviation programs, including [[Purdue University]], [[Indiana State University]], [[Embry-Riddle Aeronautical University]], [[University of North Dakota]], [[Louisiana Tech University]], [[University of Illinois]], and [[Western Michigan University]].\n\n==History==\n\nIn 1949, Rudy Frasca joined the United States Navy, where he first experienced flight simulation as a Link Trainer instructor.  Following his service, and a period of research at the University of Illinois Institute of Aviation, Frasca founded Frasca Aviation (later renamed to Frasca International) in 1958.<ref name=\"frasca.com\">[http://www.frasca.com/web_pages/information/frascat.htm \"Frasca International, Inc. Corporate History\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081024232410/http://www.frasca.com/web_pages/information/frascat.htm |date=2008-10-24 }}</ref>  All early Frasca training devices used mechanical computers exclusively.  After working out of various locations for several years (including his home garage), Frasca established a permanent manufacturing plant in downtown Champaign, IL.\n\nIn the late 1970s, Frasca devices were converted to use analog electronic computers, allowing for devices that were more simple and cost-effective to manufacture, operate, and maintain.  The electronic transition began a period of rapid technological development, culminating in the transition to a digital, PC-based simulation architecture in 1983.<ref name=\"CAT Magazine, Issue 2/2008\"/>\n\nIn 1990, in order to support steadily increasing demand, Frasca International again relocated to a {{convert|70000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} office building and manufacturing facility in Urbana, Illinois, adjacent to [[Frasca Field]].<ref name=\"frasca.com\"/>  The new facility provided a substantial increase in manufacturing capacity, and allowed for the production of the company's first Full Flight Simulator (FFS) a short time after moving to the new location.\n\nThroughout the 1990s and early 2000s (decade), Frasca continued to expand its product line, providing training devices for all types of aircraft, both fixed-wing and rotary-wing, and in 2003, Frasca manufactured a Level B [[Cessna 208|Cessna 208B Grand Caravan]] FFS, followed by a Level C [[Beechcraft Super King Air|Beechcraft B200 King Air]] FFS in 2005.<ref name=\"CAT Magazine, Issue 2/2008\"/>\n\nIn the mid-2000s (decade), helicopters began to play an increasingly prominent role in the Frasca line-up, with the first Level 6 helicopter Flight Training Device (FTD) delivered in 2007.<ref name=\"CAT Magazine, Issue 2/2008\"/>  Subsequently, two more helicopter FTDs (a [[Eurocopter EC135]] and a [[Eurocopter AS350]]) were qualified Level 6 in 2008, followed by another EC135 qualified as a JAA Level 3 FTD by the [[FCAA]].<ref name=\"Frasca 2008 News\">[http://www.frasca.com/web_pages/information/2008previous%20news.htm \"Frasca 2008 News\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090120052336/http://frasca.com/web_pages/information/2008previous%20news.htm |date=2009-01-20 }}</ref>  The Level 6 EC135, along with a Frasca Bell 206 FTD, were the first Level 6 helicopter FTDs qualified under 14 CFR Part 60.\n\nMost recently, Frasca has partnered with [[FlightSafety International]] to produce and qualify the first Level 7 FTD in August 2009.<ref>[http://www.verticalmag.com/control/news/templates/?a=11601 \"Vertical Magazine Flight Test\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717194645/http://www.verticalmag.com/control/news/templates/?a=11601 |date=2011-07-17 }}</ref>  Frasca provided the hardware, flight and systems models, and instructor station, which were integrated to the FlightSafety Vital X image generator and 8 channel visual.  Similar Level 7 Bell 206 and Bell 407 devices have been delivered. Frasca delivered a level D CJ1+ Full Flight Simulator to China in 2014.\n\n==Product line==\n\nFrasca currently manufactures a complete line of training devices including CPTs (Cockpit Procedure Trainers), AATDs (Advanced Aviation Training Devices), FNPTs (Flight and Navigation Procedures Trainers), FTDs (Flight Training Devices), and FFS (Full Flight Simulators).  Simulated aircraft range from small single-engine training airplanes, such as the [[Cessna 172]] to large transport category airplanes, such as the [[Boeing 737]].\n\nThe helicopter line covers models from the small Robinson helicopters to medical transports, such as the [[Bell 407]] and Eurocopter EC135, to large passenger transport helicopters, such as the Sikorsky S-92 and Eurocopter EC225.<ref name=\"Frasca 2008 News\"/>\n\nCRJ-200 AATD, first delivered to Central Washington University.\n\n==Customers==\nFrasca training devices are used worldwide by operators in a variety of sectors, including general aviation, business aviation, airline transport, medical, and military.\n\nNotable commercial customers include Bell Helicopter, Bristow Helicopters, Era Training Center, and Delta Connection.<ref>[http://www.frasca.com/web_pages/information/customerprofiles.htm \"Frasca Customer Profiles\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090131153744/http://frasca.com/web_pages/information/customerprofiles.htm |date=2009-01-31 }}</ref>\n\nNotable colleges and universities that use Frasca products include Embry-Riddle Aeronautical University,\nSouthern Illinois University (SIU), Indiana State University, Central Washington University, Western Michigan University, University of North Dakota, Louisiana Tech University, University of Illinois, Middle Tennessee State University, and many others.\nEmbry-Riddle Aeronautical University uses a variety of Frasca simulators for its training, including [[Cessna 172s]], and [[Diamond DA 42]] models. Embry-Riddle's first two Level 6 DA-42 Flight Training Devices were qualified Level 6 in March 2008.<ref name=\"FAA Approves Frasca DA42 FTDs at Embry-Riddle\">[http://www.erau.edu/er/newsmedia/newsreleases/2008/da42sims.html FAA Approves Frasca DA-42 Sims at Embry-Riddle] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080615125731/http://www.erau.edu/er/newsmedia/newsreleases/2008/da42sims.html |date=2008-06-15 }}</ref>\n\n== Awards and recognitions ==\n\nSeveral awards and recognitions have been received by both Rudy Frasca and Frasca International.\n\n*1994 - [[University Aviation Association|UAA]] W.W. Estridge, Jr. Award\n*1996 - Illinois Governor\u2019s Export Award\n*1998 - [[RAeS]] Flight Simulation Silver Medal\n*2000 - [[NATA]]'s \"Excellence in Pilot Training\" Award\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.frasca.com Frasca Corporate Website]\n\n[[Category:Aerospace companies]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Champaign County, Illinois]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|Frasca}}\n{{Primary sources|date=February 2011}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name                = Frasca International, Inc.\n| logo                = [[File:Frasca International Inc. Logo.png|thumb|Frasca International Inc. Logo]]\n| type                = [[Private company|Private]]\n| owner               = \n| foundation          = [[Champaign, IL]] (1958)\n| location            = [[Champaign, IL]] (1958-1990)\n                   [[Urbana, IL]] (1990-Present)\n| key_people          = John Frasca - CEO and president <br/>[[Rudy Frasca]] - Founder and former President<ref>{{cite web|title=Frasca Appoints New CEO \n|url=http://www.flyingmag.com/news/frasca-appoints-new-ceo|accessdate=5 September 2011}}</ref>\n| industry            = [[Flight Simulation]]\n| products            = Flight Training Devices, Full Flight Simulators, Aviation Training Devices\n| revenue             = \n| num_employees       = Approximately 150<ref>[http://www.frasca.com/web_pages/information/joblist.htm \"Frasca Careers\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100316125317/http://www.frasca.com/web_pages/information/joblist.htm |date=2010-03-16 }}</ref>\n| homepage            = http://www.frasca.com/\n}}\n\n'''Frasca International, Inc.''', is a [[United States]] manufacturer of [[flight simulation]] training devices, with over 3000 training devices delivered in approximately 70 countries throughout the world.<ref name=\"CAT Magazine, Issue 2/2008\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.frasca.com/pdf/CAT%20article%202008.pdf |title=\"CAT Magazine, Issue 2/2008\" |access-date=2008-12-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100925073341/http://frasca.com/pdf/CAT%20article%202008.pdf |archive-date=2010-09-25 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  Now based in [[Urbana, Illinois]], Frasca International was founded in [[Champaign, IL|Champaign, Illinois]] in 1958 by Rudy Frasca.  Frasca flight simulators are used in all segments of the aviation industry, including their extensive use in many prominent college aviation programs, including [[Purdue University]], [[Indiana State University]], [[Embry-Riddle Aeronautical University]], [[University of North Dakota]], [[Louisiana Tech University]], [[University of Illinois]], and [[Western Michigan University]].\n\n==History==\n\nIn 1949, Rudy Frasca joined the United States Navy, where he first experienced flight simulation as a Link Trainer instructor.  Following his service, and a period of research at the University of Illinois Institute of Aviation, Frasca founded Frasca Aviation (later renamed to Frasca International) in 1958.<ref name=\"frasca.com\">[http://www.frasca.com/web_pages/information/frascat.htm \"Frasca International, Inc. Corporate History\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081024232410/http://www.frasca.com/web_pages/information/frascat.htm |date=2008-10-24 }}</ref>  All early Frasca training devices used mechanical computers exclusively.  After working out of various locations for several years (including his home garage), Frasca established a permanent manufacturing plant in downtown Champaign, IL.\n\nIn the late 1970s, Frasca devices were converted to use analog electronic computers, allowing for devices that were more simple and cost-effective to manufacture, operate, and maintain.  The electronic transition began a period of rapid technological development, culminating in the transition to a digital, PC-based simulation architecture in 1983.<ref name=\"CAT Magazine, Issue 2/2008\"/>\n\nIn 1990, in order to support steadily increasing demand, Frasca International again relocated to a {{convert|70000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} office building and manufacturing facility in Urbana, Illinois, adjacent to [[Frasca Field]].<ref name=\"frasca.com\"/>  The new facility provided a substantial increase in manufacturing capacity, and allowed for the production of the company's first Full Flight Simulator (FFS) a short time after moving to the new location.\n\nThroughout the 1990s and early 2000s (decade), Frasca continued to expand its product line, providing training devices for all types of aircraft, both fixed-wing and rotary-wing, and in 2003, Frasca manufactured a Level B [[Cessna 208|Cessna 208B Grand Caravan]] FFS, followed by a Level C [[Beechcraft Super King Air|Beechcraft B200 King Air]] FFS in 2005.<ref name=\"CAT Magazine, Issue 2/2008\"/>\n\nIn the mid-2000s (decade), helicopters began to play an increasingly prominent role in the Frasca line-up, with the first Level 6 helicopter Flight Training Device (FTD) delivered in 2007.<ref name=\"CAT Magazine, Issue 2/2008\"/>  Subsequently, two more helicopter FTDs (a [[Eurocopter EC135]] and a [[Eurocopter AS350]]) were qualified Level 6 in 2008, followed by another EC135 qualified as a JAA Level 3 FTD by the [[FCAA]].<ref name=\"Frasca 2008 News\">[http://www.frasca.com/web_pages/information/2008previous%20news.htm \"Frasca 2008 News\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090120052336/http://frasca.com/web_pages/information/2008previous%20news.htm |date=2009-01-20 }}</ref>  The Level 6 EC135, along with a Frasca Bell 206 FTD, were the first Level 6 helicopter FTDs qualified under 14 CFR Part 60.\n\nMost recently, Frasca has partnered with [[FlightSafety International]] to produce and qualify the first Level 7 FTD in August 2009.<ref>[http://www.verticalmag.com/control/news/templates/?a=11601 \"Vertical Magazine Flight Test\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717194645/http://www.verticalmag.com/control/news/templates/?a=11601 |date=2011-07-17 }}</ref>  Frasca provided the hardware, flight and systems models, and instructor station, which were integrated to the FlightSafety Vital X image generator and 8 channel visual.  Similar Level 7 Bell 206 and Bell 407 devices have been delivered. Frasca delivered a level D CJ1+ Full Flight Simulator to China in 2014.\n\n==Product line==\n\nFrasca currently manufactures a complete line of training devices including CPTs (Cockpit Procedure Trainers), AATDs (Advanced Aviation Training Devices), FNPTs (Flight and Navigation Procedures Trainers), FTDs (Flight Training Devices), and FFS (Full Flight Simulators).  Simulated aircraft range from small single-engine training airplanes, such as the [[Cessna 172]] to large transport category airplanes, such as the [[Boeing 737]].\n\nThe helicopter line covers models from the small Robinson helicopters to medical transports, such as the [[Bell 407]] and Eurocopter EC135, to large passenger transport helicopters, such as the Sikorsky S-92 and Eurocopter EC225.<ref name=\"Frasca 2008 News\"/>\n\nCRJ-200 AATD, first delivered to Central Washington University.\n\n==Customers==\nFrasca training devices are used worldwide by operators in a variety of sectors, including general aviation, business aviation, airline transport, medical, and military.\n\nNotable commercial customers include Bell Helicopter, Bristow Helicopters, Era Training Center, and Delta Connection.<ref>[http://www.frasca.com/web_pages/information/customerprofiles.htm \"Frasca Customer Profiles\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090131153744/http://frasca.com/web_pages/information/customerprofiles.htm |date=2009-01-31 }}</ref>\n\nNotable colleges and universities that use Frasca products include Embry-Riddle Aeronautical University,\nSouthern Illinois University (SIU), Indiana State University, Central Washington University, Western Michigan University, University of North Dakota, Louisiana Tech University, University of Illinois, Middle Tennessee State University, and many others.\nEmbry-Riddle Aeronautical University uses a variety of Frasca simulators for its training, including [[Cessna 172s]], and [[Diamond DA 42]] models. Embry-Riddle's first two Level 6 DA-42 Flight Training Devices were qualified Level 6 in March 2008.<ref name=\"FAA Approves Frasca DA42 FTDs at Embry-Riddle\">[http://www.erau.edu/er/newsmedia/newsreleases/2008/da42sims.html FAA Approves Frasca DA-42 Sims at Embry-Riddle] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080615125731/http://www.erau.edu/er/newsmedia/newsreleases/2008/da42sims.html |date=2008-06-15 }}</ref>\n\n== Awards and recognitions ==\n\nSeveral awards and recognitions have been received by both Rudy Frasca and Frasca International.\n\n*1994 - [[University Aviation Association|UAA]] W.W. Estridge, Jr. Award\n*1996 - Illinois Governor\u2019s Export Award\n*1998 - [[RAeS]] Flight Simulation Silver Medal\n*2000 - [[NATA]]'s \"Excellence in Pilot Training\" Award\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.frasca.com Frasca Corporate Website]\n\n[[Category:Aerospace companies]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Champaign County, Illinois]]\n", "name_user": "MB", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix infobox image syntax", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frasca_International"}
{"title_page": "Love Hurts", "text_new": "{{short description|Single by Everly Brothers}}\n{{About|the song written by Boudleaux Bryant}}\n{{More citations needed|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name     = Love Hurts\n| cover    =\n| alt      =\n| type     =\n| artist   = [[The Everly Brothers]]\n| album    = [[A Date with The Everly Brothers]]\n| released = 1961\n| format   =\n| recorded = July 1960\n| studio   =\n| venue    =\n| genre    = [[Country music|Country]]\n| length   = 2:22\n| label    = [[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]]\n| writer   = [[Felice and Boudleaux Bryant|Boudleaux Bryant]]\n| producer =\n}}\n\n\"'''Love Hurts'''\" is a song written and composed by the American songwriter [[Boudleaux Bryant]]. First recorded by [[the Everly Brothers]] in July 1960, the song is also well known from a 1975 international hit version by the Scottish [[hard rock]] band [[Nazareth (band)|Nazareth]] and in the [[United Kingdom|UK]] a top five hit in 1975 by the English singer [[Jim Capaldi]].\n\n==Appearances==\nThe song was introduced in December 1960 as an album track on ''[[A Date with The Everly Brothers]]'', but was never released as a single (A-side or B-side) by the Everlys. The first hit version of the song was by [[Roy Orbison]], who earned Australian radio play, hitting the Top Five of that country's singles charts in 1961. A recording by [[Emmylou Harris]] and [[Gram Parsons]] was included on Parsons' posthumously released ''[[Grievous Angel]]'' album. After Parsons' 1973 death, Harris made the song a staple of her repertoire, and has included it in her concert set lists from the 1970s to the present. Harris has since re-recorded the song twice. [[Jennifer Warnes]] released a version on her self-titled album in 1976.\n\nThe most successful recording of the song was by [[hard rock]] band [[Nazareth (band)|Nazareth]], who took the song to the U.S. Top 10 in 1975 and hit number one in Norway and the Netherlands.\nIn the UK the most successful version of the song was by former [[Traffic (band)|Traffic]] member Jim Capaldi, who took it to number four in the charts in November 1975 during an 11-week run.\nThe song was also covered by [[Cher]] in 1975 for her album ''Stars''. Cher re-recorded the song in 1991 for her album of the same name.\n[[Joan Jett]] included a version of the song on her 1990 album, [[The Hit List (Joan Jett album)|The Hit List]], a covers compilation.\n[[Rod Stewart]] recorded the song in 2006 for his album ''[[Still the Same... Great Rock Classics of Our Time]]'' which was No. 1 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart.\n\nThe [[Bluegrass music|bluegrass]] version appearing in both the ''[[Deadpool 2]]'' \"Super Duper Cut\" and the \"Once Upon A Deadpool\" DVD, during the montages featuring the [[Deadpool|titular character]]'s failed suicide attempts following [[Copycat (comics)|Vanessa]]'s death, was first recorded by [[The Osborne Brothers]] for their 1977 Release \"From Rocky Top To Muddy Bottom: The Songs Of Boudleaux & Felice Bryant\".<ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt5463162/soundtrack?ref_=tt_trv_snd</ref>\n\nJazz guitarist [[Julian Lage]] performs the song on his 2019 [[Love Hurts (Julian Lage album)|album of the same name]].\n\n== Roy Orbison version ==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Love Hurts\n| cover      = RoyOrbisonRunningScared.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Roy Orbison]]\n| album      =\n| A-side     = [[Running Scared (Roy Orbison song)|Running Scared]]\n| released   = 1961\n| format     = [[7-inch single]]\n| recorded   = 1961\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Pop music|Pop]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=2|s=26}}\n| label      = [[Monument Records|Monument]]\n| writer     = [[Boudleaux Bryant]]\n| producer   =\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n[[Roy Orbison]] covered \"Love Hurts\" in 1961 and issued it as the B-side to \"[[Running Scared (Roy Orbison song)|Running Scared]].\" While \"Running Scared\" was an international hit, the B-side only picked up significant airplay in Australia. Consequently, chart figures for Australia show \"Running Scared\"/\"Love Hurts\" as a double A-Side, both sides peaking at No. 5. This makes Orbison's recording of \"Love Hurts\" the first version to be a hit.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1961)\n!align=\"left\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Australia\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|5\n|}\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== Jim Capaldi version ==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Love Hurts\n| cover      = Jim Capaldi Love Hurts.png\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Jim Capaldi]]\n| album      = [[Short Cut Draw Blood]]\n| B-side     = Sugar Honey\n| released   = {{Start date|1975}}\n| format     = [[7-inch single]]\n| recorded   = 1975\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Pop music|Pop]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=3|s=29}}\n| label      = [[Island Records|Island]]\n| writer     = [[Boudleaux Bryant]]\n| producer   = Steve Smith\n| prev_title = [[It's All Up to You]]\n| prev_year  = 1974\n| next_title = Goodbye Love\n| next_year  = 1976\n}}\n[[Jim Capaldi]] reached number 4 in the UK charts with his interpretation of \"Love Hurts\" in November 1975, which was to prove his highest charting UK single.<ref>[http://www.theofficialcharts.com/artist/_/jim%20capaldi/ Jim Capaldi in the UK charts] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120912114305/http://www.theofficialcharts.com/artist/_/jim%20capaldi/ |date=2012-09-12 }}, The Official Charts. Retrieved August 11, 2011.</ref> Described by ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' as having \"a sense of pain very different from Roy Orbison's.\"<ref>Marsh, Dave (11 March 1976). {{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/artists/jimcapaldi/albums/album/116873/review/5943052/short_cut_draw_blood |title=Album review |accessdate=2011-08-12 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090430135807/http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/jimcapaldi/albums/album/116873/review/5943052/short_cut_draw_blood |archivedate=April 30, 2009 }}, ''Rolling Stone''.</ref> the single also charted in the US,<ref>[http://www.allmusic.com/artist/jim-capaldi-p3832/charts-awards Jim Capaldi in the Billboard charts], Allmusic. Retrieved August 11, 2011.</ref> Germany,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.musicline.de/de/chartverfolgung_summary/artist/Jim+Capaldi/3979/single |title=Chartverfolgung / Jim Capaldi / Single |work=Music Line | publisher=[[Media Control Charts]] |location=[[Germany]] |language=German |accessdate=28 September 2011}}</ref> and Sweden.<ref>[http://swedishcharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Jim+Capaldi&titel=Love+Hurts&cat=s \"Love Hurts\" in the Swedish charts], swedishcharts.com. Retrieved August 12, 2011.</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1975\u201376)\n!align=\"left\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n|Australia ([[Kent Music Report]])<ref>{{cite book|first= David |last= Kent |authorlink= David Kent (historian) |title= [[Kent Music Report|Australian Chart Book 1970-1992]] |publisher= Australian Chart Book |location= [[St Ives, New South Wales|St Ives]], N.S.W. |year= 1993 |isbn= 0-646-11917-6}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|6\n|-\n|Canada ''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'' Top Singles<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.4096a&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.4096a.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.4096a|title=Item Display - RPM - Library and Archives Canada |website=Collectionscanada.gc.ca |date=1976-04-03 |accessdate=2019-03-31}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|15\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Germany\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|42\n|-\n|{{singlechart|Ireland2|8|song=Love Hurts|accessdate=November 1, 2018}}\n|-\n|South Africa ([[Springbok Radio|Springbok]])<ref>{{cite web|title=SA Charts 1965\u2013March 1989|url=http://www.rock.co.za/files/springbok_top_20_(C).html|accessdate=5 September 2018}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|13\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Sweden\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|16\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|UK \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|4\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|U.S.\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|97\n|}\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== Nazareth version ==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Love Hurts\n| cover      = Nazareth Love Hurts.png\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Nazareth (band)|Nazareth]]\n| album      = [[Hair of the Dog (album)|Hair of the Dog]]\n| B-side     = {{ubl|\"Down\" (non-U.S.)|\"[[Hair of the Dog (song)|Hair of the Dog]]\" (U.S.)}}\n| released   = {{Start date|1974}}\n| format     = [[7-inch single]]\n| recorded   = 1974\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Blues rock]]|[[hard rock]]<ref>{{cite book|author=Phil Hardy|title=The Da Capo Companion to 20th-century Popular Music|year=1995|publisher=Da Capo Press|isbn=978-0-306-80640-7|page=123}}</ref>}}\n| length     = {{Duration|m=3|s=53}}<br>{{Duration|m=3|s=03}} (U.S. single)\n| label      = [[Vertigo Records|Vertigo]]\n| writer     = [[Felice and Boudleaux Bryant|Boudleaux Bryant]]\n| producer   = [[Manny Charlton]]\n| prev_title = [[This Flight Tonight]]\n| prev_year  = 1973\n| next_title = Shanghai'd in Shanghai\n| next_year  = 1974\n}}\nPerformed as a [[power ballad]],<ref name=\"LLC1995\">{{cite book|author=SPIN Media LLC|title=SPIN|date=June 1995|publisher=SPIN Media LLC|pages=104\u2013|issn=0886-3032}}</ref> the Nazareth version is the most popular version of the song and the only rendition of \"Love Hurts\" to become a [[hit single]] in the United States, reaching No. 8 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] in early 1976. ''Billboard'' ranked it as the No. 23 song for 1976.<ref>[[Billboard Year-End Hot 100 singles of 1976]]</ref> As part of the \"Hot Tracks (EP)\" it also reached No. 41 in the UK in 1977.<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\">{{cite book\n| first= David\n| last= Roberts\n| year= 2006\n| title= British Hit Singles & Albums\n| edition= 19th\n| publisher= Guinness World Records Limited\n| location= London\n| isbn= 1-904994-10-5\n| page= 388}}</ref> Nazareth's version was an international hit, peaking at No. 1 in Canada, the Netherlands, Belgium, South Africa and Norway, and remains the best-known{{according to whom|date=January 2018}} recording of the song. The Nazareth single was so successful in Norway that it charted for 61 weeks on the Norwegian charts (VG-lista Top 10), including 14 weeks at No. 1, making it the top single of all time in that country.<ref name=norwaychart>{{cite web|url=http://norwegiancharts.com/bestall.asp |title=BEST OF ALL TIME \u2013 SINGLES |publisher=Hung Medien |work=[[VG-lista]] |accessdate=12 April 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141102064910/http://www.norwegiancharts.com//bestall.asp |archivedate=2 November 2014 }}</ref>\n\nA later recording by Nazareth, featuring the [[Munich Philharmonic Orchestra]], peaked at No. 89 in Germany.\n\nThe [[lyrics]] of the song remained unchanged on all [[cover version|versions]] up until Nazareth's [[Hair of the Dog (album)|1975 recording]], where the original line \"love is like a stove/it burns you when it's hot\" was changed to \"love is like a flame/it burns you when it's hot\".{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\n[[Cher]] covered this version for her 1991 album of the same name.\n\n=== Media ===\nThe song was used in an advertisement for [[Esurance]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ispot.tv/ad/wiU6/esurance-wont-last-long-song-by-nazareth|title=Esurance TV Commercial, 'The Pain Won't Last Long' Song By Nazareth|work=ispot.tv|accessdate=April 3, 2018}}</ref> and also in a series of advertisements by [[Zurich Insurance Group|Zurich]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.adsoftheworld.com/media/film/zurich_true_love_warmth|title=Zurich Film Advert By McCann: True Love, Warmth: Ads of the World\u2122|work=adsoftheworld.com|accessdate=October 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\nA cover was sung by [[Nan Vernon]] for the film ''[[Halloween II (2009 film)|Halloween II]]''.\n\nThe song has been featured in several video games, and films, including ''[[The Doors (film)|The Doors]]'', ''[[Spaceballs]]'', ''[[Wayne's World (film)|Wayne's World]]'', ''[[Josie and the Pussycats (film)|Josie and the Pussycats]]'', ''[[Sid and Nancy]]'', ''[[This Is Spinal Tap]]'', ''[[Airheads]]'', ''[[Bill & Ted's Excellent Adventure]]'', ''[[Dude, Where's My Car?]]'', ''[[Empire Records]]'', ''[[High Fidelity (film)|High Fidelity]]'', ''[[Dazed and Confused (film)|Dazed and Confused]]'', ''[[Rock Star (2001 film)|Rock Star]]'', ''[[The Rocker (film)|The Rocker]]'', ''[[The Full Monty]]'', ''[[Napoleon Dynamite]]'', ''[[Click (2006 film)|Click]]'', ''[[Monkeybone]]'', ''[[Idiocracy]]'', ''[[Speed (1994 film)|Speed]]'', ''[[Lethal Weapon 4]]'', ''[[Exit Wounds]]'', ''[[Mad Max: Fury Road]]'', ''[[Guitar Hero II]]'', ''[[Rock Band 3]]'', ''[[Barnyard (film)|Barnyard]]'', ''[[Flushed Away]]'', ''[[Detroit Rock City]]'', ''[[Chicken Little (2005 film)|Chicken Little]]'', and ''[[Toy Story 3]]''.\n\nThe song was featured in a dream sequence in Season 4, Episode 24 of \u201c[[That '70s Show]]\u201d, in which Fez daydreams that the characters Eric, Donna, Kelso and Jackie are performing the song after they hurt his feelings.\nAlso featured in the film Dazed and Confused during the junior high dance.{{citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\n=== Charts and certifications ===\n\n==== Weekly charts ====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1975\u201377)\n!align=\"left\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n|Australia ([[Kent Music Report]])<ref>{{cite book|last=Kent|first=David|authorlink=David Kent (historian)|title=Australian Chart Book 1970\u20131992|publisher=Australian Chart Book|location=St. Ives, N.S.W.|year=1993|edition=Illustrated|page=36|isbn=0-646-11917-6}} N.B. The Kent Report chart was authorized by [[Australian Recording Industry Association|ARIA]] from 1970 to 1988.</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|8\n|-\n{{single chart|Austria|11|artist=Nazareth|song=LOVE HURTS}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Flanders|1|artist=Nazareth|song=LOVE HURTS}}\n|-\n|Canada Top Singles ([[RPM (magazine)|''RPM'']])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.4088a&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.4088a.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.4088a|title=RPM - Library and Archives Canada - RPM - Biblioth\u00e8que et Archives Canada|work=collectionscanada.gc.ca|accessdate=October 24, 2019}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Denmark\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Euro Hit 50\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Germany ([[GfK Entertainment Charts|Official German Charts]])<ref>{{cite news|title=NAZARETH - LOVE HURTS (SONG)|url=http://swedishcharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Nazareth&titel=Love+Hurts&cat=s}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|30\n|-\n{{single chart|Dutch100|1|artist=Nazareth|song=LOVE HURTS}}\n|-\n{{single chart|New Zealand|4|artist=Nazareth|song=LOVE HURTS}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Norway|1|artist=Nazareth|song=LOVE HURTS}}\n|-\n|South Africa ([[Springbok Radio]])<ref>{{cite web|title=SA Charts 1965\u2013March 1989|url=http://www.rock.co.za/files/springbok_top_20_(N).html|accessdate=5 September 2018}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|-\n{{single chart|Sweden|6|artist=Nazareth|song=LOVE HURTS}}\n|-\n{{single chart|UK|41|artist=Nazareth|date=1977-09-24}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardhot100|8|artist=Nazareth|chartid=312074}}\n|}\n\n==== Year-end charts ====\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1975)\n!Rank\n|-\n|South African Singles Chart\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|-\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1976)\n!Rank\n|-\n|Australian Kent Music Report\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|45\n|-\n|Belgian ''BRT'' Top 30\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|10\n|-\n|Canadian ''RPM'' Top Singles\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|14\n|-\n|Dutch Top 40\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|-\n|U.S. ''Billboard'' Hot 100\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|23\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n==== All-time chart ====\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Chart\n!Rank\n|-\n|Norway<ref name=norwaychart />\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|}\n\n==== Certifications ====\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Canada|title=Love Hurts|type=single|award=Platinum|relyear=1976|salesamount=150,000}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United States|title=Love Hurts|type=single|award=Gold|relyear=1976|salesamount=500,000}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom|nosales=yes}}\n{{col-end}}\n\n== Cher version ==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Love Hurts\n| cover      = Cher Love Hurts single.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Cher]]\n| album      = [[Love Hurts (Cher album)|Love Hurts]]\n| B-side     = One Small Step\n| released   = 1991\n| format     =\n| recorded   = 1991\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Pop rock]]\n| length     = 4:07\n| label      = [[Geffen Records|Geffen]]\n| writer     = [[Boudleaux Bryant]]\n| producer   = [[Richie Zito]]\n| prev_title = [[Save Up All Your Tears#Cher version|Save Up All Your Tears]]\n| prev_year  = 1991\n| next_title = [[Could've Been You]]\n| next_year  = 1992\n| misc       = {{Audio sample\n | type = single\n | file = Cher - Love Hurts.ogg\n}}\n}}\n\n[[Cher]] recorded her first version in 1975 for the album ''[[Stars (Cher album)|Stars]]'', but did not release this version as a single. She later recorded a second version in 1991 for her [[Love Hurts (Cher album)|album of the same name]]. This version was a cover of Nazareth's version. The single became a minor hit in the UK in December 1991.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Chart (1991)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Denmark|8|artist=Cher|song=Walking in Memphis|accessdate=October 29, 2015}}\n|-\n|Poland ([[Lista Przeboj\u00f3w Programu Trzeciego|LP3]])<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://lp3.polskieradio.pl/notowania/?numer=523|title=Notowanie nr523|publisher=[[Lista Przeboj\u00f3w Programu Trzeciego|LP3]]|language=Polish|date=February 28, 1992|accessdate=February 28, 2019}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|21\n|-\n{{singlechart|UKsinglesbyname|43|artist=Cher|accessdate=October 28, 2015}}\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Live performances ===\nCher performed the song on the following concert tours:\n* [[Heart of Stone Tour]] (performed towards the end of the tour in Australia only, before her studio recording)\n* [[Love Hurts Tour]]\n* [[Living Proof: The Farewell Tour|The Farewell Tour]] (sung on the fifth, sixth, seventh, eighth and ninth legs of the tour, then replaced with \"[[The Way of Love]]\" on the last two shows of the tour)\n* [[Cher at the Colosseum]] (sung on the first night, then re-added during the third leg in place of \"[[The Way of Love]]\")\n\n==See also==\n*[[List_of_one-hit_wonders_in_the_United_States#1970s|List of 1970s one-hit wonders in the United States]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|everly-brothers|love-hurts}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Nazareth}}\n{{Cher (navbox)}}\n{{Cher songs part 1}}\n\n[[Category:1960 songs]]\n[[Category:1960s ballads]]\n[[Category:1975 singles]]\n[[Category:1976 singles]]\n[[Category:1991 singles]]\n[[Category:2001 singles]]\n[[Category:2005 singles]]\n[[Category:Nazareth (band) songs]]\n[[Category:The Everly Brothers songs]]\n[[Category:Roy Orbison songs]]\n[[Category:Cher songs]]\n[[Category:Rod Stewart songs]]\n[[Category:Jim Capaldi songs]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Norway]]\n[[Category:RPM Top Singles number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Single Top 100 number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in South Africa]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Richie Zito]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Felice and Boudleaux Bryant]]\n[[Category:Torch songs]]\n[[Category:Hard rock ballads]]\n[[Category:Warner Records singles]]\n[[Category:Monument Records singles]]\n[[Category:A&M Records singles]]\n[[Category:Vertigo Records singles]]\n[[Category:Mooncrest Records singles]]\n[[Category:Island Records singles]]\n[[Category:Geffen Records singles]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Single by Everly Brothers}}\n{{About|the song written by Boudleaux Bryant}}\n{{More citations needed|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name     = Love Hurts\n| cover    =\n| alt      =\n| type     =\n| artist   = [[The Everly Brothers]]\n| album    = [[A Date with The Everly Brothers]]\n| released = 1961\n| format   =\n| recorded = July 1960\n| studio   =\n| venue    =\n| genre    = [[Country music|Country]]\n| length   = 2:22\n| label    = [[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]]\n| writer   = [[Felice and Boudleaux Bryant|Boudleaux Bryant]]\n| producer =\n}}\n\n\"'''Love Hurts'''\" is a song written and composed by the American songwriter [[Boudleaux Bryant]]. First recorded by [[the Everly Brothers]] in July 1960, the song is also well known from a 1975 international hit version by the Scottish [[hard rock]] band [[Nazareth (band)|Nazareth]] and in the [[United Kingdom|UK]] a top five hit in 1975 by the English singer [[Jim Capaldi]].\n\n==Appearances==\nThe song was introduced in December 1960 as an album track on ''[[A Date with The Everly Brothers]]'', but was never released as a single (A-side or B-side) by the Everlys. The first hit version of the song was by [[Roy Orbison]], who earned Australian radio play, hitting the Top Five of that country's singles charts in 1961. A recording by [[Emmylou Harris]] and [[Gram Parsons]] was included on Parsons' posthumously released ''[[Grievous Angel]]'' album. After Parsons' 1973 death, Harris made the song a staple of her repertoire, and has included it in her concert set lists from the 1970s to the present. Harris has since re-recorded the song twice. [[Jennifer Warnes]] released a version on her self-titled album in 1976.\n\nThe most successful recording of the song was by [[hard rock]] band [[Nazareth (band)|Nazareth]], who took the song to the U.S. Top 10 in 1975 and hit number one in Norway and the Netherlands.\nIn the UK the most successful version of the song was by former [[Traffic (band)|Traffic]] member Jim Capaldi, who took it to number four in the charts in November 1975 during an 11-week run.\nThe song was also covered by [[Cher]] in 1975 for her album ''Stars''. Cher re-recorded the song in 1991 for her album of the same name.\n[[Joan Jett]] included a version of the song on her 1990 album, [[The Hit List (Joan Jett album)|The Hit List]], a covers compilation.\n[[Rod Stewart]] recorded the song in 2006 for his album ''[[Still the Same... Great Rock Classics of Our Time]]'' which was No. 1 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart.\n\nThe [[Bluegrass music|bluegrass]] version appearing in both the ''[[Deadpool 2]]'' \"Super Duper Cut\" and the \"Once Upon A Deadpool\" DVD, during the montages featuring the [[Deadpool|titular character]]'s failed suicide attempts following [[Copycat (comics)|Vanessa]]'s death, was first recorded by [[The Osborne Brothers]] for their 1977 Release \"From Rocky Top To Muddy Bottom: The Songs Of Boudleaux & Felice Bryant\".<ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt5463162/soundtrack?ref_=tt_trv_snd</ref>\n\nJazz guitarist [[Julian Lage]] performs the song on his 2019 [[Love Hurts (Julian Lage album)|album of the same name]].\n\n== Roy Orbison version ==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Love Hurts\n| cover      = RoyOrbisonRunningScared.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Roy Orbison]]\n| album      =\n| A-side     = [[Running Scared (Roy Orbison song)|Running Scared]]\n| released   = 1961\n| format     = [[7-inch single]]\n| recorded   = 1961\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Pop music|Pop]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=2|s=26}}\n| label      = [[Monument Records|Monument]]\n| writer     = [[Boudleaux Bryant]]\n| producer   =\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n[[Roy Orbison]] covered \"Love Hurts\" in 1961 and issued it as the B-side to \"[[Running Scared (Roy Orbison song)|Running Scared]].\" While \"Running Scared\" was an international hit, the B-side only picked up significant airplay in Australia. Consequently, chart figures for Australia show \"Running Scared\"/\"Love Hurts\" as a double A-Side, both sides peaking at No. 5. This makes Orbison's recording of \"Love Hurts\" the first version to be a hit.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1961)\n!align=\"left\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Australia\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|5\n|}\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== Jim Capaldi version ==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Love Hurts\n| cover      = Jim Capaldi Love Hurts.png\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Jim Capaldi]]\n| album      = [[Short Cut Draw Blood]]\n| B-side     = Sugar Honey\n| released   = {{Start date|1975}}\n| format     = [[7-inch single]]\n| recorded   = 1975\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Pop music|Pop]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=3|s=29}}\n| label      = [[Island Records|Island]]\n| writer     = [[Boudleaux Bryant]]\n| producer   = Steve Smith\n| prev_title = [[It's All Up to You]]\n| prev_year  = 1974\n| next_title = Goodbye Love\n| next_year  = 1976\n}}\n[[Jim Capaldi]] reached number 4 in the UK charts with his interpretation of \"Love Hurts\" in November 1975, which was to prove his highest charting UK single.<ref>[http://www.theofficialcharts.com/artist/_/jim%20capaldi/ Jim Capaldi in the UK charts] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120912114305/http://www.theofficialcharts.com/artist/_/jim%20capaldi/ |date=2012-09-12 }}, The Official Charts. Retrieved August 11, 2011.</ref> Described by ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' as having \"a sense of pain very different from Roy Orbison's.\"<ref>Marsh, Dave (11 March 1976). {{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/artists/jimcapaldi/albums/album/116873/review/5943052/short_cut_draw_blood |title=Album review |accessdate=2011-08-12 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090430135807/http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/jimcapaldi/albums/album/116873/review/5943052/short_cut_draw_blood |archivedate=April 30, 2009 }}, ''Rolling Stone''.</ref> the single also charted in the US,<ref>[http://www.allmusic.com/artist/jim-capaldi-p3832/charts-awards Jim Capaldi in the Billboard charts], Allmusic. Retrieved August 11, 2011.</ref> Germany,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.musicline.de/de/chartverfolgung_summary/artist/Jim+Capaldi/3979/single |title=Chartverfolgung / Jim Capaldi / Single |work=Music Line | publisher=[[Media Control Charts]] |location=[[Germany]] |language=German |accessdate=28 September 2011}}</ref> and Sweden.<ref>[http://swedishcharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Jim+Capaldi&titel=Love+Hurts&cat=s \"Love Hurts\" in the Swedish charts], swedishcharts.com. Retrieved August 12, 2011.</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1975\u201376)\n!align=\"left\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n|Australia ([[Kent Music Report]])<ref>{{cite book|first= David |last= Kent |authorlink= David Kent (historian) |title= [[Kent Music Report|Australian Chart Book 1970-1992]] |publisher= Australian Chart Book |location= [[St Ives, New South Wales|St Ives]], N.S.W. |year= 1993 |isbn= 0-646-11917-6}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|6\n|-\n|Canada ''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'' Top Singles<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.4096a&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.4096a.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.4096a|title=Item Display - RPM - Library and Archives Canada |website=Collectionscanada.gc.ca |date=1976-04-03 |accessdate=2019-03-31}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|15\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Germany\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|42\n|-\n|{{singlechart|Ireland2|8|song=Love Hurts|accessdate=November 1, 2018}}\n|-\n|South Africa ([[Springbok Radio|Springbok]])<ref>{{cite web|title=SA Charts 1965\u2013March 1989|url=http://www.rock.co.za/files/springbok_top_20_(C).html|accessdate=5 September 2018}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|13\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Sweden\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|16\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|UK \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|4\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|U.S.\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|97\n|}\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== Nazareth version ==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Love Hurts\n| cover      = Nazareth Love Hurts.png\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Nazareth (band)|Nazareth]]\n| album      = [[Hair of the Dog (album)|Hair of the Dog]]\n| B-side     = {{ubl|\"Down\" (non-U.S.)|\"[[Hair of the Dog (song)|Hair of the Dog]]\" (U.S.)}}\n| released   = {{Start date|1974}}\n| format     = [[7-inch single]]\n| recorded   = 1974\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Blues rock]]|[[hard rock]]<ref>{{cite book|author=Phil Hardy|title=The Da Capo Companion to 20th-century Popular Music|year=1995|publisher=Da Capo Press|isbn=978-0-306-80640-7|page=123}}</ref>}}\n| length     = {{Duration|m=3|s=53}}<br>{{Duration|m=3|s=03}} (U.S. single)\n| label      = [[Vertigo Records|Vertigo]]\n| writer     = [[Felice and Boudleaux Bryant|Boudleaux Bryant]]\n| producer   = [[Manny Charlton]]\n| prev_title = [[This Flight Tonight]]\n| prev_year  = 1973\n| next_title = Shanghai'd in Shanghai\n| next_year  = 1974\n}}\nPerformed as a [[power ballad]],<ref name=\"LLC1995\">{{cite book|author=SPIN Media LLC|title=SPIN|date=June 1995|publisher=SPIN Media LLC|pages=104\u2013|issn=0886-3032}}</ref> the Nazareth version is the most popular version of the song and the only rendition of \"Love Hurts\" to become a [[hit single]] in the United States, reaching No. 8 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] in early 1976. ''Billboard'' ranked it as the No. 23 song for 1976.<ref>[[Billboard Year-End Hot 100 singles of 1976]]</ref> As part of the \"Hot Tracks (EP)\" it also reached No. 41 in the UK in 1977.<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\">{{cite book\n| first= David\n| last= Roberts\n| year= 2006\n| title= British Hit Singles & Albums\n| edition= 19th\n| publisher= Guinness World Records Limited\n| location= London\n| isbn= 1-904994-10-5\n| page= 388}}</ref> Nazareth's version was an international hit, peaking at No. 1 in Canada, the Netherlands, Belgium, South Africa and Norway, and remains the best-known{{according to whom|date=January 2018}} recording of the song. The Nazareth single was so successful in Norway that it charted for 61 weeks on the Norwegian charts (VG-lista Top 10), including 14 weeks at No. 1, making it the top single of all time in that country.<ref name=norwaychart>{{cite web|url=http://norwegiancharts.com/bestall.asp |title=BEST OF ALL TIME \u2013 SINGLES |publisher=Hung Medien |work=[[VG-lista]] |accessdate=12 April 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141102064910/http://www.norwegiancharts.com//bestall.asp |archivedate=2 November 2014 }}</ref>\n\nA later recording by Nazareth, featuring the [[Munich Philharmonic Orchestra]], peaked at No. 89 in Germany.\n\nThe [[lyrics]] of the song remained unchanged on all [[cover version|versions]] up until Nazareth's [[Hair of the Dog (album)|1975 recording]], where the original line \"love is like a stove/it burns you when it's hot\" was changed to \"love is like a flame/it burns you when it's hot\".{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\n[[Cher]] covered this version for her 1991 album of the same name.\n\n=== Media ===\nThe song was used in an advertisement for [[Esurance]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ispot.tv/ad/wiU6/esurance-wont-last-long-song-by-nazareth|title=Esurance TV Commercial, 'The Pain Won't Last Long' Song By Nazareth|work=ispot.tv|accessdate=April 3, 2018}}</ref> and also in a series of advertisements by [[Zurich Insurance Group|Zurich]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.adsoftheworld.com/media/film/zurich_true_love_warmth|title=Zurich Film Advert By McCann: True Love, Warmth: Ads of the World\u2122|work=adsoftheworld.com|accessdate=October 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\nA cover was sung by [[Nan Vernon]] for the film ''[[Halloween II (2009 film)|Halloween II]]''.\n\nThe song has been featured in several video games, and films, including ''[[The Doors (film)|The Doors]]'', ''[[Spaceballs]]'', ''[[Wayne's World (film)|Wayne's World]]'', ''[[Josie and the Pussycats (film)|Josie and the Pussycats]]'', ''[[Sid and Nancy]]'', ''[[This Is Spinal Tap]]'', ''[[Airheads]]'', ''[[Bill & Ted's Excellent Adventure]]'', ''[[Dude, Where's My Car?]]'', ''[[Empire Records]]'', ''[[High Fidelity (film)|High Fidelity]]'', ''[[Dazed and Confused (film)|Dazed and Confused]]'', ''[[Rock Star (2001 film)|Rock Star]]'', ''[[The Rocker (film)|The Rocker]]'', ''[[The Full Monty]]'', ''[[Napoleon Dynamite]]'', ''[[Click (2006 film)|Click]]'', ''[[Monkeybone]]'', ''[[Idiocracy]]'', ''[[Speed (1994 film)|Speed]]'', ''[[Lethal Weapon 4]]'', ''[[Exit Wounds]]'', ''[[Mad Max: Fury Road]]'', ''[[Guitar Hero II]]'', ''[[Rock Band 3]]'', ''[[Barnyard (film)|Barnyard]]'', ''[[Flushed Away]]'', ''[[Detroit Rock City]]'', ''[[Chicken Little (2005 film)|Chicken Little]]'', and ''[[Toy Story 3]]''.\n\nThe song was featured in a dream sequence in Season 4, Episode 24 of \u201c[[That '70s Show]]\u201d, in which Fez daydreams that the characters Eric, Donna, Kelso and Jackie are performing the song after they hurt his feelings.\nAlso featured in the film Dazed and Confused during the junior high dance.{{citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\n=== Charts and certifications ===\n\n==== Weekly charts ====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1975\u201377)\n!align=\"left\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n|Australia ([[Kent Music Report]])<ref>{{cite book|last=Kent|first=David|authorlink=David Kent (historian)|title=Australian Chart Book 1970\u20131992|publisher=Australian Chart Book|location=St. Ives, N.S.W.|year=1993|edition=Illustrated|page=36|isbn=0-646-11917-6}} N.B. The Kent Report chart was authorized by [[Australian Recording Industry Association|ARIA]] from 1970 to 1988.</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|8\n|-\n{{single chart|Austria|11|artist=Nazareth|song=LOVE HURTS}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Flanders|1|artist=Nazareth|song=LOVE HURTS}}\n|-\n|Canada ([[RPM (magazine)|''RPM'']])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.4088a&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.4088a.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.4088a|title=RPM - Library and Archives Canada - RPM - Biblioth\u00e8que et Archives Canada|work=collectionscanada.gc.ca|accessdate=October 24, 2019}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Denmark\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Euro Hit 50\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Germany ([[GfK Entertainment Charts|Official German Charts]])<ref>{{cite news|title=NAZARETH - LOVE HURTS (SONG)|url=http://swedishcharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Nazareth&titel=Love+Hurts&cat=s}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|30\n|-\n{{single chart|Dutch100|1|artist=Nazareth|song=LOVE HURTS}}\n|-\n{{single chart|New Zealand|4|artist=Nazareth|song=LOVE HURTS}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Norway|1|artist=Nazareth|song=LOVE HURTS}}\n|-\n|South Africa ([[Springbok Radio]])<ref>{{cite web|title=SA Charts 1965\u2013March 1989|url=http://www.rock.co.za/files/springbok_top_20_(N).html|accessdate=5 September 2018}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|-\n{{single chart|Sweden|6|artist=Nazareth|song=LOVE HURTS}}\n|-\n{{single chart|UK|41|artist=Nazareth|date=1977-09-24}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardhot100|8|artist=Nazareth|chartid=312074}}\n|}\n\n==== Year-end charts ====\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1975)\n!Rank\n|-\n|South African Singles Chart\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|-\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1976)\n!Rank\n|-\n|Australian Kent Music Report\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|45\n|-\n|Belgian ''BRT'' Top 30\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|10\n|-\n|Canadian ''RPM'' Top Singles\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|14\n|-\n|Dutch Top 40\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|-\n|U.S. ''Billboard'' Hot 100\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|23\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n==== All-time chart ====\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Chart\n!Rank\n|-\n|Norway<ref name=norwaychart />\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|}\n\n==== Certifications ====\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Canada|title=Love Hurts|type=single|award=Platinum|relyear=1976|salesamount=150,000}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United States|title=Love Hurts|type=single|award=Gold|relyear=1976|salesamount=500,000}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom|nosales=yes}}\n{{col-end}}\n\n== Cher version ==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Love Hurts\n| cover      = Cher Love Hurts single.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Cher]]\n| album      = [[Love Hurts (Cher album)|Love Hurts]]\n| B-side     = One Small Step\n| released   = 1991\n| format     =\n| recorded   = 1991\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Pop rock]]\n| length     = 4:07\n| label      = [[Geffen Records|Geffen]]\n| writer     = [[Boudleaux Bryant]]\n| producer   = [[Richie Zito]]\n| prev_title = [[Save Up All Your Tears#Cher version|Save Up All Your Tears]]\n| prev_year  = 1991\n| next_title = [[Could've Been You]]\n| next_year  = 1992\n| misc       = {{Audio sample\n | type = single\n | file = Cher - Love Hurts.ogg\n}}\n}}\n\n[[Cher]] recorded her first version in 1975 for the album ''[[Stars (Cher album)|Stars]]'', but did not release this version as a single. She later recorded a second version in 1991 for her [[Love Hurts (Cher album)|album of the same name]]. This version was a cover of Nazareth's version. The single became a minor hit in the UK in December 1991.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Chart (1991)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Denmark|8|artist=Cher|song=Walking in Memphis|accessdate=October 29, 2015}}\n|-\n|Poland ([[Lista Przeboj\u00f3w Programu Trzeciego|LP3]])<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://lp3.polskieradio.pl/notowania/?numer=523|title=Notowanie nr523|publisher=[[Lista Przeboj\u00f3w Programu Trzeciego|LP3]]|language=Polish|date=February 28, 1992|accessdate=February 28, 2019}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|21\n|-\n{{singlechart|UKsinglesbyname|43|artist=Cher|accessdate=October 28, 2015}}\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Live performances ===\nCher performed the song on the following concert tours:\n* [[Heart of Stone Tour]] (performed towards the end of the tour in Australia only, before her studio recording)\n* [[Love Hurts Tour]]\n* [[Living Proof: The Farewell Tour|The Farewell Tour]] (sung on the fifth, sixth, seventh, eighth and ninth legs of the tour, then replaced with \"[[The Way of Love]]\" on the last two shows of the tour)\n* [[Cher at the Colosseum]] (sung on the first night, then re-added during the third leg in place of \"[[The Way of Love]]\")\n\n==See also==\n*[[List_of_one-hit_wonders_in_the_United_States#1970s|List of 1970s one-hit wonders in the United States]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|everly-brothers|love-hurts}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Nazareth}}\n{{Cher (navbox)}}\n{{Cher songs part 1}}\n\n[[Category:1960 songs]]\n[[Category:1960s ballads]]\n[[Category:1975 singles]]\n[[Category:1976 singles]]\n[[Category:1991 singles]]\n[[Category:2001 singles]]\n[[Category:2005 singles]]\n[[Category:Nazareth (band) songs]]\n[[Category:The Everly Brothers songs]]\n[[Category:Roy Orbison songs]]\n[[Category:Cher songs]]\n[[Category:Rod Stewart songs]]\n[[Category:Jim Capaldi son